Date:         Wed, 10 May 89 11:43:21 EDT
From:         Mike Hojnowski <MQH@CORNELLC.cit.cornell.edu>
Subject:      Membership and Attendence

Good Gentles, Mistress Niccola Sebastiani has been following the discussions
of the Pennsic War on "The Geeknet", as she calls it.  She had the following
to add to the discussion... Orlando
---
Aside from the question of how the space allocation at the War is going
to run this year, it is time to discuss *who* it is who comes to Pennsic.
Here is the monolog I heard in my game store last week:
"You know what I'm doing this summer? I'm going to the war. It's
down in Pennsylvania. You know, it's a Sca thing. And they fight
with swords and everything. My brother- he isn't really in Sca-
he's going and he's going to take me."

The speaker was a young woman whom I know not to be a member of our local
group and whom I judge by her conversation not to be a member of any
group. I'd just as soon she didn't come to Pennsic. She's going to take
up space and water and time in lines for registration and to get ice
cream and to go to the bathroom. If she's unlucky or stupid she's going
to take up the attention and supplies of our chirurgeonate when she gets
heatstroke or hypothermia or a broken ankle or one of the other
afflictions we deal with at the War. And do you know what she's likely to
contribute to the War to repay us? Five bucks to a dubious "improvements"
fund, the even more dubious pleasure of seeing all too much of her
breasts above a "folk" costume, and free sex for how ever many of us
she's willing to accomodate.

Now, Pennsic is a great place for party time. No one denies it. Everyone
goes to party, one way or another (though some of us party by hitting
each other with sticks and some by talking armor nonstop for five days
and so on). All I want is for Pennsic to be a party *for the SCA*.

There are lots of times when it is appropriate to introduce new people to
the SCA. Local meetings. Fighting practices. Pleasant, laid-back events
where people have time to introduce them around and explain things to
them. We are pleased to meet people new to the SCA and to show them a
good time at these events.

There are also times when you do new people a disservice by taking them
to an event. Events where there is a lot of business, both personal and
official, to get done. Events where people are tired and disinclined to
strike up a conversation with someone neither they nor their friends
know. Events where people have travelled a long way and are anxious to
deal with their friends from far away. Events which are too large for a
couple of people to oversee. Events where unusual activities take place,
activities not characteristic of the usual run of SCA events. Crown
Tournaments. Coronations. The Pennsic War.

People who are very new SCAjuns should not be encouraged to go to those
events. People who are not in the SCA and who do not contemplate joining
should be excluded. I do not care if that means the Tuchux and the
merchants from Ren Fairs and MSR and all kinds of groovy guys from SF&F
conventions and gaming cons and LARPG, much as I enjoy their company
elsewhere. The SCA is not a charitable organization which runs a summer
camp for those folks who are not able to avail themselves of the
pleasures of the SCA year round because they're busy playing some other
game. The Masons do not invite miscellaneous Rotarians to their
conventions.

How do you tell if somebody's in the SCA? Easy. They have a membership
card. Or a TI. Or a kingdom newsletter. Or someone who is identifiable as
a member tells you he saw that person put his subscription check in the
mail. *They are paid members.* I'm willing to give people all kinds of
leeway. I'm willing for them to have $6 memberships. I'm willing for
their memberships to have expired within the previous year. I'm willing
to have minors come in with their parents, even if their parents haven't
bought a family membership. I'm willing to be imposed upon periodically
by jerks who abuse the system. But I would like to have the SCA have a
clear idea that it is a club with members who run dinners and conventions
for each other (even though we call them "events"). We are not a
travelling circus for strangers to gawk at. We are not a travelling
brothel for strangers to take advantage of for a price. Let us make our
large events OUR events and take reasonable steps to ensure that they are
restricted to our members.

