Date: 10 May 89 16:44:17 GMT
From: unmvax!ncar!tank!fac_ddf@gsbacd.uchicago.edu
Subject: Contests, cooking, names
Message-Id: <3159@tank.uchicago.edu>

Competitions:     Awilda Halfdane raises the question of whether A&S
competitions are a good idea, and suggests the alternative of something
modelled on a state fair, with almost everyone getting some sort of
ribbon. I was persuaded many years ago that competitions are generally a
bad idea (although if anything could change my mind, it would be Niccola's
creative approach to using contests to bully people into doing things
right); my reasons are given in some detail in the article "Concerning
Contests" in the Miscellany; if there is sufficient interest I could post
the whole article, which is a little over two pages. 

One addition I would make to Awilda's suggestion is to push it a little
farther back. I believe, although I am not certain, that our state fairs
are descendants of the medieval fairs. At medieval fairs, as I understand
it, merchants and craftsmen came to sell their goods; blue ribbons and the
like originated as an endorsement by some local authority (the people
running the fair? the lord in whose land it was held? I do not know enough
of the relevant history) of a particular merchant or craftsman's work. We
could make our fairs feel much more medieval by adopting that framework.
People who wanted to display their work but did not actually want to sell
it could explain that they had nothing for sale at the moment, but were
displaying in the hope of future business. 

Cooking: Looking at the recent Rolls Ethereal (from which I seem somehow
to have been omitted), there seem to be a lot of cooks on the net, so I
thought I would mention a few things of interest to medieval cooks. 

The first is that I have found verjuice. As you probably know, it is a
common period ingredient, generally described as a sour juice from unripe
grapes, crabapples, etc.; there is also green verjuice made from sorrel. I
was in a middle-eastern grocery store looking for something else when I
came across a jar labelled "sour grape juice." I have not yet cooked with
it, but I have tasted it, and it seems to fit the description.

The second is that I have found Dibs--in fact, it was what I was looking
for when I found the verjuice. Dibs is mentioned in ibn al-Mubarad (15th
c.) as an alternative to sugar or honey for making Hulwah (sweets). It
turns out that it is date syrup, and can still be found in middle-eastern
groceries.

The third is that the Miscellany and both volumes of the cookbook
collection are currently available from me. I will have them at Pennsic,
and am willing but not eager to sell them by mail--with the warning that
neither I nor Elizabeth is very well organized, which is one reason for
the "not eager" part. For more information, contact me via EMail.

Names:   With all the recent discussion about registering names, I thought
people might be interested in my my recent experience. When I originated
my persona I was loosely basing it on a Muslim character in one of the
Chansons de Geste (Carahue of Mauretania in Ogier le Danois). I somehow
got the impression that Cariadoc was a variant of Carahue--I have no idea
how. Later, when I started trying to do things more carefully, I came to
the conclusion that "Carahue" was probably not based on any arabic
original, but on similar celtic names--it was simply an attempt at
something a little exotic sounding for a foreign character.   So I asked a
friend who was a professional linguist if he could find me a plausible
arabic name that could have been corrupted into "Cariadoc" by european
speakers, just as Abu Ali ibn Sina became Avicenna to Europeans, or Salah
ad-din became Saladin. He found one, with the assistance of an Arabist
friend of his, and published it, with a delightful frame story explaining
how he had "discovered" what my real name was, in TI many years ago.

None of this presented any difficulty for me with the heralds, since I am
in any sense grandfathered--I registered my arms long before the heralds
started worrying about names. The problem arose when my son wished to
register his device and name--the latter being Patri ibn Cariadoc. The
Middle Kingdom heralds sent the submission back with a small
alteration--it was changed to Patri ap Cariadoc, on the grounds that
Cariadoc was obviously a Welsh name and the Welsh for "son of" was ap not
ibn (which is arabic for "son of.")

It is worth noting that several of the heralds involved know me, and one
of the things obvious to everyone who knows me in the society is that my
persona is Muslim. The heralds seem either to believe that if I have what
sounds like a Welsh name then I am Welsh, whether or not I wear a turban,
or else that what they are making consistent is the name not the persona.
I provided the reference to the TI piece on my name--and they changed my
son's submission to Patri son of Cariadoc. 

This raises a fairly obvious problem for the system of naming. On the one
hand, the heralds would, reasonably enough, like the name to be
historically consistent. On the other hand, what are they to do with
anomalies that could have happened in the real Middle Ages and do happen
in the current Middle Ages? A medieval Muslim certainly could have named a
son after a Christian friend, giving "Patri ibn Cariadoc."  I in fact did
name my son after a friend--Patri is both the mundane and society name of
both my son and his namesake.

The obvious solution for us, and the one I expect Patri will probably
take, is to register as "son of" and introduce himself as "ibn." But
although that evades the problem for us, it does not really solve it in
general.

One further point on the subject of nameing. A number of people have
suggested retaliating against unreasonable restrictions on names by
adopting names that are absurd but legal. The problem with this is that
you are retaliating against the wrong people. Silly names, or names that
sound out of period (even if they are not), make events less real, harder
to believe in as really medieval, for the other participants--it is they
and not the heralds who are being hurt by the retaliation.

Since I seem to have gotten left out of the current rolls ethereal, here
is the information that should have been there:

