Date: Wed, 10 May 89 13:47:44 edt
From: chanson%lucy.wellesley.edu@RELAY.CS.NET
Subject: A modest proposal

What to do about the annual Pennsic land rush, especially the lack of space
left for those who only come a week early?  Why not (warning: rhetorical
question) greatly enlarge the space reserved traditionally for the royal
camps?  That way, the kings can grant camping space in a good location to
fighters who promise to fight for them all war.  Think of the advantages
of the system: 

- it put someone explicity in charge of the space problem, something only
being done for the first time this year, really, and that someone is not
the War Autocrat; saving that worthy another headache;

- it gives the royalty more real power (which is of course what they all
crave :-)), but with it some real responsibility (which they don't have
enough of :-) :-)) as the king can't pass out more space than he has;

- it provides a subtle mechanism to balance the sides at Pennsic, which
makes everything more fun (except the bridge battle), since fighters who
show up later will have to fight for the previously less popular side 
(which has no space left)

- it now makes more difference which kingdom you consider yourself a 
subject of;

- best of all, *it's period!!!*  So what if each advantage listed above
has a down side, has inherent problems?  Kings who need more land to
reward their vassals, divided allegiances, mercenaries who sell their
swords to the highest bidder in land (not just chocolate chip cookies)
- so what, I say, they're period problems!  We're enhancing the quality
of our recreation by bringing back the feudal system.

Actually, as far as the question of multiple fealty goes (this is a
signal that I'm moving from the facetious-but-original part to the
serious-commentary-on-what's-already-been-said part), by the height
of the feudal system, say mid-13th to 14th centuries, it was fairly
accepted practice to swear fealty to more than one lord.  Not necessarily
standard, and the various lords may not have been too happy about it,
but as long as you made your priorities clear in your oath, and made
it clear which lord got what from you in exchange for what, it was
accepted.  (William de Corbie mentioned Enguerrand de Coucy; I will
look up other examples if the discussion continues.)

I did some productive research on the origin of the Order of the
Garter, but then my connection to the net broke down for 2-3 weeks
and by the time I got back on (i.e. now) the discussion is over.
If anyone cares, I e-mail it to you direct.  And if anyone brings
it up again on the Rialto, I'll report here as well.

And as far as speaking treason, remember the earlier exchange in
_Captain Blood_, also between Olivia de Havilland and Errol Flynn:

"Sir, you speak treason!"

"I trust I do not make myself obscure."

