Date: Thu 11 May 89 00:24:08
From: "]ke Eldberg" <CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>
Subject: Banishment
Message-Id: <890511002408.18.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>

Mundane crimes should be punished by mundane authorities. A rapist or a
child abuser should be reported to the police. But then, the SCA also needs 
some sort of internal justice, concerning membership and attendance at SCA
events. Nothing (short of a long prison sentence) stops a convicted rapist
or child abuser from attending SCA events. The BOD can refuse membership,
but that doesn't stop bad people from attending events. So it seems that
banishment is just about the most powerful tool we have, to get rid of
really bad people.

The only problem I can see with it is that it is not preceeded by any sort 
of trial. It's simply a royal command. This opens up possibilities for 
misuse, e.g. that the king can banish his personal enemies as he sees fit,
wether guilty of crimes period or mundane at all. 

We need to decide wether banishment should be a tool to get rid of bad
people, or wether it should be a less serious, in-period, in-persona thing
by which the king could punish someone for bad behavior strictly within
the SCA system. 

With the very liberal rules for who is allowed to attend events, we need a
powerful tool to keep 1st class assholes away. At the same time, it's nice 
to let kings have the opportunity to rid themselves of persons they find
obnoxious during their reign. It's very period.

I would like to see two kinds of banishment: one in-persona and one mundane.
The in-persona banishment would then be the privilege of the king, to get
rid of personas who have behaved unchivalrously, etcetera, all within the
period setting of the SCA. This would then mean that the person in question
might still attend events, but under a different persona. S/he would lose
any offices held. Mundane banishment on the other hand, would affect the
mundane person and ban him/her from attending events in the kingdom. This
should be decided by a court of chivalry, nothing less.

This spontaneous reaction comes from your friendly neighborhood Norman,
William de Corbie
