Date: 10 May 89 21:20:21 GMT
From: uxc!tank!fac_ddf@deimos.cis.ksu.edu
Subject: Membership requirements and new people at Pennsic
Message-Id: <3163@tank.uchicago.edu>

Mistress Niccola raises some legitimate questions in her recent postings,
but I think I disagree with almost all of her conclusions:

1. I agree that Pennsic, and other events, might be more fun if one could
exclude the people who only come to party and have no interest in the
Middle Ages. It seems to me that requiring membership would be a very poor
filter for that purpose--lots of members have no real interest in the
Society (and don't help with heralding, chirurgeoning, troll booth, etc.)
and some non-members do have such an interest. I am not sure that
requiring someone to be vouched for by a member would do much better--I
doubt the lady Niccola describes would have much trouble passing that
hurdle.

A better approach, where possible, is to get people to self-select, by
designing an event that will appeal more to the people you want to come
than to those you do not want to come. Our local group recently ran an
event designed to be low-key but considerably more medieval than events
usually are. We made that clear by the announcement and the seneschal's
flyer. So far as I know, not a single person complained about the lack of
silly contests, not having an elimination list, the pressure to keep
mundane things out of sight, or anything related. I presume one reason is
that those who would have complained did not come. Applying the same
principle to Pennsic is a more difficult problem. My present solution is
self-selection within Pennsic--an in persona encampment where anyone is
welcome who wants to play by the same rules we want to play by.

In general, I think the idea of requiring membership for things is a very
bad one. It confuses the SCA Inc., which is a California corporation, with
the Society, which is a social network of people with common interests.
Someone who has not sent his $20 to the Registrar has not contributed to
the Corporation, but he may have contributed far more to the Society than
someone who pays his membership and comes to events in the belief that he
is now an audience and it is someone else's business to entertain him. 

To require membership for participation is, in effect, to say that the
Board of Directors owns the game and the rest of us must pay them for the
privelege of playing. But the Society was not built by the Corporation
(although the Corporation has certainly played an important role in the
process). It was built by the combined efforts of thousands of
participants over twenty-some years. 

For a longer diatribe on this subject, see "A Letter" in the current (4th)
edition of the Miscelleny.

Mistress Niccola also argues that the war is a bad event to bring new
people to. I disagree. The war is the SCA on a large scale; for some new
people that may be frightening, for others fascinating. 

Vissivald, who is visiting with me at the moment, cites his own "wargamer"
story to balance Niccola's. Vis went into a war-game shop and asked if
anyone was interested in trying medieval tactical. Someone was, so a few
weeks later Vis carried him off to Pennsic IV. The gentleman is still in
the Society. Note, by the way, that Vis's story happened--in Niccola's,
the overheard conversation is real but the rest is conjecture.

Etienne d'Argent writes "But, basically, new people are "FUN", they do new
things, they have enthusiasm, they aren't stuck in the same-old-rut." I
would add that I think it is often easier to get new people to "do it
right" (by my standards of what the Society should be) than old people. To
the new people, wearing costumes and fighting with swords is magical, so,
with only a little effort, they can be persuaded to feel and act as if
they are really in the Middle Ages. For old people, dressing up in
medieval clothes and hitting each other with sticks is what they always do
on weekends--why should they feel (or talk, or act) any different than at
other times?

David Friedman (Cariadoc)
College of Grey Gargoyles, Middle Kingdom
Chicago, IL  FAC_DDF@gsbacd.uchicago.edu (Internet)
FAC_DDF@gsbacd.uchicago (bitnet)

