Why do we need to put an end to people arriving earlier and earlier?  Why
should be not establish a permanet site for Pennsic?  

The problem with people arriving earlier than other people is that they hog
space by roping off areas for people who might be coming, but who do not show
up.  This deprives late comers of space to camp in.  

And I like the idea of a pemanent Pennsic site.  I dream of a site that has
adequate showers, reliable hot water, flush toilets, pressure inthe showers, 
potable drinking water (I'm one of many people who gets sick on Pennsic water.
I now haul my own.)  All these things I wish for, and more.  Laundry facilities
where all the machines work all the time, and there are enough to go around so
that I don't have to devote my whole afternoon to keeping my place in line.  A
laundry that has chairs to sit on.  Someplace airconditioned where I can 
retreat when all this "back to nature"-ness takes its toll.  

Of course, my greatest fantasy of all is my own private room with a bed that
doesn't have lumps and whose bedding isn't perpetually damp.  With my own
private bathroom with a tub to soak in when my legs are killing me and a
toilet I know nobody's thrown up on.  

How age changes us.  I used to scorn RV users because "they weren't really
camping".  Now one of my great ambitions in life is to become one.  

I  would welcome a permament, well provided for site.  I've been coming to
Pennsic ever since Pennsic VIII.  I've seen two bath houses built, new flush
toilets added, a second swimming hole made, water piped to the Tu Chucks camp,
a laundry built, camping space expanded, the store grown to provide all manner
of useful items and now occupying a tent as well as the building, ice carted
in, firewood cut, and so on.  I think the Cooper's are doing an excellent job
attending to our needs.

I think some other things could be done.  Expanding the water system,
definitely.  More faucets to more areas of the camp, more flush toilets, more
showers, an air conditioned site for the chirugeons, some place more suitable
for holding classes than the barn and bath house.  

And I think the idea of establishing a paid office for whoever autocrats the
war is an excellent idea too.  I sure wouldn't want to autocrat it.  And the
people who do so much for us are deserving of compensation. " All the fine words
and all the fine phrase never helped put food on the table," to paraphrase a
plaque hanging in my mother's kitchen.

Yours in Service to a Livable Pennsic,
