Re:  Banishment, and restriction of attendance.

Basically, the SCA has no way to prevent attendance at events.
Other than the procedures any other group/individual has.  i.e. the
SCA, Inc., (or presumably a local group) could follow mundane legal
procedure, either by having the individual arrested (for a crime),
or by having a "restraining order" issued by a judge (if threat to
individuals could be shown).

The SCA, Inc (or presumably a local group) could limit the
activities of individuals (i.e. no fighting) or restrict the
membership.  But I see no way to limit access to "non-profit
educational activities open to the public".  (other than mundane
legal procedure)

Re:  Persona Banishment.

So what?  Basically, many people in the SCA don't have personas.  I
don't claim to have a persona, Count William the Lucky claims to
have no persona.  Many people I know don't have personas.

The people who have personas, and are willing to modify their
behavior because their "persona" was "banished" aren't usually the
problem.  They would probably modify their behavior anyway, if asked
under the right circumstances.  i.e. they're willing to play "the
game".

Re:  Copora suggested banishment.

Basically, this is suggesting we quantify what is probably the
maximum allowable (legally).  And limiting its use to specific
individuals (Kings/Princes).  i.e. we are limiting ourselves, both
to protect ourselves, legally, and to restrict our "game".

i.e. Should people other than the (King/Prince) be allowed to banish
someone?  Should a banishment effect all areas of the SCA?  or just
the local area?  Should a banished person be able to fight (at all),
or should their authorization be voided?  etc.

These seem to be the issues that need to be addressed, not "can we
keep people out we don't like", to which the answer is basically no.

Etienne d'Argent
Abeyance of the Westermark
Kingdom of the West

