In article <25534@amdcad.AMD.COM>, daver@amdcad.AMD.COM (Dave Rubin) writes:
> In article <8905051428.AA02132@tut.cis.ohio-state.edu>, WANDERER%MTUS5.BITNET@CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU (Karl Jacobs) writes:
> > Anybody made boiled leather and want to give me advice?
> 
> [Good advice for small pieces deleted]
> Take the piece
> out, let the wax drip off, then form it and place it in the
> freezer. You may have to put it in the freezer briefly before
> forming it as leather directly out of the boiler is very soft
> and won't hold a shape. 

I usually dump the leather onto foil or newspaper to cool.  I let is sit until
it comes down to a reasonable temperature and then fit it.  This takes a
little longer, but my freezer is full enough, and the excess wax has more
time to run off.

> Second: Pieces too large to fit entirely in the wax can be
> worked through from one side to another as long as each area
> is in the wax long enough to stop bubbling (tiny bubbles btw).

Be careful.  If the wax is too hot or has hot spots, you can toast the
leather and ruin the piece. While the above method works, it introduces
opportunities for uneven coverage, leaving soft spots in the armour.  For
large pices, I generaly buy a diposable (large) cookie sheet and I have an
old basting brush just for this work (I used to use a cheap paint brush, but
the glue kept melting :-).  Put your large piece on the cookie sheet in an
oven set to about the melting point of the wax (130 - 150 Deg. F) and let
it warm up.  Use the basting brush to baiste the leather with hot wax every
5 minutes until the piece will not absorb more wax. Check that the wax has
penetrated the piece.  If it has, take it out and let it cool, if not, wait
a bit longer and check again.

> I made mine maybe 6 years ago and it has held up
> tremendously since. It is still very hard and provides as much 
> protection as steel. If you don't have the skills or facilities
> to work in metal, boiled leather is a great alternative. It is
> even a valid first choice for much early and transitional period
> armour.
> 
>     Robyn Solarius             Dave Rubin

I have to agree, It is a good choice for easy to craft protection. I am
satisfied with mine after much time in it.

