In article <11586@well.UUCP> hrh@well.UUCP (Harry Henderson) writes:

> >The East has had two unbelted Kings.  As far as I know, no one ever
> >expressed doubts over Their qualifications for the crown on that
> >point . . .
> 
> If *all* qualifications are met--why do they not receive the honors
> they have earned?  As Mistress Hilary so wonderfully puts it:  We don't
> *make* Peers--we find 'em.  Surely if they are qualifed in all respects
> it harms the Kingdom not to recognize that fact?

Ah, but the qualifications of a King are not the same as the
qualifications of a Knight.  A King must be a wise and careful ruler,
slow to anger and quick to forgive, deliberate in his thoughts, and
resolute in his decisions.  In practice, he just has to have one good
day on the field.  A Knight must be the model of chivalry and honor at
all times, first in battle and last in retreat, unswerving in his
loyalty to the Crown.  It is often the case that these qualifications
occur in the same man, but not always.

> Do all of your Peers, then, individually swear fealty to a new King?
> In light of the individual oaths, does the King have a different oath
> fo each of his Peers?  This would certainly be period, but it could
> get a little difficult.

Yes & yes.  In First Court, each peerage order is called into court
and the companions are given the opportunity to swear fealty
individually.  The Crown responds to each peer individually.  It takes
a while, but I think it creates a much stronger bond between the
individual peer and the Crown than would a group oath.  Great Officers
and Landed Baroncy also swear oaths in the same manner, and have also
joined the escalation in oaths.  Two reigns ago, Baron Settmour was
carried into court on a palanquin with armed guards, dancing girls,
and trumpets, flinging gold into the crowd.  Quite a performance.

  It might be worth noting that Eatern officers do not swear fealty,
but rather swear an oath of office.  The distinction may be a fine
one, but it is important.  My own oath, for example, tends to run
something like:

I am Arval Benicoeur, Brigantia Principal Herald.  I am Your voice and
Your ears, your messenger and ambassador.  I swear to fulfill the
duties of my office to the best of my ability, and to obey Your every
lawful command, saving only my duties to the Laurel Queen of Arms.  I
offer you my counsel and my aid in all Your endeavors.  All this do I
swear for as long as I serve the Crown of the East and You sit on Your
thrones, and should I fail in this oath, may my tongue rot in my
mouth.

...give or take a bit.

	Arval.
