Date: 9 May 89 19:59:14 GMT
From: uxc!tank!fac_ddf%gsbacd.uchicago.edu@iuvax.cs.indiana.edu
Subject: inter-kingdom anthropology and others
Message-Id: <3141@tank.uchicago.edu>

I am writing in response to Hal Ravn very interesting queries about
inter-kingdom differences. 

Ceremonies: Parts of the original Middle Kingdom coronation oath (and
allegiance oaths) were also, and independently, lifted from Tolkien.  The
ceremony also included the "this is what it means to be a king" passage
from C.S. Lewis, "The Horse and His Boy." When I came back to the Kingdom
some fifteen years later and attended a coronation, what struck me most
was the process of accretion. Much of the original ceremony still
remained, but it looked as though every second or third king had decided
to add just one more bit, to "improve" it. The result was poetically and
dramatically much weaker than the original (you may want to allow for my
bias on the question). Recently Eliahu, with whom I had discussed the
matter, did a rewrite that seemed to substantially improve the situation. 

Unbelted Kings: The situation as I remember it in the East was that there
was a time when no unbelted fighter had ever been crowned--either the
winner was a knight, or he was knighted after winning. A number of us felt
that that was an undesirable situation, since it seemed to imply that
prowesse alone was a sufficient qualification for knighthood. At the same
time, it was hard to break the tradition, since failing to knight the
victor would seem to imply that he was particularly unqualified. The
problem was finally solved when someone won the crown who was unbelted and
thought the tradition was a bad one; he requested the king not to knight
him. All of this is by memory, and some of what I am describing may be
what I thought other people thought was happening, so to speak, but I
think it is essentially correct.

Another posting (by Arval) said that the East had had two unbelted kings,
Viktor and Morgan. Memories are short. I believe Fernando was the first
unbelted King of the East and Gyrth the second; Gyrth got knighted during
his reign by the King of Meridies at Pennsic, with (I am told) the
unanimous assent of the Eastern Chivalry.

The same posting asserted that the ratio of knights to population is lower
in the East than in other Kingdoms. I would be interested to see numbers.
I have occasionally tried to do such estimates, for particular kingdoms,
and do not have the impression that the East is strikingly different from
Meridies or the Middle. I have heard that Atenvelt has more knights and a
different definition of what a knight means than other kingdoms, but do
not know if it is true.

The posting also asserted, about the residency requirement, that "We
established this requirement because we believe that the East is a very
different land from the other 11 Kingdoms.  Much of what is important
about the East is not written down anywhere, but only exists as custom.  A
King unfamiliar with Eastern custom could not rule well." True and false.
Arval seems to imply that the other kingdoms were similar to each other
and the East somehow special. That was not true when the residency
requirement was established, and is not true now. The reason for the
requirement was that kingdoms are different from each other, not that the
East was more different than other kingdoms.  

Hal Ravn also seems to take it for granted that the West has more peers
than the East. I would be interested to see the numbers. The East has a
substantially larger population, and although it is younger, a difference
of two years or so is not all that large from a distance of over twenty.

Entering the Crown: In the Middle at present, all belted fighters are
allowed in the crown unless specifically forbidden by the King. Unbelted
fighters are permitted by invitation, with many but far from all being
invited. As far as I know this is the only kingdom that does it that way.
In the very early years, the rule was all belted fighters plus anyone who
had won one major or two minor tournaments since the last crown (I think;
details may be wrong, given that I am remembering events from almost
twenty years ago). In effect, we were using other tournaments as
preliminary elimination rounds to keep down the size of the crown lists.
At some point that shifted to the present system, where the king in effect
decides who would make a tolerable successor. On the whole, I think it is
a bad idea, for reasons that would take a while to go into. On the other
hand, it seems to have worked all right, and I like the idea of different
kingdoms having their own traditions.

Some more queries: How do the relations between peer and
squire/apprentice/protegee vary among the kingdoms? My impression of one
kingdom where I have lived was that an apprentice was not so much someone
the Laurel was teaching a craft to as someone the Laurel was sponsoring to
become a Laurel--thus it was considered perfectly normal for a Laurel to
take an apprentice who practiced an art the Laurel had no expertise in.
Someone else, commenting on a different part of the same kingdom,
expressed the opinion that apprentices and protegees were, in effect,
trading labor (doing the less pleasant parts of what had to be done in a
household) for political support. That is certainly not how I perceive the
relation, but I do not know how things vary through different kingdoms. A
couple of objective questions that might shed light on such issues are: 1:
Do Laurels take apprentices not their own field? 2: How common is it for
someone to become a peer without first being a squire/apprentice/protegee?

Unrelated topics: For Ariel, and her posting re self-defense in kitchens:

A blade is a maid's last appeal
To prove her refusal is real
De ____, I'm told,
Being timid and bold,
Now courts in a full shirt of steel

For Alexander Kay: The source for the Orlando Translation anecdote, I
believe, was the modern preface to an edition of the Elizabethan
Translation. I have forgotten the translator's name, but if you look under
Orlando Furioso in a good university liberary you should be able to find
it.




