as originally concieved, is from hwella, "wheel" and -land "land"
(surprised? :-).  I palitalized the h to a k, giving me basically
kwellaland, and then, in process as old as English itself, dropped
the repeated sylable, yeilding kwelland, meaning a circle of land,
or in my case, completing a journey.  (England comes from Anglaland,
and the two -la-'s in it were dropped by the same process.)

	Then I found out (after using it for about 4 years) that I
had to document the name...  uhoh.  What saved me was that I had
used (more or less by accident) good linguistic methods in generating
it, so it was easy to find an almost identical word, cwellend.  The
c -> k shift was simply orthographic and the a->e was trivial, 
since neither is stressed it sounds about the same in modern 
speach.  And, luckily (and it is luck that lets one slide by with some
thing like this) the word was an adjective, and perfectly period
one 'killer' (not one I would have chosen personally, but it makes
