Date: Tue, 9 May 89 19:38:28 EDT
From: "S. Gwen Johnson" <sgj%ctj.uucp@BRL.MIL>
Subject: arts and science competitions
Message-ID:  <8905092001.aa02893@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>


Fro a number of years I took it as my special duty to feed and clothes newbies
in our area.  As I helped them learn about the SCA, eventually we discussed
arts and science competitions.  Few of them were thrilled by the concept.  Two
attitudes prevailed 1) I do it because I like it and letting other people
nit-pick my work isn't fun.  2) I'm new to the group and just started doing
this stuff so I could never win so I won't enter.  I tried to encourage people
to enter, but not being too enthusiastic about the system myself, I'm afraid my
persuasions lacked conviction.  Now my Shire is threatening to make me Minister
of Arts and Sciences and I've been thinking about this issue, and I have a
suggestion to offer.

Adopt the state fair system.  At fairs, all entrants are judged and awarded
either a blue, red, or yellow ribbon.  ALL entrants receive ribbons, except for
pieces that are utterly pathetic, which rarely ocurrs.  One piece in each
category is picked for a "first place" or "best of category".  One piec is
picked for "best of show".  Thus everybody gets feed back and appreciation for
their efforts. People with less skill can still win, because they get ribbons.
People with high degree of skill can be honored with best of category and best
of show awards. Sometimes special awards are sponsored by businesses and 
awarded on diferent criteria than the fair awards.  This means everybody has
lots of chances to earn distinction for themselves and be encouraged to
continue, rather than be disappointed and discouraged because their piece was
good enough.

I've noticed that arts and science competitions are generally pretty thin with
entries.  I would enter a lot more often if I felt I was getting positive feedback
instead of being nit-picked.  I bet a lot of other people would too.  By
adopting this system it would also be easier to reccommend people for arts and
science awards.  Instead of writing a letter of reccomendation that says
"George has made all these really neat things this year, and one of them won
once, but I think he should have won more"  could be replaced with more
objective criteria "George has entered four different pieces of armour in
competitions in the last year and has received three blue ribbons and a red
ribbon.One of his pieces took best of category."

This system would also make it easier for people to know and recognize the
achievements of other people, even in fields they didn't know much about.  When
I go up to embroidery, I can tell what's good, because I know embroidery.  But
when I look at leatherworking or calligraphy, I know almost beans about them.
All I can say is: "I think it's pretty."  But I don't know if the person has done
something difficult or easy, or even if it's period or not.  If I see a piece
with a blue ribbon on it I learn something.  "Aha, bright red is period after
all! Otherwise it wouldn't have gotten a blue ribbon."

I think we might see people entering more obscure items if they didn't have to
try and shoehorn them into some other category so that there'd be enough pieces
to judge among. I remember when a fellow painstakingly recreated lampblack ink
and did a small piece of calligraphy with it.  He had a two page article
documenting his sources and methods.  There were no other inks, dyes, pigments,
or any kind of colorants entered, so they put him in the calligraphy category,
even though it was the ink, not the writing he was entering.  Argh!  He didn't
win, but personaly I feel he should have been recognized.  But he didn't fit
the standard categories.   Everyone agreed he did a wonderful thing, and
calligraphers were hunting him down and asking for his ink, but no  award.

Assuming I do win the election to the post of minister of arts and sciences, I
am going to try and implement this system for competition.  Hopefully it will
spark people do more along these lines.  Our shire seems more interested in
hosting events and fighting than arts and sciences. As far as I can tell so
far, very little a & s is being done here.  (Except cooking.  We have a strong
and skilled cook's guild.One of our cooks has the great distinction of the
massed populace crying "We want more turnips!" "But nobody likes turnips," he
replied in bewilderment.  He has promised turnips for our next feast, lots of
'em.)

Yours in Service  to getting artsy people off their duffs,
Awilda Halfdane
Bright Hills, Atlantia
<sgj%ctj.uucp@smoke.brl.mil>
PS.  If the Atlantian minister of arts and sciences is reading this, can you
please send me a copy of the judging standards?






