Date: 10 May 89 01:02:18 GMT
From: uxc!tank!fac_ddf@deimos.cis.ksu.edu
Subject: Is the Pennsic War Too Large?
Message-Id: <3149@tank.uchicago.edu>

First, I apologize for this being an ephemeral posting: David Friedman is
guesting me and I have no permanent access to the net. I am not likely to
answer any queries this posting might create, but hope the topic is of
general interest to some.

In a recent posting, someone made the claim that the Pennsic War was
getting too large.  I don't think this is true. It seems to me there are
three possible meanings for the statement.

1) The battles are becoming too large to conduct. From the fighter's
standpoint, I think this is patently false. The neat thing about Pennsic
battles are that they can be conducted at a size normally impossible to
us.  From a safety standpoint, a larger battle is riskier in the sense
that the likelihood of someone getting killed is larger with 2000
participants than with 500. It is also riskier in the sense that medical
response time for any battle is longer, since it takes a notable time to
stop a battle and get the appropriate personnel to the injured fighter /
waterbearer / spectator. From the first cause,  an individual's risk is no
higher personally; from the second,  the field/bridge battle becomes
riskier to fight in, but less risky than the woods battle, since the
terrain is gentler, and medical response time is still higher than for
someone in the woods.

2) The site is too small. It might be the case that there isn't enough
room to camp, isn't enough water to shower with, the woods are too small
to do battle in, etc.  I think the physical facilities are adequate -- the
Coopers keep expanding the available land, and they keep building more
facilities. It is the case that the Far Hill is a terrible place to be
camped for a lot of people: you essentially leave your campsite in the
morning, and come back in the evening.  I think there are things that can
be done about this problem:  with a new woods area to fight in,  more of
where we fought the old wolds battle can be used for camping; the hillside
could be landscaped so camping could occur closer to the main event area; 
a place for storing equipment (with a checkin/checkout facility) could be
set up in the main area; a discounted fee could be offered to people
willing to camp on the hill.

3) Nobody wants to autocrat an event with 10,000 people at it. I know I
sure don't. I think if Pennsic does become that size, we should pay some
of our people to do the work required. We do it for other parts of the
Socity, and here we have the advantage of being able to pay for help out
of the event charge.

Tom Courtney
aka Vissevald Selkirksson

