Date: Sat, 6 May 89 21:45:16 EDT
From: "S. Gwen Johnson" <sgj%ctj.uucp@BRL.MIL>
Subject: Corpora comments on banishment
Message-ID:  <8905071234.aa11390@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

The idea of banishment is basically a way to legislate who will be allowed in
the SCA and who will not.  This bothers me.  I can see people being banished
simply because they're not popular with the local powers that be.  I am willing
to accept banishment of SCA personas for SCA reasons. For example, an officer
failing to carry out his office could be banished until such time as he had
caught up on his duties.  Banishment in such a case would basically be a
warning "Get it right, or you'll lose your office."

Banishing people, well, I don't go for that.  Yes, I've met men who couldn't
understand the word "no" too.  I think that such matters ought to handled on a
personal level.  A scenario could be,  Masher offends Lady.  Lady goes to her
champion and tells him about it.  Champion challenges Masher.  Masher doesn't
fight, so he has to get a Champion.  Everybody knows the Masher, nobody will
champion him.  Baron decides that everybody has a right to champion, so he
volunteers.  He decides also that justice must be served, so he fights with a
dagger and no shield and loses.  Masher has to apologize to Lady and promise to
stay away from her.  This is the period way to handle such affairs, and its
what chivalry is all about.  It also sends a very clear message to the offender
that his behaviour has made him unpopular and he'd better shape up, or leave.
It also means that anybody who wasn't aware of the Masher's behaviour is going
to hear about it.  Details need not be given:  Offense to a Lady is explanation
enough.

But people in the SCA are polite and tolerant.  They don't beat the daylights
out of somebody just because he's attempted to rape a woman.  So banishing him
is a nice neat way for them to avoid coping with the issue while getting him
out of their hair.  Some mashers are incurable.   Some mashers learn.  Remember
Gawain?  Gawain had a thing for the ladies.  Poetic justice was served out on
him by making him the defender of women.  Whenever a woman needed help in any
situation, Gawain was her champion.  Being forced to take the ladies' side
repeatedly eventually taught him to sympathize with them-and he became a gentle
knight.  He was still fond of the ladies, but he a was sensitive about it.

And then there is the situation:Banishment as a punishment for what mundane law
could prosecute.  In these situations, let the mundane law prosecute.  Passing
judgement on others is not a function of the SCA.  It is quite conceivable that
a person banished for a theft that wasn't mundanely prosecuted could sue the
SCA for denying him his rights without due process of law.  If we're going to
banish people we need to set up some kind of judicial proceeding to fairly
examine all points of view and determine whether banishment (or any other kind
of punishment ) is appropriate.  This is not medeival, the whims of kings were
law in period. But we live in the modern world, and modern American law says
you can't deprive a person of anything without proper proceedings.  That's a
can of worms I don't want to open.  SCA judges?  Yuck.  I'd rather keep things
personal.  The custom of duelling does have it's advantages, even if we modern
folk are so civilized we're shocked by the concept of using violence to solve
problems. 

Of course, what I expect to happen is what has been happening: SCA folk will
ignore unpleasant people to the best of their ability and eventually they go
away.  This seems to be  a reasonably workable system and I don't think the 
Corpora needs to concern itself with matters like these.  The Corpora ought to
confine itself strictly to those matters necessary for the SCA to function.

Yours in Service,
Awilda Halfdane
once a upon a time a pre-law student
