Date: Sat, 6 May 89 21:42:32 EDT
From: "S. Gwen Johnson" <sgj%ctj.uucp@BRL.MIL>
Subject: Corpora comments
Message-ID:  <8905071234.aa11393@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

The subject of names is a tricky one.  Various gentles have spoken in favor of
requiring documented names only.  they consider the phrase "period ambience" an
invitation to abuse.  We do need a standard, and at first glance I think
documented only is a good idea, but then I remember problems people have had.
Let me give an example, using a completely fictious name so that I won't be
intruding on anybody's privacy.
	
A friend of mine tried to register the name XXn.  The heralds refused.  Xxn was
only used as a part of names,  and his name would have to be the long form of
some other name, such as Xxnbio, or Xxnal, or Xxndred.  They wouldn't let him
use plain old Xxn, because it wasn't documented.  He tacked on a knickname, and
became Xxn of Vv, but they still didn't go for it.  "Xxn" is never used alone
they proclaimed.  Then, one day, quite by accident, he came across reference to
an obscure Celtic king named Xxn.  Therefore he was able to document it as a
period name, and they had to pass it.

I think that if Xxn is used in compound names there is no reason why it
shouldn't be used singly.  I'm sure Xxndred's friends called him just Xxn, so
why not let somebody else have it as is?  There are lots of other names that
can't be documented, that is to say, you can't point at an existing historical
person with the same name, but nonetheless would be recognized as a
comprehensible name by the poeple from its period.  So I think names that are
plausible variations or dirivatives of known period names ought to be
accepted.

And if we're going to insist on period names used in period ways, well, that
can be abused too.  For example, twenty-five per cent of the men in Normandy
during William the Bastard's day were named William.  Are we going to require
one fourth of Norman personas to be named William?

And what is acceptable documentation?  I picked my name from legend and it
passed.  Names that ocurr in legends in period could have been used by ordinary
people, and often were.  I have met a modern mundane woman with my SCA name,
showing that the boundary between legend and reality is thin.  And what will
we do about "legends" that might be history?  Is it acceptable to use an name
that is completely fictional, but was used in period?  Medeival writers often
invented names.  Can I use one of them?

An example: Hamlet.  Shakespeare
used the name, but it was not a name in currency any place in Europe.  It was a
derivative of an older Danish name, Amleth.  Shakespeare's play is a reworking
of an old Danish legend.  Can Hamlet and Amleth be used?  They were used in
period, at least in fictional pieces.  Or are they forbidden, because they are
fictional?  Or if I want to use the name Amleth do I have to prove the
historical validity of the legend?

I am willing to accept names that can be shown to have some kind of historicity
as their basis.  Something that came out of the blue with no connection to
anything is out.  I am also willing to allow the use of names from fiction
provided that the name is used in a period manner and has a period basis.
Maybe meeting somebody named Gandalf would make you think of Tolkien's work,
but I have met a mundane person with t he surname of Gandalf.  At first i was
startled, but then I recalled that all of Tolkien's names have historical
basis, so I got used to it.

  If somebody wants to use a name that's already been used and made famous 
by someone else,all they have to do is tack something onto 
it that makes it possible to distinguish among them.  This is already done
by people who have picked commonly used names.  People named John, Sean, 
and William are already dealing with the issue.  I have no objection to people
using names like "Loki the Weaver" because Loki is a name well known to have
existed in period, even if it was not in common circulation.  The addition of
the knickname, "the Weaver" serves to notify that this person is not claiming
to be the Norse god of mischief, but is merely named after him.

And people did invent names.  Maybe these names were considered odd by the
people around them, but well, most of our personas would be considered to be
odd by the people we base them on. 

I suggest that the writers of the Corpora rewrite their proposalon names to
clarify what is and is not allowed.  And that is the real key, it must be
expressed so clearly that everybody will generally agree on what's allowable
and what's not, that way people don't have to make up their own definitions,
only to run into to trouble because somebody higher up doesn't share their
understanding of what the rule means.

Since this posting is too long now, I'll pass on banishment and subjects at
this time.

Yours in Service,
Awilda Halfdane
<sgj%ctj.uucp@smoke.brl.mil>

