Date:     Sun, 7 May 89 21:22 EST
From:     <PERKINS%MSUPA.BITNET@mitvma.mit.edu>
Subject:  a couple of points of interest (or maybe not:-)

--Lord Arval [Joshua Mittleman (joshua@paul.rutgers.edu)] writes:
>
> In modern America, it is certainly the case that parents can name
> their children anything they want, and often make-up names with no
> basis at all.  This was not the case in most times, in most places.
> In particular, it is not true today in many countries, where a child's
> name may need legal approval (France, USSR, Argentina, and any who is
> Catholic), nor was it true in medieval Europe.  Names formed a
> distinct class of words in each language, and it was very rare for
> names to be added to that stock.  There was some variation, but it was
> not random: It followed certain linguistic rules in each culture.  As
> the SCA is trying to recreate those cultures, their naming systems are
> something we should at least try to use.
>
Note that medieval fiction writers often made up quite fanciful names (by
the "linguistic rules" of their cultures).  There are books with lists of
such names available at more complete libraries; of course, books of "real"
medieval names reside at such libraries as well, and such names are more
easily justifiable to the heralds.  Reading through actual medieval English
documents, one of the most striking things is the lack of diversity in
names:  it seems like all men were named John, Roger, Henry or William
(+ maybe one or two others) and all women were either nameless or called
Alyce or Mary!  So perhaps a little more open-ness towards the "possible"
might be in order here, as actual practice tended towards the downright
tedious in many cultures.


--Ariel of Caer Myrddin (Karen J. Norteman) writes:
>
> Whatever are we going to do?  In my shire we're thinking about drawing straws
> to see who has to make the trip out early so we can get a place to camp.  Last
> year we had 100 people in our camp, from 10 different groups. This year, we'll
> be up a creek if we can't get someone to get out there two weeks ahead of
> everyone else.  And will it be three weeks next year?  Four?
>
Perhaps we can go to a "hereditary" system, in keeping with our "medieval"
inclinations ? :-) :-)    This overpopulation crisis would have been
amusing (had any of us foreseen it) to those at the first Coopers' Lake
Pennsic (VI), when the west half of the campground was continuously
occupied by non-SCA campers, and arriving on Thursday night brought
greetings from the dozen or so people who had gotten there earlier...


