Subject: training

    Some background info: I am the Marshal of Marwick (Canton of Settmour
Swamp, East Kingdom); I am Squired to Duke Sir Ronald Wilmot; and I hold
regular fight practices.  Here's my two-cents worth about what you do with/to
beginners:
    Before any beginner even tries on someone else's armor, they must attend
several practices and just do UNARMORED slow work, the goal of which is to
build some endurance in holding up the shield, some control in swinging the
sword, and to demonstrate that they are really interested in fighting.  While
they are doing this, we are teaching them the basics of how to block, and the
basics of throwing blows.
    Some people have given up before getting into armor.  We save these people
time and money, which they would have thrown away on armor they wouldn't have
used. The ones that stick with it long enough, eventually wind up in armor (we
have some loaner gear), and if they STILL want to continue, then we help them
design and create their own armor. (Marwick also holds regular armor workshops,
also at my house.)
    To date, no one who has shown up at the Marwick practice, and persevered
through a few weeks of really basic training, and made it into armor, has then
quit.  We are proud of the fact that we turn out safe, easily authorizable
fighters.

Laird Mitchell MacBain, Esquire

