Date: 6 May 89 07:54:29 GMT
From: hoffman@gondor.cs.psu.edu  (Richard C. Hoffman)
Subject: Responses to planned Pennsic Camping Space Allocation (LONG)
Message-Id: <4551@psuvax1.cs.psu.edu>


     Things are pretty hairy around here right now, but I just couldn't
let this pass by without comment.  This reply is fairly long, fair
warning.

	   Chelidon
-------------------------------------------------------------------------


          Unto my Lord Morgan,  and all the gentles of the Pennsic
     War Council,

          Chelidon o Gaerddrych does send fair greetings,


          My Good Gentles,

          I  have  read through your  proposal  regarding  camping
     space allocation at the Pennsic War.
          First and foremost,  I would like to thank you for  your
     efforts  in a most difficult and controversial  task.   Space
     allocation  has  always,  and will always be,  a  troublesome
     situation.  I applaud the effort expended by you all.

          I would like to bring up several serious reservations  I
     have with respect to your proposal:

          As  a basic overview,  I must state that in my  mind,  a
     simple  formula applies with respect to both the SCA and  the
     mundane world in general:   The more restriction and  bureau-
     cracy, the less enjoyment of the situation at hand.   Pennsic
     is my *vacation*.   In exactly the manner as the SCA  itself,
     if,  through humbug of one kind or another,  leisure activity
     reaches  a certain level of perturbation,  I will  simply  go
     elsewhere.  I get enough grief from the normal affairs of the
     world to want to deal with it in my time off.   I may be  off
     the  mark,  but I think that I am by no means alone  in  this
     philosophy.
          I of course understand that a certain amount of  regula-
     tion is necessary in any organization,  and for an event  the
     size  of  Pennsic,  a great deal of planning  must  be  done.
     Again,  for allocating some of *your* leisure time to perform
     this  planning,  I am most grateful.   My point is that  this
     "necessary" level of regulation and paperwork MUST be kept to
     an absolute minimum.

          Specific suggestions follow:


     I.   The $5.00/person site reservation fee at the time of the
     camping  site lottery unfairly discriminates  against  larger
     camping groups.   While it is fair and reasonable to expect a
     certain  amount of prior organization from  large  households
     and camping groups,  a certain percentage of the people camp-
     ing  with _any_ group will invariably be unable to get  their
     reservation  fee to whoever is handling the site lottery  for
     their group.   It would be foolish to ignore the fact that  a
     very large proportion of SCA members tend to be, like myself,
     disorganized nincompoops at times.   To deny this basic char-
     acteristic of our population is,  at best,  wishful thinking.
     For smaller groups, the amount of unpaid fees which had to be
     covered by the "space-holder" person might amount to at most,
     $30 or so.   For larger groups, however,  this total could be
     upwards of $100.   While I am willing to spend several nights
     before leaving for the war calling people who have signed  up
     to camp,  in order to confirm their names on my camp list,  I
     am not willing nor able to cover large amounts of fees out of
     my own pocket for people who, for one reason or another, were
     unable  to get their $5.00/person in by the time I  left  for
     the war.  Refusing to let these people camp with their house-
     holds, local groups, and SCA families for the duration of the
     War would be plainly unfair,  and degrade the quality of  the
     experience for many.
          I understand the purpose of the fee,  and fully  deplore
     the practice of knowingly filling one's camp roster with non-
     existent people simply in order to grab more land.   This  is
     clearly a most dishonorable practice.
          However,  by levying such a tax,  you are attempting  to
     legislate honor,  which is an endeavor doomed to failure,  in
     addition to being against the most basic spirit of the  Soci-
     ety.  If you treat people as if they have no honor, they will
     tend  not to act honorably in response to  your  legislation,
     and I think it unlikely that you will develop a system  which
     cannot be frustrated.
          If such a fee is retained,  I will be most disappointed.
     In that case,  however,  I would at least ask that the amount
     of such fees be reduced to $1.00/person.  While this may,  in
     your  judgement,  reduce the deterrent value of the  fee,  it
     would  at least reduce the inequitable discrimination  placed
     upon  large  camping  groups by such an  exercise  (as  noted
     above).
          In addition,  if such a fee is levied (call it an  Honor
     Tax, for lack of a better term), I will insist on knowing ex-
     actly what that money is used for (beyond the general "Build-
     ing Fund").   The process of adding a fee to the costs of at-
     tending  Pennsic which is not directly related to the  number
     of nights spent at the site is,  in my opinion,  a truly  bad
     precedent to set, and should be strongly discouraged.


     II.  The proposal to prohibit camping before Sunday, August 6
     (only  one week previous to the week of the War),  except  on
     the  site  of the battlefield has several  serious  flaws  as
     well.

          A.        For  those people (like myself),  with  large,
          cumbersome  encampments (I reside while at Pennsic in  a
          rather  sizable yurt,  with accompanying  detrius),  the
          thought of being forced to set up camp (an all-afternoon
          project,  at  least) three weeks before  the  War,  then
          repack a week later,  take down the yurt,  reload it  on
          the  trailer,  pull the trailer to another site,  unpack
          it,  put it up, and reestablish my household,  consuming
          at  least  an entire day of my vacation  time,  is  most
          distasteful.   In addition, there is at least one gentle
          I  know  of  who brings his equipment to the  war  in  a
          rented truck,   and who then rents the vehicle again for
          his trip home.   Are you then insisting that he rent the
          truck  yet a third time,  in order that he relocate  his
          campsite?   Now I know that what would in reality  occur
          would  be that some kind gentle would donate his or  her
          vehicle  to the project, solving the immediate  problem.
          The point I make, however, is that you must consider the
          large  amount of trouble and disarrangement you are  go-
          ing to force at least 120 people (by last year's  count,
          and  probably  more) to go through in order  to  execute
          your plan.

          B.        The  above  objections form the  least  of  my
          points on this matter.  Regardless of what I said above,
          I would be entirely willing to pick up and move my camp-
          site,  despite the trouble involved,  if this  were  the
          only consideration involved.
                    When I arrive several weeks early at the  War,
          and  spend  my  entire vacation there,  I  gain  several
          benefits  by  doing  so.   One  of  the  most  important
          of  these benefits is the relative solitude enjoyed  be-
          fore   Cooper's Lake gets too crowded.   I really  enjoy
          having   plenty of space around me for a  while,  before
          tents  fill   up most of the available space.   I  enjoy
          camping  just   under the treeline,  in order  to  enjoy
          shade during the  day, and the stars at night.   I enjoy
          an  unobstructed  view of the surrounding campsites.   I
          enjoy  the  ability   to be  secluded,  yet  visit  with
          friends   if I choose.   I  enjoy the quiet,  surrounded
          only by the  sounds of nature ,  and the mood this  puts
          me in.   I enjoy  being  within easy walking distance of
          the swimming hole  and  the lake, and being able to eas-
          ily  wander around the   vacant sites that I know,  will
          soon  be  filled with thousands of people  who  share  a
          common vision.
                    Of  course  I don't mind when the rest  of  my
          fellow   SCA   brethren  show  up,   and  I   love   the
          crowded  bustle around the barn and the merchants  area,
          meeting  friends  you  haven't  seen  for  a  year,  the
          buildup  to the weekend,  fighting for the  War  Points,
          and the sheer  impact of so many thousands of people all
          living their Dreams.  This is valuable to me, and one of
          the reasons I show up at Pennsic each year.
                    Yet equally as valuable to me is the  pleasure
          I  get in the weeks before everything gets  so  joyously
          chaotic.   If  I am forced to camp on the  flat  battle-
          field,   together with everybody else who arrived early,
          not by  choice,  but by compulsion, a large part of what
          I find  valuable in the War will have been taken away.
                    I  understand if the Coopers wish to keep  ev-
          erybody  who  arrives early together  in  one  place--it
          makes  things  much  easier for  them  logistically  and
          is  much cheaper in terms of overhead,  since they  will
          have  many  less  bathrooms  to  clean,  porta-johns  to
          empty,  etc.,  than if we were more  widely  distributed
          throughout  the grounds,   and they will also get a  few
          extra   weeks to  make ready the regular campsites  than
          they are used to.  Yet,  when I  arrive early, I am pay-
          ing  the same rate as for  my  regular campsite,  though
          the  site  you  say will be available is  a  great  deal
          less  desirable  to me.   I would be   willing   to  pay
          an  increased  daily camping fee for the   time  leading
          up to  August 6,   if this enables the Coopers to   open
          the  normal camping areas at the usual time.


          I realized how long this is getting, and though I have a
     number of additional points,  I will end my letter here.   If
     you  have any questions regarding my opinions,  feel free  to
     contact me, either through this account, or at home.

          In conclusion I'd like to add that,  although I feel the
     addition of further administrative procedures and regulations
     to the Pennsic War is a bad thing,  I would be willing to put
     up with the lottery system under certain conditions.   I per-
     sonally feel that there is nothing wrong in there being  cer-
     tain benefits in arriving "early" at the War.  If a person is
     able,  and willing,  to spend several weeks at Cooper's Lake,
     possibly  forgoing  salary during that period,  paying  addi-
     tional  camping  fees,  and living in a tent for weeks  at  a
     time,  why SHOULDN'T they have a greater selection of camping
     spaces then someone who arrives later?  SCA members shouldn't
     be penalized for wanting to arrive at the War early.  Many of
     us would arrive much earlier than we do, if our circumstances
     were different.  Many others of us are willing to accept cer-
     tain mundane penalties in order to achieve this goal.

          Yet,  I acknowledge that some people have problems  with
     the  way land distribution has been handled in the past.   As
     stated above, I see nothing wrong with certain advantages ac-
     cruing  to those who are able and willing to make the  sacri-
     fices necessary to arrive early at the War.  For those groups
     who have as a member a person who is able and willing to make
     those sacrifices,  or who are willing to sponsor a person  to
     do  so,  I see no problem with that group  getting  a  larger
     choice of sites than other groups.   What I find unacceptable
     is  any group taking more space than it really needs.   Grab-
     bing  additional  camping space at the expense of  others  is
     clearly dishonorable.   However,  camping space should be  at
     slightly less of a premium,  since the entire wood where  the
     Woods battle was previously held will be available for  camp-
     ing this year.

                    *         *         *         *

          I firmly believe that a fair and equitable  distribution
     of  camping land can be gained simply by requiring a list  of
     people  camping with each group,  as was done last year.   In
     addition, it must be made clear that during the War,  Encamp-
     ment Captains will visit each group,  and check their  lists.
     Camps would be required to show proof that a substantial num-
     ber  of the people on the list were actually there,  by  pre-
     senting numbered "camping tags"  which every person would  be
     given upon check-in at the Troll Booth,  in addition to their
     personal tags.   Groups unable to show such proof would  have
     their  site size reduced,  and the extra space would be  made
     available  for arriving gentles.   The decisions of the  Cap-
     tains would be final, with perhaps some form of appeal avail-
     able directly to the War Autocrat or a Deputy.   In addition,
     setting aside some reasonably agreeable area for single camp-
     ers  who  are not affiliated with any group is  a  very  good
     idea.   Groups can usually afford to send someone to the  war
     early,   if  no  individual  in  the  group  can  do  so   by
     his/herself.   Individuals do not have that option, so should
     be   given   an   alternative  to  camping   in   the   least
     desirable/accessible spots.

                    *         *         *         *

          Such a system would be infinitely preferable to any form
     of site lottery.  With a lottery system, discontent would not
     necessarily  be reduced,  but instead of some people  feeling
     general discontent at "those land grabbers,"  you will have a
     directed  discontent aimed at the people who  legislated  the
     situation, the same people who have the enormous task of run-
     ning the War.  If a few people at the War feel that they have
     been done an injustice by another group, no real serious harm
     is done to the War as a whole, and the groups can discuss the
     problem  if necessary between themselves.   If enough  people
     have the attitude that they have been wronged by the  persons
     "in authority," you have a situation where the efforts of the
     people  trying to keep the War running smoothly will be  hin-
     dered.  This would be a Bad Thing.  The job's tough enough as
     it is.

          This  lottery  system  changes nothing  as  far  as  the
     "Pennsic Land Grab"  goes,  except to eliminate the advantage
     of arriving more than a week before the war.  I disagree with
     the reasoning behind this move, and I most strongly  disagree
     with the penalties exacted upon people who want to spend more
     than two weeks at Pennsic.  In particular,  forcing everybody
     who arrives early to camp on a flat hot field with  everybody
     else who arrives early, and then forcing these people to pick
     up and move their campsites is indefensible.

          Please  consider  the  opinions  I  have  attempted   to
     present, and again, feel free to contact me for any reason.

