Date:    Fri, 5 May 1989 0:57:56 EDT
From:    WELLING @ CPWSCA.PSC.EDU (JOEL WELLING)
Message-Id: <890505005756.2220706d@CPWSCA.PSC.EDU>
Subject: Pennsic War: space allocation, etc.

Hi Folks;

  As it turns out, I am one of the East Kingdom's two representatives on the
Pennsic War Council, which is a group charged with coming up with clever ideas
to smooth the operation of Pennsic.  (I shudder to admit it on the net, but I
am also the seneschal of the soon-to-be Principality of the Lakes, if you want
to yell at me about that).  This council had a meeting at Cooper's Lake last
Saturday, April 29, and we think we came up with some good ideas.  I will post
a full summary when I get the official minutes from Claire FitzWilliam, the
autocrat, but I noticed that Dani had made a post about some of the stuff we
discussed at the meeting ("Pennsic Campsite Allocation Policy", 3 May 89), so
I thought I should throw in a semi-official version.  PLEASE NOTE THAT WHAT
FOLLOWS IS NOT OFFICIAL OR CERTAIN; as I say I don't have the minutes of the
meeting yet and my recollection may be incorrect, or some other circumstance
may force a change.  Until Claire officially announces a plan, nothing is set
in stone.

If you want to correspond with me about this stuff or anything else, please do;
I get mail at welling@morgul.psc.edu or welling@cpwpsca on bitnet.  Please
mention the SCA in the subject line, so I can tell the mail isn't work-related.

Of course, the hot topic is the space allocation policy.  Last year things got
rather out of hand;  we want to prevent that this year.  The Coopers also want
to put a stop to this business of people showing up earlier and earlier, year
after year, to reserve space.

We agree that, as usual, there will be the traditional block reserved for royal
encampments.  I *believe* we also agreed that there would be some space held
for last-minute, single-tent walk-ons.  All the rest of the space will be
assigned by lottery.

Before Sunday, August 6, SCA people will only be allowed to camp on the
battlefield.  There will be no SCA encampments in the areas where all the
tents will ultimately go.  This is to make it easier for the Coopers to do
things like mowing of the camping area, and to discourage people from coming
much earlier than that.

From some time Saturday August 5 until noon Sunday, August 6, groups will
register for the lottery.  A group is a list of people;  no person should
belong to more than one group and no group may register more than once.
There is a 5 dollar fee for each person not yet in attendence in each group;
that fee is to be paid when the group registers and goes directly into the 
building fund.  Obviously, the fee is to prevent people from registering many
times and to prevent groups from pumping up their rolls with non-existant or
unlikely people.  We argued long and hard to find a fee that would discourage
these things without being an unbearable burden on some people, and it's not
clear that we found one, but we felt something was needed.

At about 1:00 Sunday, they will start drawing the names of large groups;  as
each group is called it can go rope off an appropriate amount of space.  When
the large groups are done grabbing space, the small groups will be drawn in a
separate lottery.  There were about 120 people on-site at this point last year,
so that should give you a rough idea of how many groups will be participating.

Obviously, the purpose of the lottery is to make sure there is no advantage to
arriving early- as long as your group's name is in the hat when the lottery is
drawn, you have an equal chance at the good sites.  We are drawing in two
groups in order to improve the packing efficiency of the camping space.  It
seems clear that one wants to rope off the larger areas first, just as one
wants to put the large pieces of armor in a duffle bag first, or allocate the
large chunks of memory first.  The cut-off between large and small groups is
likely to be a group size of about 30 people, but this is *not* a hard figure. 
Ideally half the groups would fall in the 'large' class and the other half
would be 'small'; if the cut-off of thirty produces a split which is too far
from this we will arbitrarily and without warning change the number.

Hopefully, people will have sat round on Saturday night and worked out a nice,
peaceful partition of the camping space between themselves.  We will provide
maps to help this along.  It's our hope that this discussion period will give
groups a chance to keep their traditional sites.  The lottery is there to be
the final arbiter of any disputes;  nothing would please us more than to have
all the space allocations planned out before the first ping-pong ball is drawn.

The following Sunday, August 13, an assigned enforcer and a hand-picked band of
Dukes and other ruffians will go through the site, compacting encampments that
can't demonstrate that they're using their space reasonably efficiently.  We
hope that this will provide some additional space for new arrivals.  

And that's the plan.  Any comments would be much appreciated;  I will pass them
on to the powers that be.  There should be very little trouble with crowding,
both because of this new system and because the Coopers are making a good deal
of new camping land available this year.  There will be more tent space than
there has been in the past.

In other news (you will like this, I think), the Woods Battle is in a
completely new piece of woods this year.  It's state park land;  if you go up
the causeway and then fail to make the left up toward the high meadows you
enter it.  There is a plug of brush there, and then the old railway path
resumes and runs for some distance.  It's a great area, and substantially
larger than the current woods.  My understanding is that all the old woods is
to be available for camping.

Hope that helps,
Magnus de Cnoc an Iora
Debatable Lands
