Date: 5 May 89 06:07:51 GMT
From: apple!well!hrh@rutgers.edu  (Harry Henderson)
Subject: Crowns and offices - do they mix?
Message-Id: <11529@well.UUCP>


Greetings from Hal Ravn:

Before we get too deeply into the question of Royalty holding offices,
I'd like to make a couple of comments.

Part of the problem here is that the amount of work--and length of time--
varies a good bit between Kingdoms.  Note that, for example, the West 
has 3 reigns a year (the only Kingdom to do so as far as I know), and
therefore our Kings and Queens serve for a *total* of only 6 months.

We also have Princes that are not heirs to the Kingdom thrones.  The
only other groups with experience that way are the Kingdoms that formed
by separating from existing Kingdoms.  As I understand, the East (isn't it?)
is about to form an internal Principality, but the West is the only Kingdom
with long-term experience this way.  The Prince's of the Mists and 
Cynagua (and--I presume--Oertha and Lochac) have 6-month reigns, for
a total of about 9 months official involvement.  They have rather fewer
demands on their that (outside observation) than the King and Queen.

Therefore, it seems to me that a King or Queen could well turn over
any but a Great Office of State to a Deputy (under supervision) for
the duration of a Reign and a Prince or Princess could probably do the
same--with the caveat that this also applies to Principality offices.

In Kingdoms with longer Regins--especially where the Crown Tourney is
held closely following Coronation--this may not be practical.

Perhaps all of the discussions on the Corpora should start with a
discussion about differences among the Laurel Kingdoms.  We're not
all *that* homogenous, you know.

