	A good question, and one that strains the limits of our
ability to act in persona.  Not being part of a group that 
is sensitive to such things (southern hillbillys being made fun of
but seldom laughed at, and the amerind side being too remote to
hurt on those few occations where I do run into that kind of prejudice) 
I can't tell how such stories would be taken.  The only solution that
comes to mind is to step out of persona for a moment to point out
that the following is a period tale that some may find offensive, 
but I can also understand why this is offensive to Lord Cariadoc.
Short of this I see only two real choices, to tell or not to tell.
(With the side note that censoring them would involve removing much
of the story in some cases, and censoring them by merely changing the
stereotypes involved isn't a solution.  I don't think either is aesthetically
pleasing to the storytelling side of *me*.)
	
	My personal inclination would be to go ahead and tell them.  If
need be, have someone 'planted' in the crowd to raise, if possible, these
objections in a (non-violent!) period manner.  You can then gage the
reaction of the crowd to the tale and to the person objecting and decide
if it is best to continue or move on to another tale.

	I think that storytellers in period, particularly ones outside of
their own country, faced something of the same problem.  There, however,
it would have been easier to shift the maligned group in the case of 
racist stories. (Sexist tales probably required no such modification...
unless you were performing for Elisabeth!)(And I'm not even certain then.)
In period the storyteller would have simply chosen different tales for
different crowds.  I fear that you'll have to do something simular here too.


)One consequence is that, when I recite a poem (by Malkin) containing
)a reference to Odin, I immediately follow it by an "explanation"
)interpreting Odin as a Djinn or Demon, who the Northmen falsely
)believe to be a God--not only is such an explanation (I think)
)appropriate to my persona, it may be necessary to cover myself
)against accusations of heresy or blasphemy. On one occasion I got a
)very hostile reaction from a Norse persona, along the lines of "I
)don't say nasty things about your god, you shouldn't say them about
)mine." It was fairly clear that the reaction was coming out of 20th
)century ideas of religious toleration. The question I want to raise
)is whether expressing intolerant views on religion is appropriate as
)a reflection of what our personae would have been like, 
)or whether it is behavior that should be self-censored so
)as not to offend modern sensibilities.
	
	Again, I would say that the period storyteller had much the same
problem.  There are a lot of Norse persona's in the SCA, would a period
storyteller use those words knowing that the crowd contained some of these
hot-headed, dangerous (and potentially cannibalistic!) people?  Perhaps
phrasing it so that the heathen can laugh knowingly at your ignorance of
the power of Odin while making it clear that your faith is in Allah would
be an appropriate responce.

 
)David Friedman (Cariadoc)

