Subject: Dolmetsch

Margaret MacDubhSidhe asks about "Dances of England and France, 1450-
1600" by Mabel Dolmetsch.  Well, use it if you can't find anything
else but...
Dolmetsch was a very early redactor of period dances.  There wasn't
much prior research for her to work from, and she invented a lot.
It is probably better to use her material than not dance at all,
but Arbeau isn't that hard to come by or make some sense out of.

It would be better to track down some of the simpler period sources
and interpret for yourself - it isn't all that hard, and the learning
process can be quite interesting.  I would suggest finding a copy
of "Orchesography" by Thoinot Arbeau (it is available in paperback
from Dover) or "Dancing at the Inns of Court" by James Cunningham,
which contains the original manuscript for a number of almans and
pavans, as well as commentary, as a good place to start.  I don't
have my list of sources here at work to give publishers and such,
but these shouldn't be too hard to track down.

One of the interesting classes promised (threatened?) for a collegium
to be held in Storvik (Washington, DC) in September is to distribute
the text of a period dance to several different people/groups of people,
for each to interpret separately.  Then we will see how similar/different
each version is.  This should be lots of fun, and very educational...


