In article <8905051428.AA02132@tut.cis.ohio-state.edu>, WANDERER%MTUS5.BITNET@CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU (Karl Jacobs) writes:
> I am cosidering creating a suit of boiled leather with a twist. To  keep it as
> cool as possible at Pennsic, I thought of inserting canvas tarp grommets at
> intervals to increase air circulation around the body.  Has anyone done this
> before? 

Never done it before with holes, but as one who bakes inside his
leather body armor this sounds like a good idea to me. My only
concern would be whether adding enough grommets to do any good 
temperature-wise wouldn't add too much extra weight.

> Anybody made boiled leather and want to give me advice?

Quick run-down on how to boil leather (at least my technique).
Make a double-boiler type arrangement with pans that your
leather pieces will fit in. Use paraffin as the wax. I added
Stearic Acid (I think that's right) as a hardener so that the
wax won't leach out of the leather later due to heat. I've
also heard of people using candle-wax hardener, but I don't
know what this is. Bring the double boiler up to a temperature
where the pariffin is melted (it will become very clear) but not
boiling. Submerge the leather piece completely in the wax until
the bubbles stop. At this point the pores in the leather are
full (if I understand the principles correctly). Take the piece
out, let the wax drip off, then form it and place it in the
freezer. You may have to put it in the freezer briefly before
forming it as leather directly out of the boiler is very soft
and won't hold a shape. Some hints: Dye the leather first, and
experiment with some test pieces for color. My cheap leather 
didn't take the black dye too well, but the Cuir Bouilli
(boiling in wax) process really made the black deep and dark.
Second: Pieces too large to fit entirely in the wax can be
worked through from one side to another as long as each area
is in the wax long enough to stop bubbling (tiny bubbles btw).
> Does anyone kno
> w where I can get nickel(-plated)  canvas tarp grommets and leather rivets?
> Tandy only carries the brass versions, and I would like to use something with a
> silvery look.  Thanks in advance to those who can help me here.

Most sewing/material places have silver grommets although these
tend to be on the small size. I've gotten large silver grommets at
army surplus places. Look in the tent area...

>           In Service to the Dream,
>              V'larishtaal the Wanderer

This has gotten long, but let me close with a plug for Cour Bouilli
armor. I made mine maybe 6 years ago and it has held up
tremendously since. It is still very hard and provides as much 
protection as steel. If you don't have the skills or facilities
to work in metal, boiled leather is a great alternative. It is
even a valid first choice for much early and transitional period
armour.

