Date: 4 May 89 16:45:07 GMT
From: joshua@paul.rutgers.edu  (Joshua Mittleman)
Subject: Re: Regarding the new _Corpora_
Message-Id: <May.4.12.45.06.1989.9163@paul.rutgers.edu>

Lord Sirhan al Siani, aka Diablu, writes:
 
> I think that as long as the name has the "proper period and cultural ambience
> it should be passed.  Requiring documentation for persona names, I feel, is
> unnecessarily limiting, especially for newcomers to the society.  I had
> a very difficult time trying to get my name passed (it took me eight years).

I must disagree, my lord Sirhan.  The SCA is a medieval recreation
group.  It is perfectly reasonable to require each member of the
Society to conform to that definition at least to the extent of taking
the effort to choose a correctly formed, medieval name.  For someone
new to the SCA, this process requires about an hour's work checking a
history book or two, or a good name dictionary, and finding a name
which is existed the Middle Ages.  The problems arise, almost
uniformly, when people fail to do take that basic step.

An additional problem arises from the phrase "proper period and
cultural ambience".  How on Earth is this to be defined?  The current
College of Arms policy boils down, essentially, to "if you can
document it, it's acceptable.  If not, then not."  What is an
objective definition of "proper period and cultural ambience"?  Who
gets to decide if it "sounds medieval"?  The choice really appears to
come to having standards for medieval names, or having no standards at
all. 

Finally, I would like to note that you have stated a common
misconception:

> Also, the process of naming people is a very subjective thing.  Parents have
> been known to make up names for their children simply because the combination
> of letters sounded good.  Why then, should we be restricted from using the
> same process in choosing our names?  So long as people are not claiming to
> actually be the fictitious character I do not see the harm in using the name.

In modern America, it is certainly the case that parents can name
their children anything they want, and often make-up names with no
basis at all.  This was not the case in most times, in most places.
In particular, it is not true today in many countries, where a child's
name may need legal approval (France, USSR, Argentina, and any who is
Catholic), nor was it true in medieval Europe.  Names formed a
distinct class of words in each language, and it was very rare for
names to be added to that stock.  There was some variation, but it was
not random: It followed certain linguistic rules in each culture.  As
the SCA is trying to recreate those cultures, their naming systems are
something we should at least try to use.

	Arval the Herald.
