Date: Fri 5 May 89 04:44:22
From: "]ke Eldberg" <CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>
Subject: Names and citizenship
Message-Id: <890505044422.17.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>

Diablu (Dwayne Herron) writes:

>I think that as long as the name has the "proper period and cultural ambience"
>it should be passed.

The question is what is meant by "proper period and cultural ambience". This is
a fudge sentence that could mean almost anything. In my interpretation, it
covers the system we have now. You don't need to document that there existed
a person with exactly the name you want. Spelling is optional. But in a dif-
ferent interpretation, the above fudge could open the way for monstrosities.
There are enough of those already...

>Requiring documentation for persona names, I feel, is unnecessarily limiting,
>especially for newcomers to the society. I had a very difficult time trying
>to get my name passed (it took eight years).

Well, after eight years, you were hardly a newcomer any more. Getting names
past is a problem if you can't document it - but it's not a treshold for
newcomers unless they themselves choose to see it that way. The potential for
problems will remain as long as we have *any* rules about names, because there
will always be someone who wants something that's not allowed. The present
rules have the good side effect of forcing people to learn a little about
medieval names, if they want to register one. But nobody is forced to do that
in order to participate in the SCA.

>Also, the process of naming people is a very subjective thing. Parents have
>been known to make up names for their children simply because the combination
>of letters sounded good. Why then, should we be restricted from using the
>same process in choosing our names?

Again, I disagre There were strong traditions about names in the Middle Ages,
much stronger than today. Parents would choose the names carefully according
to their cultural traditions. Sometimes the name was thought to have an
almost magical meaning, giving the child the qualities of the person they
were being named after (or of an animal, e.g. Biorn = bear). Other practices
existed, such as the Germanic/Scandinavian variation system (see my article
in the Compleat Anachronist #36).

If we are here to re-create and learn about medieval culture, then we should
follow those traditions as best we can. I can see so reason not to do it,
except perhaps if a person is not interested in the middle ages, in which case
he/she doesn't belong here anyway.

>So long as people are not actually claiming to be the fictitious character I 
>do not see the harm in using the name.

Well, if I meet a "Gandalf Grey" or an "Arwen Undomiel", I will certainly
think of the fictional characters, regardless of who the bearer of the name
is claiming to be. The reference to the book is there and cannot be avoided.
I prefer to keep my elves and hobbits in the local Tolkien group, and to 
make a difference between fictional characters from medieval literature and
the "real people" that we ourselves are supposed to be.

>I feel that one should be allowed to be considered the subject of the
>kingdom that one calls home.

I would like to agree. Every person has a place where he considers himself
to belong. American military personnel who live in Europe remain Americans.
People will not resign their citizenship until they feel more at home
somewhere else.

But medieval kingdoms were not nations in the modern sense. Nobility was
international. For a nobleman, the most important fact was *who* his liege
lord was. A "foreigner" was a person with bonds of fealty to the king of
another realm. And fealty had consequences other than keeping the emotional
bonds to one's homeplace.

There are four options, if you are living in Awayland but feel like you
belong to Homeland:
a.) Swear fealty to the king of Homeland only.
b.) Swear fealty to the king of Awayland only.
c.) Swear fealty to both kings.
d.) Don't swear fealty.

The a.) option means you remain a foreigner in Awayland. You cannot hold
office there, or receive peerage from its king. Also, this option would
not be open to just anyone. An Awayish noble couldn't just decide to
swear fealty to the king of Homeland, in order to escape the Awayish
king - that would be treason.
In the a.) option, the noble woulbe in trouble if there was a war with
Homeland. He would suddenly find himself an enemy of the land where he is
living, his property will be confiscated and himself will be taken hostage.

The b.) option is the least complicated one. The noble simply becomes a
subject of a different country, with all the duties and privileges 
appertaining thereunto.

The c.) option makes the noble a legal problem. Both kings now have claims
on his services. The natural cause for them is to try and win the noble
over to their side, and to mistrust him if they can't. In war, the noble
had better stay neutral lest he commit treason. (Witness Enguerrand de
Coucy who held lands in England and France at the same time, and stayed
neutral in the war).

The d.) option means you are in no-man's-land. Without fealty there is
no privilege. No office, no peerage. You don't belong anywhere.

So much for the middle ages. In SCA terms, implementing these possibilities
would be nice but impractical. On the theoretical side, it would result in
so many multiple "citizenships" that few people would know where anybody
belonged. It would get the kingdoms all mixed up. In a place like Drachen-
wald, where the people are drawn from all over the USA, I fear it would
mean chaos. (Witness the difficulties of the crusades, when knights from
all over Europe found themselves together in Palestine, but all served
different kings and took this as a licen not to serve or obey the local
authorities. Finally, a new kingdom had to be created to sort this out.)

It might be feasible to allow peers to swear fealty to any king they
choose. But it would not work with officers. Allowing double fealties
could be left up to the sovereign. As I said, I would like to agree, but
the whole idea smacks of something that could create an impossibly
tangled "legal" and feudal situation. Very period, but not good for the SCA
as a society.

William de Corbie
