While not directly applicable to the posting above ...

	Prior to a baronial arts and sciences competition, the various
powers that be kept exhorting us lowlifes to create and enter projects.
While all well and good in and of itself, there were also some people
bragging about their entries to the point that us lowlifes on highly
limited funds, barely experienced in the society, and not too talented
in such things besides, knew that we had absolutely no chance of winning.
To answer this crying need for appropriate competition, Slag von Zeig
and myself crafted "The Masterpiece." Bending a length of 9 ga galvinized
fence bracing wire into a 1" split ring was the easy part. For we then
had to carefully flatten the ends with erratic blows with a ball-pein
hammer. By this point, the ring was more than a bit eccentric, and we
distorted it further by overlapping the ends. With the utmost artistry
and a dull drill bit, we pierced the overlapping irregular lobes. After
repeated attempts at forming a rivet from 14 ga steel wire failed, we
put a length through the holes, and hammered the living bejabers out of
the whole assembly. This we dubbed "The Masterpiece" and adding a quickly
scrawled note reading: "They had rivited chain-mail in the Medieval Ages,
and this here is one." We then proceeded to show it to our friends, who
ooh-ed and aww-ed over it. We entered it in the arms and armor part of
the competition and pointed it out with great fanfare to acquaintences
from far and wide. Finally, we celebrated long and loud over our "narrow
loss" to a "fine, fine, project" at post-revel.

	The key was that we presented it in as serious of a manner as
the hucksters in "The Emperor's New Clothes" and it became a game for
all who became involved. Critical comments as, "What wonderful gouges!
Did you perchance use vice-grips?" basically made it a fun time for
us who couldn't do well in the "real" competition, and we too had
something to celebrate at post revel. As an aside, all the judges but
one recognized the nature of our entry and made humorous observations
about it. I entered a well-made, but uninspired coif. Slag had some
other "serious" project as well.


More to the point ...

	Perhaps the resources of the fisher-folk could help the poor
soul with a coif sans documentation? I displayed mine without such
paperwork a number of years ago when that was not particularly damning
for such things that were regaurded as being of "common knowlege," so
I'm afraid that I can't really help on that one.

