Message-Id: <AYLlmry00Uw-Q3i2NS@andrew.cmu.edu>
Date: Wed,  3 May 89 11:37:27 -0400 (EDT)
From: Dani Zweig <haste+@andrew.cmu.edu>
Subject: Pennsic Campsite Allocation Policy

Here's what I've heard about this year's plans to allocate campsites at
Pennsic.

IMPORTANT NOTE:  What you are reading now is third-hand information
about a policy which is not yet official.  I would rate it as reasonably
reliable rumor.  I am posting what I've heard for your information, but
would strongly advise against people doing more than talking about it
until more official word is forthcoming.

1.  Pennsic officially begins August 12th.  On August 6th, everyone
currently camping at the Coopers' campground will be asked to move to
the battlefield.  In other words, NO BENEFIT will result from camping
there from the beginning of June, or even the beginning of August.

2.  A lottery will be held.  On August 6th and 7th anyone who wishes may
enter the lottery on behalf of a group.  First chosen from the lottery
gets first choice of campsite, second chosen gets second choice, etc. 
(A large map will be available to aid in this process.)  People are free
-- indeed encouraged -- to make private arrangements such as trading
sites, posting notices saying "please don't ask for this spot because
our group has been camping here for fifteen years", etc.  If they can.

3.  Only one person need show up for each group in the lottery.  (A
group may be any size, and is expected to take an appropriately sized
piece of land.)  That person will have to pay the $3/day or whatever
camping fee, but the rest of the group will not, till they show up.

4.  HOWEVER, there will be a *fee* of $5 per person for each group in
the lottery.  So if you're putting in for a twenty-person campsite you
must *pay* $100.  The money is not a deposit.  It is an extra charge for
the privilege of reserving a good site.  All money paid into the lottery
goes directly into the Building Fund.  (An extra $5/person isn't that
much, but it *should* discourage people from claiming too much land on
spec.)

5.  The tentative plan is for there to be a tiered lottery.  That is,
first there will be a lottery for large groups (tentatively defined as
over thirty people) and then another one for small groups.  The
reasoning is that there are a lot of good campsites which are
inappropriate for large groups, and that this will avoid problems of
small groups setting up in the middle of a large field and making it
unusable for a larger group.  (This part of the plan seems somewhat
abuse-prone to me.)

6.  On August 12th, the autocrat will come around to make sure that
nobody's taken too much land, and to ask those who have to pull back and
make room for latecomers.  To facilitate this, the number of tents which
will be at the campsite must already be on the ground at that time.  Not
necessarily set up, but there.  (This part of the plan seems impractical
to me.)

So there it is.  It's certainly a better plan than last year's.  It's a
composite of a number of the plans that were suggested in the wake of
last year's 'experience', and addresses some of the issues
intelligently.  My opinion is that whether it will work or not depends
on the degree to which the autocrat has the time, inclination and
ability to administer it fairly and creatively, and the degree to which
people do or do not try to exploit loopholes in the system.

