Message-Id: <sYLm1Xy00Uw-03i2gP@andrew.cmu.edu>
Date: Wed,  3 May 89 11:53:07 -0400 (EDT)
From: Dani Zweig <haste+@andrew.cmu.edu>
Subject: Pennsic Archery War Points

Here's what I've heard concerning archery at the War this summer.  Don't
take it as gospel until you've heard it from the mouth of a horse of an
appropriate color.

There will be a clout shoot and a charging-man shoot, both slightly
different from those of previous years.  The clout shoot will be a
ten-yard diameter circle at a range of 100 yards.  (Slightly larger than
last year's, at a longer range.)  (For those who aren't familiar with
this shoot, the circle is a wall of hay bales about two feet high,
representing a castle wall.  One point is scored for every arrow shot
within this circle in thirty seconds.  I believe that arrows hitting the
front of the front hay bales or the tops of the back bales are deemed to
have bounced off while those hitting the back of back bales or the tops
of the front bales are deemed to have gone in, but I might have the tops
reversed.)

The charging-man shoot this year will include *six* targets, at 70, 60,
50, 40, 30 and 20 yards, each consisting of the silhouette of a man. 
(In previous years it's been a viking, and an arrow hitting anywhere but
the axe or the small shield has counted as a point.)  I'm told this will
also be a 30-second shoot.

I have personal doubts about the latter shoot.  For one thing, it seems
more practical to me, if there are six targets, to make it a six-arrow
shoot (one at each range) than a timed one.  For another, I'm not sure
how practical the setup will be in terms of everyone on the line being
able to get a reasonable shot at each target -- some of the angles will
be *real* strange.

Well, time to start practicing.  *We'll* practice, if it ever stops
raining :-)

