I think the issue here is names, not personae.  The SCA
does not require a persona for participation.  All we want
is an *attempt* at garb. 

In particular, I think the issue here is REGISTRATION of names.  
In the SCA, you can call yourself whatever you want, as long
as it is not presumptuous or otherwise offensive, regardless of whether
it is authentic.  What I think the BoD is concerned with is whether
you can register (with the Heralds) a name that is made up, taken
from Tolkien, etc.

Since registration of a name is not required for participation,
it seems to me that this is not a barrier to new members.
And, of course, your local heralds should be there to help
you when you choose a name to register, so inability or unwillingness
to do research should not be a barrier to registering a name.
The name you register is that name by which you will be
called up into court, but need not have any relation to what
people call you, or to your persona-l fantasies, etc.

Some heralds, well, I anyway, find it puzzling that people should
want to register Elvish names, random names, and other stuff,
when so many beautiful and authentic names exist.  

>>Banishment (the Steward is especially interested in input on this topic);
>>under what conditions it should be implemented, and how.

>Fisrt I've heard on this topic, can someone clue me in???  Are
>you as a person, or you as a persona, banished?

Fortunately, it does not happen often.  It is very serious, and, of course,
applies to the real-life person, not their persona, if any.
(We wouldn't want some crook who gets banished to come back under
a new SCA name.)

