Date: Tue,  2 May 89 00:33:21 EDT
From: "Pandora B. Berman" <CENT@AI.AI.MIT.EDU>
Subject: SCA weddings
Message-ID: <589155.890502.CENT@AI.AI.MIT.EDU>

Eowyn Eilonwy of Alewife Brook gives greetings from Carolingia to all who
read these words, and especially to Ulfin of Wyrmgeard, who seeks advice
on weddings.

I have attended three SCA weddings that I can recall (as opposed to
modern-world weddings of friends in the SCA), and will try to recollect
their peculiarities for you.

The first occurred several years back (perhaps a decade by now -- one loses
track), between Lord Taran of Windy Hill and Lady Lark of Esherwood, both
of Carolingia (Boston area).  Their SCA wedding was held sometime after
their modern one, as part of a revel here, in a hall of no special
significance.  As I recall, both principals and their attendants were
attired in fancy new court garb, and somehow each was led forward to kneel
on pillows before the assembled crowd -- and, come to think of it, probably
before our Baron, since this may well have taken place as an adjunct to
Baronial Court.  While the bride and groom knelt, facing each other I
think, the heads of their respective households took turns offering
promissory blessings.  It went something like this: Baron Steffan ap
Cennydd, head of House Silverwing (to which Taran belonged) offered to set
up their first son to train to be a knight; then Baroness Kathryn Goodwyn,
head of House Goodwyn (to which Lark belonged), offered to set up their
first daughter with proper gentle training and a good marriage.  Then
Steffan tried to top that by offering something for their second son....
    By the time Steffan and Kathryn had reached about the fourth of each
type of offspring, Taran begged them to stop, pointing out that while
he welcomed the opportunity to inherit from his kin, he would prefer to
wait until they died before cleaning them out completely -- he's a herald,
so he put this more wittily than I can recall.
    Then Cardinal Lord Michael of Winterskeep (who holds no ecclesiastical
rank in the modern world, as far as I know), spoke a short time on standard
(dare I say canonical) wedding topics, and then I believe they gave each
other vows before the assembled company.  I apologize that I cannot recall
more, but it -was- quite some time ago.

The next was still some 4 or so years ago, the wedding of Lord Harold von
Auerbach and Anne (I've forgotten her full SCA name), both of Stonemarche
(NH -- well, technically at that time they were both from one of the shires
which preceded Stonemarche, because the NH shires combined to form that
barony only a year and a half ago).  Their wedding was held as part of an
All Saints' Day revel in that shire -- I believe some time after their
modern wedding.  This took place during the reign of Sebastian and
Sirillian, which will date it for anyone with a good memory, because the
King and Queen were there and he presided.
    The event was held in a small church, and most of the activity took
place in the hall under the sanctuary, but the wedding (and later, court)
occurred upstairs in the sanctuary.  For the wedding, we were all called to
come sit in the pews and bear witness.  Seats had been set up in front for
the participants, and the royalty were already there.  Harold and Anne, in
nice court garb I believe, came forward with a few attendants and asked the
King to recognize their marriage.  They presented a marriage contract
(presumably calligraphed by Harold, who's good at that sort of thing)
setting out the terms of the dowry and such, and swore that all the terms
which could be fulfilled before the ceremony (e.g. gifts of cattle) had
been.  Sebastian then spoke a few suitable words, explaining that a king
cannot cause or enforce a marriage, he can only recognize it, and I think
offering them non-sectarian good wishes.  I believe sometime in here Harold
and Anne spoke vows to each other.  Again, my memory of details fails due
to the passage of time.

Most recently, a royal wedding occurred in the East.  A year and a half
ago, when Gavin Kilkenny of Kilcarrin won the Crown for his (modern-world
wife of a few years) Sedalia MacNair, he swore at Crown Tourney that he
would marry that lady (SCA-wise) before taking the throne.  At their
Coronation, a year since, the wedding occurred.  As usual for the East, the
outgoing monarchs held court and gave out awards and such, and when they
asked if any further business existed, Gavin came forward (with an armed
honor guard) to claim the Crown.  The various appropriate folk swore
publicly that Gavin had won the previous Crown Tourney and was the Royal
Heir, and despite the outgoing King's recitation of the burdens of the
Crown, Gavin was still willing to become King -- indeed, he swore on the
Stone of Scone (or a reasonable papier-mache' facsimile thereof, carried
into court and deposited before the thrones for this purpose) that he
would.
    But Gavin's predecessor (one of the Morghuns?  I've lost track) noted
that an apparently unfulfilled condition of his accession was his vow to
marry Sedalia.  Gavin stated he was prepared to marry her then and there,
and Sedalia came forth attended by numerous ladies in waiting, so the King
directed them to wed immediately according to their "barbarous northern
customs".  What I recall of the wedding (I hadn't slept the night before,
so I was a bit woozy) was that Gavin and Sedalia both stood on the "stone",
and Earl Sebastian Nightwind (one of Sedalia's longest friends in the SCA)
came forward wearing a baldric of MacNair tartan and claimed to be the
representative of the MacNair of MacNair (Sedalia's presumed clan chief),
and to bring word from that worthy that this member of his clan was in fact
allowed to proceed with this wedding.  There was some mention of dowry, at
which point the ladies in waiting all displayed the lengths of fine cloth
and fancy trim they had been carrying.  Then Gavin and Sedalia spoke their
vows while still standing on the stone, and then they were crowned.  Soon
thereafter, the flunkies returned to remove the "stone" so the nobles
wishing to swear fealty to the Crown could do so unobstructed.

I regret that I cannot give you further details of these occurences;
mayhap someone else with better memory will be able to fill the gaps I
have left.  Good luck and best wishes to you and your lady wife..

