To Cynthia from Isenfir, who wanted to know what to bring to Pennsic:

The best list I've ever found is the one in the Known World Handbook; Arastorm
the Golden wrote the article, and though I can't remember its title, I do
remember that "Waggonloading for the Compleat Idiot" is right next to it.  It's
worth the $$$ to get the Handbook from the Stock Clerk, or send me private
email and I'll send you an extensive list of the goodies I bring.

The basics are these: 3 or 4 warm-weather outfits, something for cool weather,
something waterproof, a tent, a sleeping bag, lots of money (especially if you
plan to eat at the Inn rather than cook your own), a box of garbage bags, your
feast gear, and a large water container.  Are you camping with a household or
a territorial group?  Do you have access to any communal supplies?  We can
talk about this offline and save everyone the disk space, unless there is
sufficient interest to make this public.

To Robyyan Torr D'Elandris and everyone else who's been thinking about meeting
at Pennsic:

I too would love to meet the faces behind the messages; I know most of the
East Kingdom posters, but would love to see the rest of you too!  Please don't
open another can of worms on my account, but was it really decided once and
for all that we "netters" would hang fishnet around the camp so that we might
be recognized?  (I wander a lot; it would be a sad thing if one of you came
to visit me, saw the net, and I was out looking for you!)

Thursday night is traditionally the Archers' Social and Friday night is usually
Clann Party time, but I'll happily come to a gathering at any other time.
Those are just my suggestions; if the Rialto gathering happened on one of 
those nights I'd try to come anyway.  (I might have to "do" someone's SCAdian
wedding on Friday, too.  Please try to avoid Friday night if at all possible.)
What do the rest of you think?  It really isn't too early to plan; everyone
else who has stuff to do is already talking about it!

To Padraig Cosfada o Ulster: Paisano!  Glad to hear from you!

I actually had sources -- none of them in the fiction bins -- for what we
found on Celtic weddings.  I have to get the bibliography from Seosamh since
he has all the books, but I'll email the list to you as soon as I'm able.

We didn't find anything on Druidic ritual per se; our ceremony itself was a
construction based loosely on what we know from the symbolism and even more
loosely on modern ritual.  We actually announced the nature of the ceremony to
our guests, in order not to offend on either a religious basis or on the basis
of authenticity -- we wanted to construct a ceremony that might have been.  I
will include what we found, and where.

We did find a lot about Brehon laws on marriage; they came from a couple of
excellent sources (albeit 19th-century ones).  Because of the oral nature of
ancient Irish record-keeping and the number and savagery of the English laws
and actions against Irish ways, a frightening percentage of the knowledge is
lost.  There are few -- if any-- primary sources from ancient Ireland, though
we have some from people who had been to Ireland and wrote about it.

This posting is long enough.  Talk back to me!  I'd like to hear from other
Celts who've engaged in research.

