Date: Tue, 2 May 89 10:23:34 PDT
From: Kevin Karplus <karplus@azuki.ucsc.edu>
Message-Id: <8905021723.AA01111@azuki.ucsc.edu>
Subject: Lady Niccola's challenge

I'm sorry I won't be in the East to see this year's Ice Dragon Pentathalon.
Here are some tips on how to Lady Niccola.

First decide whether you want to beat Lady Niccola in one category, or overall.
It is easier to beat her at one thing (she, after all, has been working on
several projects, so can't spend as much time on any single project), but it
would be more satisfying to beat her overall.  The easiest category to beat 
someone is "miscellaneous"--research an area no one has been working in, and
add a new facet to SCA re-creation.  Of course, the judges will probably know
nothing about the field, so you'll have to back up the 3"x5" card with lots
of documentation.

If you decide to go for broke and try for an overall victory, you will probably
need more than the minimum five categories.  Have a couple of extra entries,
to protect yourself against a really superb entry from someone who is only
entering one contest.  I'm sure Lady Niccola is preparing more than five
entries.  Some of your entries will probably have to be in a field in which
you are not already expert, which means you'll have to do extra research 
and make some practice pieces.  One of the great things about the Ice Dragon
arts competition is the way is induces people to try things they wouldn't
otherwise have done.  Many Myrkfaelinnites have acquired new skills and hobbies
preparing for Ice Dragon.

Use good materials.  If you are poor, choose projects that can be made out of 
wood, steel, or other fairly inexpensive materials.  Don't try to fake 
gold, silver, and other expensive materials--the results come out looking like
stage props.  The biggest problems with materials are often in the garb
competitions, in which flashy outfits are sometimes made out of low-quality
synthetics.  You're better off with a well-researched, well-constructed garment
(perhaps from an earlier period or a lower social class) made out of sturdy
cotton or wool.  The judges do notice details like hand stitching, so try
not to take too many short cuts.

It helps a lot to meet regularly with other artisans.  One reason that the
Myrkies take more than their share of Ice Dragon prizes is that they regularly
get together, both in the official arts meetings and in Mac's shop.
When several people are working on similar projects, they swap tips about
how they managed to solve technical problems.  The extra enthusiasm often
gets people past the depression of a botched attempt or an apparently endless
project.

I hope that these hints help someone (other than Lady Niccola) win.
I'm only sorry I won't be there to see the competition--it sounds like it'll be
the best year yet.

Kevin Karplus	(karplus@azuki.ucsc.edu)
Knud Kaukinen (AoA, Maunche)

(In case you're wondering about my credentials in offering this advice,
I did win an Ice Dragon Pentathalon once, thanks mainly to the urging of Lady
Niccola, and the support that Myrkfaellin gives to fledgling artisans.)



