Greetings!

Lots of little comments, this time around...

LONGSHIPS:  Large-scale model longships have been built and burned several
times in Trimaris, usually for a simulated Norse funeral.  Most notable
amongst these was the longship burned at the end of the first reign on Duke
Baldar Longstriter.

MUSEUM REPLICAS, LTD.:  Being in the South, their stuff is readily available,
and I see it all the time.  For the most part, their blades are very good.  I
regard Museum Replicas as the most reasonable alternative for large blades,
for SCA'ers.

WEDDINGS:  I wholeheartedly agree with everything that's been said about
imagination and planning beforehand.  In my experience, SCA weddings can be a
lot of fun.  In the instances where the SCA wedding and the mundane wedding
were coincidental,  potential tensions between the SCA and mundane guests were
eased by the bride and groom simply making sure that there were a few people
whose sole task was the performance of introductions.  It got everyone talking
to each other, which really helped.  A good example (and a quick anecdote as
well) is provided by describing some of the arrangements for the wedding of
Lady Caitlinn Emrys and Sir Eric von Rabenscold, now Baron and Baroness
Wyvernwoode.

The wedding was essentially Cavalier, and was held at an event.  It was the
mundane as well as the SCA wedding.  As I remember it, those gentles who
comprised the formal escort during the ceremony (including providing the arch
of swords for the recessional) acted as ushers.  They introduced the bride and
groom's parents and other assorted relations around, and seated everyone.  The
mundane guests were seated together, which made it easier on their nerves.
:-)  The only hitch I ever heard about concerned Lady Caitlin's father, when
he was being seated (and who told me this himself after the ceremony).  He was
escorted by Elina Thrymsfostra (surname/sp?), who was dressed in male garb
(including rapier), and who was part of the formal escort.  Cat's father
looked down to see that Elina's arm was bent, which deepened somewhat his
already-existing quandry as to whether to take Elina as a male or female in
this instance (since he fully understood what was going on):  was she offering
him her arm? Was *"he"* offering "his" arm?  What was the correct course of
action?  How to proceed?

Then Cat's father realized that Elina was simply resting her wrist on the
pommel of her rapier, and *that's* why her arm was bent...

One other note, prompted by Awilda Halfdane's remarks in Dig. #317:  I have
read (although I freely admit that I forget where) in early America that
affianced couples were allowed to keep warm by cuddling together in bed.  This
was done with the parents' knowledge, and was supposedly a fairly common
custom.  No doubt little imagination is needed to figure out what some of the
results of this custom were...

YANG THE NAUSEATING:  Will always be remembered for his famous exchange of
remarks with one Crown:

                 Crown:  "You speak *treason*, sir!"

                 Yang:  "*Fluently!*"

BAWDY STUFF/CARIADOC'S POSER:  First, my compliments to Li Kung Lo for his
recent remarks.

All SCA performers have a number of things to consider when choosing a piece,
and all performers should try to maintain a sense of appropriateness with
respect to time and situation when making their choices.  I think this is
fairly clear, and that everyone recognizes it.

There are two aspect, however, which are in my opinion often overlooked:
degree of comprehension; and "environmental programming."  By the former, I am
referring to the fact that, since the gentles sitting out there listening
represent interests in many different cultures, many will be unfamiliar with
any given culture's style of presentation.  As an extreme example, lots of
European types would be bored silly by a samisen player, no matter how fine
the performance.  Lack of familiarity in various and sundry forms (not knowing
the language, for instance) makes comprehension, and therefore appreciation,
difficult.  I wish it noted, however, that I also think that exposure to new
and different things does one good, so I personally try not to be pay
attention (assuming that I can hear and that my meal isn't interrupted for too
long... :-) ).

By the latter, I meant two things:  1) like it or not, we do not completely
park our 20th Century sensibilities at the door when we attend an event-- they
are ingrained in each of us at a sub-conscious level; 2) what was appropriate
in the context of one culture might not have been appropriate in the context
of another, even if they were contemporary.  This is the bind I think Duke
Cariadoc gets caught in.  There have already been several excellent
suggestions made for working around this situation.  To them I would add
another:  if one wishes to remain completely in persona (a la' Cariadoc's
description) have oneself introduced to the audience by another party.  The
party performing the introduction could, for instance, introduce Cariadoc
as an Islamic story-teller, working in a few brief comments explaining the
attitudes the audience is about to encounter.  A warning about the
explicitness of the material (or whatever) could also be worked in.  It could
be *great* schtik, serious or funny!

MEAD/TANNIN:  Apart from tea and North Florida ground water, the three best
sources of tannin I know are:  acorns, acorns, and acorns.  However, acorns
are *much* more potent than tea as far as tannin goes.

You might want to try this:  gather *lots* of acorns.  Remove the caps, put
them in a big pot of cold water, and boil.  The water will turn brown,
indicating the leaching of the tannin in the acorns.  You can use some of this
water in your mead (or whatever).  Change the water; boil again.  Do this
until the water no longer turns brown.  Dry the acorns; toast if need be by
spreading on a cookie sheet in roasting at 400-425 degress for about 15 min or
so.  Grind acorns into flour, combine with unbleached white flour, and make
into bread.  You will have a very period peasant's bread, as well as all the
tannin you could want.

SIR KENELME DIGBY:   I am *sick and tired* of not owning a copy of Digby!!
Can anyone suggest where I can get one?  There are excellent bookstores
locally, so if someone can name a good source, I should be able to order one
no problem.  Thank you!


