A while back, Lord Kwellend-Njal posted information about a
publication called Early Period.  I followed up on his info with a
letter to the publishers, and found out that the magazine still
exists, only the address had changed.  I subscribed and ordered the
sets of back issues and I must say, I'm very impressed!  

Basically, the articles deal with pre-1066 topics of interest to
persons with early period personae in the SCA or similar organizations
(quote from the cover).  All articles are published with sources
(Yay!), and the topics range from Viking Musical Instruments to 
Adapting Early Style Helms for SCA Fighting to Roman Women's
Hairstyles to Early Period Tents to Pronouncing Welsh to ... you get 
the idea.  I got those titles just by flipping through issues at
random; there's lots more.  Also included are recipes for feasts,
patterns for shoes and embroidery, etc.  This looks like a must for
anyone interested in early period personae and provides something hard
to find for early period, documentation!  

Subscriptions are $10.00 per year (comes out quarterly), and each of
the two sets of back issues is also $10.00 (there are 10 back issues).
Ten bucks may seem steep for a quarterly, but each issue is about 30 
pages long.  It is available from:
		David & Rebecca Wendelken
		P.O. Box 631
		Rome GA 30161

I was told that the next issue is at the printers now, so I'll be 
looking for it and will post a review when it comes.  

Disclaimer: I have no connection with this publication other than
being glad I discovered it (Thanks, Kwellend!).  

