I was going to answer this by email, since I wasn't sure quite what was
being asked, but my response bounced, so I'll just post it.:


Before moving on to the heart of your question, I'd like to comment on
the first
part by noting that a) It is better to sing.  b) There is a surprising
amount of
good period material.  c) A good compromise for a folk singer is to pull
out
material from the seventeenth and early-eighteenth centuries, as most of
the
audience will think them period and the ones who know better will
probably not
find them jarring.

As to sources for songs, I'm not quite sure what it is you are looking
for. 
Period ballads?  Songs with the right feel to them?  Simple melodies or
complete arrangements?  I am particularly interested in the traditional 
Child ballads, myself, so I'll give some comments about those.  The
definitive source for traditional melodies is Bertrand Bronson's "The
Singing
Tradition of Child's Popular Ballads" (1959-1972), which many good
libraries
will have.  Not too many of the tunes are period, but he identifies
those that
are.  And, as I suggested, slightly out of period is only slightly bad
:-).
There are a good many traditional ballads (See Francis James Child's "The
English and Scottish Popular Ballads") which do not come with tunes, but
you can
follow the period custom of stealing contemporary tunes (See Claude
Simpson's
"The British Broadside Ballad and Its Music") that seem to fit.  Note
that what
you'll generally find is a fairly unadorned melody line.  A warning
about the
traditional ballads:  The ones "everyone knows" are almost invariably
nineteenth
or late-eighteenth century.

I can give more specific comments if this is the sort of thing you were
asking
about.  If I've missed my mark, please give me some examples of what
you're
looking for.

