Message-ID:  <8904281352.aa03105@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

My Lord Cariadoc,

The way to survive as an entertainer basically means knowing your audience and
presenting a good mix of materials.  If children or other people of delicate
sensibility are present, drop out the more explicit material.  If you've got a
party of rip roaring drunks, the sentimental songs of love are unlikely to go
over well. An it's perfectly all right to make comments that are in persona
even if they are chauvinistic, as long as they are performed in such a way that
people realize it is the persona speaking, and they are not being insulted.  In
this way you can include tales that you don't approve of, for whatever reason,
but can present a variety of pieces suitable for a variety of tastes.

 Basically, remember that entertainment is like a dinner:  If every course 
included cinnamon, everyone would soon be tired of cinnamon, no matter how 
well they liked the spice.  Vary your material.  Tell a  mixture of tales,
with a little explanation to warn the audience of what's coming up.  "Next I'd
like to tell of lovestory that I have often heard your Frankish troubadors
perform,"  and "This is tale popular with some of the more wicked of my people,
perhaps you will find it amusing."  Such lines  let you, in persona, educate
people as well as entertain them. By such devices you can tell them when and
where a song was performed, and whether it's period or not.  Patter of this kind
provides a graceful link between pieces, and whether the audience realizes it
or not, they're learning something.

And by the way, I did not say the Horde was the first non-europeans, obviously
there were a few scattered about before then.  Only that the Dark Horde opened
the way for them.  It was after the Horde formed that SCA experienced a large
increase in non-Europeans, and people accepted the idea that non-europeans had
a place in the SCA. And the Horde does maintain it's patronage of belly dance,
the Horde dancers winning awards for their skills.  I will confess that I have
heard the Horde's version of the origin of belly dancing, but as it gyved with
what I remember  at one of my very first events, I accept it as basically
true, if biased account.

Yes, this all happened a long time ago, and everybody has thankfully mellowed
out a lot since then, and maybe it was really never more than a tempest in a
tea cup, but for the people immediately involved it certainly seemed important.

Yours in Service to Letting Dead Dogs Lie,
