Message-ID:  <8904291738.aa20587@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

Some gentles have written to suggest that if pearls were so popular in the
Middle Ages, they couldn't have been very valuable.  I would like to refute
that by calling their attention to the modern jewelry market.  

Today, diamonds are the most valuable gems, and diamonds are what the jewelry
stores sell, surpassing all other gems.  Human nature is not much changed, I'm
sure the kind of motivations that compell people to buy diamonds today
compelled people to buy pearls yesterday.

And pearls did have more uses that just their ornamental value,  I have seen
various recipes ascribing various magical properties to pearls.  Even today a
substance called "pearl creme" is being marketed on television as a way for
women to appear younger.  

Let me relate a few of the tales about pearls.  I have no idea how old some of
these ideas are, or how current they might have been in our period, but they
give you an idea of the mystique of the pearl.

Pearls maintian youth and beauty.  Cleopatra was supposed to have bathed in a
concoction made of ground pearls and mother's milk.

Pearls dropped in wine will disolve, and the resulting beverage can be drunk to
restore youth, vigor, and virility to men.

Pearls will nullify poison.  A pearl dropped in a glass of poisoned wine will
disolve, deactivating the poison.  

Pearls worn on the person will guard against disease and disaster, especially
water disasters.  

Pearls, if eaten whole, will make the eater wise.

Pearls, eaten whole, will prevent illness.

Pearls, worn on the person, gradually  change color to reveal the nature of the
wearer.  Pearls worn by pure persons will maintain their luster, pearls worn by
imperfect people will yellow and dull.

Some of these superstitions have basis in reality.  I have never tried it, but
from what I have read, vinegar is a strong enough acid to dissolve pearls.  And
pearls do maintain their luster better when worn regularly-the human skin
provides oil that maintains their moisture content.  On the other hand, I have
a necklace made of mother of pearl that has not yellowed noticeably in the years
I've had it, so maybe not.

Yours in Service to Pretty Things,
