In article <609508255.M1147@PBN33.Prime.COM> BB13093@pbn33.prime.com writes:
)     About fighting and training- there is a new Pike Company being
)formed here in the Barony of Carolingia.  Although I am very new to
)heavy list, I can see that this presents a whole new set of training
)problems - formation drills, etc.  Are there any other gentles on the
)Rialto who have participated in group efforts on the field of battle?
)Isn't it a bit ridiculous how FEW fighting units there are?  My
)understanding is that in period a much larger percentage of men on the
)field were "attached" to someone.  Correct me if I am wrong in this.
)What is it like to fight in a unit?
)                                      Nicolette Bonhomme

	I've fought in a few units, ranging from a two-man team to a unit
about thirty strong.  Only one of them, a five man team at the "Flail for
Ail" in the Steppes back in A.S. (doing conversion in my head) 18, had even
*fought* together before.  The larger units, at the last two Pennsics, were
units that came together there (though most of us joined earlier) and were
still effective (surprisingly so.)  

	A part of the problem has already been addressed, it is often
difficult to find a time when everyone *can* meet, even when they are
geographically close enough for this to be practical.  The Steppes was
a large Barony with plenty of people, but not that many fighters (though,
myself excluded, we more than made up for lack of numbers with quality!)
Other than there I have been in places where there really weren't enough 
us, (or anyone willing to organize...) to form a unit.  Dragon'smark 
had, throughout most of my time there, about 5 authorized fighters,
three of whom were Dark Horde, and going to fight with the Horde in
battle (not that the Horde doesn't accept help on occation, I've fought
with them and had a lot of fun.)  Here I find myself in the hinterlands of 
one Barony and with most of my friends in another, but basically, once again
not in a good situation to practice group tactics.  So I've always been
in the possition of finding a unit to attach myself to a the last minute.
(This isn't usually a problem, as people are almost always willing to 
accept another shieldman, and for some perverse reason I *enjoy* fighting
in a shield wall...)

	There *are* units in the area.  The Wetlands Alliance (I know 
Settmore Swamp and Carillion are in it, I think Rusted Woodlands and
Bhakail are as well) should be able to field a large force, and, from
the pictures I've seen, do field a reasonable one.  They could field
a *huge* (for our purposes) force, but various households, rather than
fighting with their Baron, prefur to fight as a separate unit.

	There are also units that seems to fight together well enough that 
they must be practicing together.  Calantir seems to get some practice
before the war, and the Barony of Septemptria (in Ealdamere, in the Midrealm)
look like they get some practice in.  And various households also seem to
practice some group tactics.

	I don't know that we are *that* off from period practice.  While
it sometimes looks (especially in modern battle diagrams) like there were
large units in the field in period battles, mostly these were constructed
much as ours are, from several small bands.  If I remember correctly,
one of the more potent units on the field at Hastings was the professional
core of Harald's army, numbering a whole (correct me if I'm wrong) 200 men.
The rest were were the southern fird, raised only in the last few weeks
to combat the incoming armies.  And maintaining this large a permanent
fighting force was unusual in period, normally the king would only
have his personal household.  This changed as time went on, but seems 
to be the pattern throughout our period.  Most of an army was individuals
fulfulling feudal duties, some with a small retinue.  The more powerful
the vassal, the larger the retinue.  To a certain extent, we are very
accurate in part of our recreation. :-)

	As for what it is like...  Perhaps another posting, this one has
gotten a bit long...

