From: discvr::norteman (B-) Go get yourself some cheap sunglasses)
Subject: Crashing at people's houses and SCA weddings

In one of the recent Digests, Nicolette Bonhomme asked about the etiquette of
crashing at people's houses.

When people crash at my house after an event, I'm usually far too trashed from
working at the event to be much in the way of company.  This is a shame, as I
live alone and love to entertain.  The people who've made the Guest Hall of
Fame after staying at my house include:

everyone who brought his/her own towel

the person who brought the raspberry coffee

the couple who bring bagels, cream cheese, and honey butter everywhere they go

all the sweethearts who washed mountains of coffee cups and helped put out the
trash after the initial crowd was gone

The people who helped make a big breakfast for the crowd

the people who stayed behind to socialize after the work was done

If any of you recognize yourselves in that list, thank you!  I hope you'll
stay with me again next time, and that you'll make yourselves at home.

On SCA weddings: I think they go off best when they're constructed with one
period in mind.  My SCAdian husband and I (who are friends mundanely) are both
9th-century Celts, so it was relatively easy for us to research wedding customs
in Ireland, and make the rest up as we went along.  (We discovered that the
early Irish recognized many different types of marriages, but that's the topic
for a lengthier posting.)

We were married at Pennsic XIV, at sunset.  Since we lived in different camps,
his procession travelled halfway across the site to meet mine.  Other friends
of ours joined the processions as they went along, until we had a veritable
parade once the two groups came together (including Ariel the greyhound, two
ferrets, and a cow and pig we had "raided" from the nice man living next to
Horde Camp).  The entire wedding army proceeded back to Clann O Choda camp,
where we were married by one of the Druids of our Clann.  We drank from the
chalice, bound the cord, declared ourselves to be married, and the celebration
began!

We put on a small, informal feast: roast meat, beer, and assorted other 
goodies (thankfully, someone else in our household took care of all that).  All
our friends came to perform for us -- we had singing, dancing, stories, and
merrymaking late into the night.  We received lots of beautiful gifts, and we
gave small tokens to everyone who came.

It was a wonderful time and a truly great experience (someday I hope to have a
mundane wedding that's half as much fun as that was!), but an incredible
amount of work.

Milord Ulfin: If you're interested in more information, please email me
privately.  I could ramble on and on, and I suspect you're interested in some
of the details of how we managed to pull off this little drama.  The two
major factors in its success were: a devoted and hard-working household, and
LOTS of advance planning.

Thanks to everyone who responded when I mentioned that a second persona just
didn't work for me.  It has nothing to do with my appearance, the quality of
my research, or any of that: but I'm a Celt and will always be one.  I like
the fancy clothes, but I don't wear the attitude well.  Slainte!

--Ariel of Caer Myrddin (Karen J. Norteman)
