Date: 26 Apr 89 05:31:34 PDT (Wednesday)
Subject: re: etiquette for "crashing"
From: "Orilee_J_Ireland-Delfs.wbst845"@Xerox.COM
Message-ID: <890426-234743-4538@Xerox>

Unto Nicolette Bonhomme does Orianna vander Delft send greetings:

Whew, where to begin?  I assume that you know about "bringing your own"
(sleeping gear, towels, toiletries, etc.).  I also recommend to anyone
crashing at someone's house that you call them in advance, say the week
before the event, introduce yourself (if you don't know them), let them
know where you are coming from and what time you will be arriving (I *hate*
staying up until the wee hours of the morning for someone who never
shows!), and get specific directions to their house (we've had some fun (?)
driving around strange cities in the dark of the night).  *Hint:  If
possible, get a street map of the city or town where you will be.  AAA
membership is one of the best investments I ever made for getting maps!*

Gifts:  that's a toughy.  What I have gotten in the habit of doing with
people I don't know is bringing something for breakfast.  A gallon of
orange juice or a dozen fresh croissants is always a welcome addition when
you are feeding several dozen strange people breakfast.  If you know the
person, you might bring a small token (their favorite
wine/beer/liquor/soda) or some such.  One thing that I have had happen when
I autocratted Crown in Thescorre and had a number of people crashing is a
couple of people did my dishes for me, both Saturday and Sunday mornings.
That was probably the *best* gift I have ever received (I *hate* doing the
dishes).  If I can't afford a present, I at least try to send a thank-you
note the week after I have crashed to thank the person for their
hospitality.

Finally, when you are actually crashing at someone's house, respect their
house rules.  Many regular crash houses post a list of the house rules for
their guests so strangers feel more at home and less apt to disturb the
normal run of things. 

