A good deal of what Awilda Halfdane says about the Horde and
Northwoods is exaggerated, to say the least. Par exampla:

The Dark Horde "opened the way for non-European personas." (Awilda)
In fact, at the time the Dark Horde first appeared, the King of the
Middle was a non-european persona.
"In those days North Woods did (not?) drink, smoke dope, smoke
tobacco, fool around, or Have Fun, and by God, nobody else was
either."
I don't know about smoking and fooling around, but during my second
reign the main organization engaged in making fun of the king was the
Mummer's Guild of Northwoods--including the Baron. They stole most of
their material, incidentally, from a certain comic strip featuring a
short king.
"They introduced and continue to maintain the art of belly dance in
the Known World." The first belly dancers I saw in the Middle were
Lady Morna (later fourth queen) and Morgana. They, or other personae
of theirs, may have joined the Horde later, but at that point they
called themselves, as I recall, the Northwoods Dancers' Guild. 
"Gentles who were foolish enough to drink a beer at an event were
politely (and coldly ) informed that It Was A Free Country, And You
Can Do What You Like, But We Don't Do That Sort Of Thing Here." I
never saw it. One of my activities at the time was brewing mead (that
was before I decided that part of taking my persona seriously was not
drinking alcohol in public), and I cannot remember any hint of
criticism or hostility from any of the Northwoods people. 

"not long after I joined the SCA, some where back around AS X  ...  
When I first joined I was warned away from those terrible people, the
Dark Horde.  There were some real sore tempers about the whole
affair." From which it follows that all of your report, concerning as
it does the events leading to the sore tempers (c. AS4-7), is
hearsay. I was there when it started, and that is not how I remember
it.

I realize that some of this is quite critical, but both Yang and the
Northwoods people were friends of mine, and I do not like hearing
either group slandered on the basis of second-hand gossip from
fifteen years ago.

Awilda also repeats (in another posting) her assertions that pearls
were more valuable than diamonds in period, and that diamonds became
really popular only in the nineteenth century, as a result of
advertising by the De Beers Cartel. In defense, she writes:
"I have not specifically researched this topic, but after many years
of reading history, original sources, and talking to people, I have
seen a definite pattern develop. which I have referred to both
jewelers and financiers, and had them support my position."
In other words, she has no evidence to offer to support her
assertion. If she would like to cite her "original sources," I would
be interested to read them. I provided a quote from Cellini on the
value of gemstones, which made it fairly clear that in his time
diamonds were one of the most valuable stones (after ruby and
emerald); he referred to pearls as "fish bones."  

As some more casual evidence, John Evelyn in the poem "Mundus
Mulieribus" (1690) refers to diamonds five times, pearls twice.
Randomly consulting jewelry books from my library, I find references
dating the rise of the diamond from about the 15th to 17th centuries.
Looking at period pieces, I see pearls used with a profusion
inconsistent with their being among the most valuable of gemstones. 

English Medieval Lapidaries (EETS 190) contains seven lapidaries,
ranging from the eleventh to the late sixteenth century. I can find
one mention of pearl (as Margarita), eight of diamonds (as Adamas). 

