Date: 27 Apr 89 15:02:29 GMT
From: tank!fac_ddf%gsbacd.uchicago.edu@speedy.wisc.edu
Subject: Censorship in the SCA, not just Bawdry
Message-Id: <2949@tank.uchicago.edu>

Almost everyone seems to be against censorship of bawdy songs, so I
thought I would raise some related issues. I am a storyteller, and my
persona is Muslim. The period sources from which I lift my material
are sometimes sexually explicit beyond what is usually accepted in
modern American culture. For example, there is one story involving a
Caliph and two slave girls. One of them has given him an erection,
and they are arguing about which gets the benefit thereof, quoting
Islamic law back and forth ("the hunter who has roused the game
.."). The stories also embody views on race and gender not generally
approved of at the moment. Black males are portrayed as ugly but very
sexually attractive to women, women (sometimes) as almost
pathologically unfaithful. As some of you may know, the frame story
of the 1001 nights starts with two cases of queens having affairs
with blacks. In each case queen and lover are killed. The next part
of the story revolves around the point that it is impossible to keep
a woman faithful. (The same theme, incidentally, occupies one canto
of Orlando Furioso, so it is not only an issue for Muslim personae).

It is not, incidentally, that the story is consistently misogynist;
Shaharazad, after all, is the heroine, and there are other strong and
attractive female characters. One of my favorites is the young lady
who is brought into the presence of a man who has been enchanted into
the form of an ape. She immediately asks her father why he is shaming
her by bringing her unveiled into the presence of a strange man, and
when her father expresses surprise, explains that the ape is an
enchanted man. How does she know? "Well, Daddy, I never happened to
mention it, but I'm a powerful enchantress." She is later killed, in
a heroic enchanters' duel with the Djinn who had enchanted the man.
On the other hand, I cannot offhand think of any cases of black males
who are portrayed favorably in the Nights.

The question I am raising is whether your opposition to censorship
applies to what would currently be labelled racism and sexism as well
as to bawdry? Should I tell my stories straight, censor them, or only
tell the ones not too offensive to modern taste?

I have a second and related question. My persona is, and I think
ought to be, an Islamic Chauvinist, with a low opinion of the
cultural level of Western Europeans ("Franks"). He also strongly
diapproves of polytheism, both as a violation of God's commandments
and as an intellectually indefensible position ("contrary to the
teachings of both the Prophet and the Philosophers"). My general
policy is to let those attitudes show, subject of course to the
prudential restraints that would have applied to my persona, given
that he is living mostly among Franks. By doing so, I help keep
myself and those I deal with conscious of the fact that my persona is
not a 20th century person.

One consequence is that, when I recite a poem (by Malkin) containing
a reference to Odin, I immediately follow it by an "explanation"
interpreting Odin as a Djinn or Demon, who the Northmen falsely
believe to be a God--not only is such an explanation (I think)
appropriate to my persona, it may be necessary to cover myself
against accusations of heresy or blasphemy. On one occasion I got a
very hostile reaction from a Norse persona, along the lines of "I
don't say nasty things about your god, you shouldn't say them about
mine." It was fairly clear that the reaction was coming out of 20th
century ideas of religious toleration. The question I want to raise
is whether expressing intolerant views on religion is appropriate as
a reflection of what our personae would have been like (Cariadoc in
fact suspects that some Franks are cannibals, although not the Franks
he knows), or whether it is behavior that should be self-censored so
as not to offend modern sensibilities.

David Friedman (Cariadoc)
College of Grey Gargoyles, Middle Kingdom
Chicago, IL
 

