Date: Thu, 27 Apr 89 14:05:12 EDT
From: almond%hustat@harvard.harvard.edu (Russell Almond)
Subject: My ride on a Longship


Unto the good people of the Rialto does Mustapha al-Muhaddith send his
wishes for peace and prosperity.  

I was hoping that someone with more familiarity with the Longship
group could tell this tale, but as it appears that no one is forth
comming, I will tell it myself.

The Markland Mideval Militia, or rather a special Longship company
does in fact own a Longship (in fact more than one).  As one of my
friends is a sometime captain of the Longship, I aranged to take a
journey on it one time.  We took the longer of the ships (a 24', 30'
boat (my memory fails me), I understand that the shorter one will fit
on a trailer and hence has made the journey to the lake at Pensic.
And I was given a first class birth.  First class birth consist of
bench seats with a large wooden bar in front of the passanger.

They have both a canvas and a nylon sail, and we took the nylon sail
on this day (it being lighter and more managable).  This of course
prompted the very quotable line "(-: If the Vikings had rip stop nylon
they would have used it ;-)".  The voyagers, there were about 12, were
divided up into three teams, each team had at least one experienced
member who sat in front and directed the rowing.  We rowed out of the
harbor past some of the most expensive houses in Alexandria, VA.  I
understand that there is something that makes the people there nervous
about a Dragon boat passing by them.  I personally am far more
offended by the modern boats with there large wake, I feel there is
something picturesque about a viking long boat, being a true sailor at
heart.  The coxswain directed the rowing by chanting "O-o-o--din,
O-o-o-din" over and over again.  It was hard work, and I was glad when
my team was taken out of the rotation.  There were three teams, and
two sides of the boat, so at any time there were two teams rowing and
one team resting.

When we got out into the middle of the bay we rested and ate our
lunch.  As the wind was behind us we then hoisted the sail to try and
sail back twards the harbour.  As longboats do not have a keel they
can only run (for those of you who are not sailors that means moving
with the wind directly behind you, actually one of the slower ways to
sail on a boat with a keel).  As we got closer to the harbor we kept
tilting the angle of the sail and playing with the rudder till the
boat was actually sailing on what was pretty close to a beam reach
(right angle to the wind) or at least a not very broad reach.  We were
all pleased as that meant we didn't have to row until we were very
close to the docks.  

I believe the Longship company made the boats themselves, or at least
they had them made for them.  I will try to get in contact with them
to find out how it was done and where plans could be found if there is
any interest.  

	Pleasant voyaging to all,

		--Mustapha

