Subject: Dark Horde vs. Northwoods

Awilda, some minor corrections:

As a ex-Northwoods SCAdian, back when Yang was active, I have to point out that
Northwoods people were known to  drink, smoke dope, fool around, and have fun.
It was not unusual for us to sing Imperium compound ourselves at post-revels.

Of course, many of us were into SCA in a big way (Northwoods had 24 hours of
SCA activities a week, every week during the quarter--actually there were more
hours of activity, but some of them overlapped).

I think that Northwoods acquired a reputation in much the same way that
Carolingia did--by doing many things, they did some of them much better than
their neighbors.  People began to feel that people fell into to two classes:
those who were interested in authenticity, and those who were interested in fun.
My own impression is that those who were careful about authenticity were 
also those who had the most fun.

Northwoods at that time was known for service.  When a new group 400 miles away
was putting on their first event, 10 or 20 of us attended, and volunteered to
do kitchen chores, cleanup, entertainment, or whatever the group wanted to
help them make it a success.  I can't remember how many "away" events I ended
up pushing a broom.  I have seen other groups in the SCA give major service 
awards for what Northwoods expected of every member.  Of course, those who were
interested in serving the SCA beyond what everybody did, generally ended up 
with Kingdom level offices, and did get Awards of Arms after a year or so.  

Incidentally, "away" events in those days were often very far away--usually
400 miles through snowstorms.  Of course, the Middle was bigger then, as were 
the other two kingdoms.


Kevin Karplus (karplus@azuki.ucsc.edu)
