        Unto the good gentles of the Rialto Li Kung Lo once again sends
greetings! First, I would like to throw in two cents worth on the current
discussion of alternate personas, and then a word on the responses to my
posting on period music performance.
        My position is moderate on alternate personas. I can see Cariadoc's
point of view, wishing to do one as well as you can, and I can also see the
fun of Elizabeth Braidwood vs. Lizzy. (I'm sure I would appreciate them both
at the right place and time!) Sometimes I feel like both, because my persona
is precisely a period alternate persona. There are times when I feel
"homesick" or at least far enough from the inquisitors to expound on Taoist
philosophy, to dream of an obedient woman with bound feet, to reject chivalry
for victory through treachery, or just to be revolted by overcooked,
overwatered saffron rice.(which sometimes makes me wonder how "your" culture
survives) There are other times when I play the acculturated worshipful
Christian squire, who will defend the honor of a lady in distress, who is
loyal to the crown, and who might be called upon to lay down his life in
defense of the holy land (sorry Mustapha...).
        I suppose Li Kung Lo and John Lowe, esquire, are my alternate
personas, but they also represent the changes of a man throughout his
lifetime,socially isolated, and forced to adapt, not just to survive, but also
to have a sense of belonging. If it were not for fealty to my liege and the
pure love of a fair lady I should be nothing more than a renegade exile. I was
born, as Justin du Coeur said *quite* Chinese (I'm touched that you think so),
but I shall die *very* British, and I hope and pray, a knight! Why have an
alternate persona when you can experiment with change? After all, the knowne
world is a big place!
        Regarding my posting on performance, I tried to avoid making my own
feelings clear, because I wanted to hear from other people, and I have, both
in person, on the net, and by email. I wasn't expressing an opinion, but
rather the feeling of being caught between a rock and a hard place. Some peer
says, "Your majesty, you should hear this lord sing, he's a bard!" The crown
says, "Play minstrel!", and Eliane de sans Asile (a loved one of mine, who's
favor I proudly bear), leaves the room in disgust. How would you feel?
        I guess on this one I'll make my camp with the purists. Trust me, I'm
going to learn to sing in Middle English and Provencal, so I may express my
courtly love as a man should.(I refuse to sing Chinese, I've got enough
problems already.) Anyway I've got some idea of what the concensus is, and this
is my perception of it:

1. Carolingians are *not* stuffy A-cops, and we're not particularly more
authentic than any other well established group, but we are trying, and it is
our attempt that makes us seem that way sometimes.

2. This is an issue throughout the knowne world, but the people who don't want
to hear folk or filk at events are mostly quiet, because they're trying not to
spoil everybody else's fun. Also, they don`t want to be called "stuffy".

3. I'm more caught in the middle than most. Performing arts are like that.
I'll bet nobody twists your arm to do modern calligraphy on scrolls for court.

4. Like it or not, folk and filk are acceptable (read: they're being
performed) at feasts and bardic circles throughout the knowne world, and most
people don't have enough of an ear for period melody to know or care. Those
who have devoted a great deal of effort, even years of study to period musical
performance have characteristically received less recognition and cooler
audiences than performers of filk and folk music.

5. What do you do? Spend your summer learning Provencal. I'll be back...

