Message-ID:  <8904260750.aa16890@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

My Lord Cariadoc,

You point out and apparent discrepancy in my discussion of personas.
Specifically, I say that people should feel free to try their best two do two
or more personas if they want to, while later in the same article I describe a
couple of gentlemen who are so thoroughly real that they would disrupt my
version fo the Dream.

There is no discrepancy.  I see no reason why people should not have as many
persona as they want.  Persona are characters we invent.  We give them an
illusion of reality by thoroughly studying the milieu from which they spring,
but they are only an act, a nd we all know they're and act and play along with
the game.

The two gentlemen I described were not personas, they were people.  They were
what they were every moment of their lives, in every inch of their bodies.
They never quit playing the game.  They did not put on costumes, they wore
clothes that were perfectly natural to who and what they were.  They did not
assume manners of another time and places, their manners and attitudes were
their own.

At first I thought the blue-eyed samurai was a persona.  Because, well, he was
Caucasian and I made the mistake of assuming Caucasians could not be samurai.
His persona was so well done I went up to him and complimented him on it, and
discovered it was only his second event, and he had only a hazy notion of what
a "persona" was, he was just being himself.  We continued a friendship, even
though he rapidly dropped out of SCA and went back to Japan where he could live
the reality instead of playing the game.

And Julious is a much older, more mature, more developed person than that young
samurai was.  I can't imagine him being interested in people who don't take
things as seriously as he does.  Julious does not "play the game" either.

We do.  Even if someone does such a thorough job on their persona that they win
the Academy Award for Best Actor, Best Historical Drama, and Best Costume, they
are not their persona.  At some point they take off the costume, go home, and
relax, and say, "Thank God it's another year till Pennsic...Maybe I'll make a
pavilion for next year.."

Those people are the ones we give our awards to.  How can we compete with
people who inherit their artifacts?  Some people in the SCA are excellent
bladesmiths.  But they fall short of Julious' heirloom sword made by the
Imperial swordsmith and given to Tokugawa Ieyasu by the Emporer.  And that
sword was  later given to his ancestor as a reward for his service. That sword
is one of the most beautiful things I have ever seen.  It stays in its vault except
for the rare occassions he feels a guest has proven themselves worthy of
looking at it.  

Yes, such a person could bring a lot to the SCA.  But he has his own students
(one of whom was the first American woman to be liscensed as a samurai by the
Emporer).  He has chosen a different way to live the Dream.  I respect that,
and while I admire him, I cannot do what he has done.  Nor do I think he can do
what I have done.  We are different people, each loyal to their own inner
selves.  We follow different paths.

Yours in Service to the Recognition that there are More Dreams than the SCA,
Awilda Halfdane
