Greetings to all and sundry who read this missive.
And greetings in special to the lady who was unsure of joining in a society
which echoes a period in time where ladies were quite limited in what they
were allowed to do.
In truth, it is possible to find locales where this condition is less a
burden.  Such is the reason why Cynthia du Pre Argent is a French Basque.
Basque women served on the town council, and even assisted the Mass. (One must
remember that even to this day, the Pyrenees are remote, and it is likely that
few clergy passed through on a regular basis!)  The women had their own sphere
of influence, and the men spent most of their time up on the peaks, or near
peaks, with the sheep.  An elaborate whistle language was developed so that
they could communicate; I have seen it demonstrated on the babble-box, and it
could say things as complex as "one of the lambs is caught in a rift; I will
be an hour late for supper."  They also have an elaborate although flawed idea
of where children come from: they are curdled, just like the cheese which is a
mainstay of their diet.  But I digress.
For those who are curious, I reccommend the book "The Return of Martin Guerre"
which is a rather dry scolarly book.  I hear that it was made into a pretty
decent movie, but I have not seen it.  There is also the book "The Circle of
Mountains" which is the doctorate thesis of some woman whose name I do not
recall.


