Date: Wed, 26 Apr 89 08:11:22 EDT
From: "S. Gwen Johnson" <sgj%ctj.uucp@BRL.MIL>
Subject: Quick and Easy Alternate Persona
Message-ID:  <8904260807.aa17581@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

Everyone agrees that doing a persona well requires lots and lots of work, and
very few people manage to pull it off well.  So of course I had to search my
memory to come up with an example contradicting conventional wisdom.   

The particular case I recall was Midrealm Twelth NIght while Hugo and Caitlinn
were Prince and Princess.  Sylard of Easgleshaven had been outlawed for the
kidnapping of Lord Robert.  (And thereby hangs a tale, several of them in
fact.)  Wanting to attend Twelth Night, but not wanting to be arrested, Sylard
came disguised-as a ninja.

Ninja were uncommon back in those days, and people weren't quite sure what to
make of him.  Nobody spoke to him, except Stepann who thought, but wasn't sure
that just maybe it was Sylard. All his attempts at communication were met with
Japanese monosyllables and polite bows.  Frustated, he wandered away and went
around accosting people to see if they knew who that mysterious stranger
in black was.  Nobody knew (well, I knew, but then I was crashing with him and
had seen him getting ready. And I wasn't telling.  But it was hard not to
laugh).

His prescence had a very strange effect on people.  This solitary figure,
masked, lurked quietly in the corner.  It was a crowded hall, but there was an
empty space around him.  People worked their way through the crowd rather than
pass next to him.  After a while of being ignored and avoided he got bored and
drifted over to a large group of people who were chattering non-stop at one
another.  They were occupying the middle of the room, so anybody passing
through perforce became a part of their group.  Suddenly people noticed the
dark figure hovering on the edge of their conversation.  Silence fell.  They
looked at him.  They then tried to pretend he wasn't there and resume their
chatter.  It was awkward and died, and the group dissapated.  The ninja was
left standing by himself in the middle of a ten foot circle. A man entered the
room, started to cross the circle, paused, looked at the ninja, and went the
long way around, through the crowd.

This went on until dinner time.  At which point the Fool's Court pardoned
Sylard and he unmasked.  A great shout went up from the populace.  They were
astonished.  It was wonderful.  And then the dragon challenged Sylard...but
that doesn't have anything to do with alternate persona.   

That alternate persona lasted for one night and was a lot of fun...the costume
wasn't anything special, the prep work that went into it wasn't much either.
If I recall correctly he didn't even have a real sword, only a boken or shinai.
Yet the illusion worked.  It seems to me that the principal ingredient
necessary for a successful persona is the ability to act.  All the research
does is reinforce the act.  And an impressive costume will temporarily blind
people so that they don't realize there is no persona.  

Yours in Service to SCA Folklore,
Awilda Halfdane
Bright Hills, Atlantia
<sgj%ctj.uucp@smoke.brl.mil>


