Well, I'm not with the SCA, but I may be able to help. I'm into buckskinning,    and also have a freezer full of hides. Your friend has several options,      
depending on how much time he wants to spend, how much cash he wants to spend, 
or how understanding his wife is :-)

1. Send the hides to a commercial tanner or taxidermist. Here in Ohio, many of     the taxidermist will tan out hides. I have been told that it runs approx. 
$11.00 ( american) per hide but I have not recently checked on it. 

2. Purchase a home tanning kit. These are available from companys like TANDY 
   Leather, or many of the shops that sell muzzleloading supplies. They are 
   rather easy to use, and provide a commercial-like tan.

3. Brain tan them yourself.  This gives a very exellent hide, similar to a 
   fine grade of flannel. it is also VERY  messy!!!. The general idea is 
      1. scrape all of the hair off of the hide
      2. rub in a paste made of brains. 
      3. strech the hide out to dry on a frame. While the hide is drying, it
	 must be continually worked by rubbing it untill it is dry or it will 
	 dry very hard. 
      4. After the hide is dry, it is smoked over a fire. This will prevent the
	 hide from getting stiff if it gets wet. 
 this is not intended as a how-to to brain tan a hide, but it gives you the 
 general idea of what is involved. for more information, check with some of 
 the firms that carry  buckskinning supplies. They will cary some books that
 can give you detailed instrutions (they are too lengthy to type in!!)
