I, too, have not researched the question, but I have a thought which
might reconcile His Grace's comments with Lady Awilda's.  Most of the
major sources of diamonds in the world are outside of Europe.
Therefore, in period, one would expect diamonds to be rare.  The
evidence of popularity of diamonds to which Lady Awilda refers occurs
at the about the time when one would expect diamonds from other
sources to be reaching England in significant number.

On the other hand, the art of gem-cutting was not fully developed
until after our period.  A few styles of cut gems are found in period,
but for the most part, stones were merely polished.  Pearls, which
come pre-polished, would thus have a greater allure.

