Subject: Staying Alive
Message-Id: <2895@lindy.Stanford.EDU>

Basically, there are two different places you need to "stay alive"
in combat; The Tourney Field, and in Wars.

Staying alive in Tourneys:  Get REAL GOOD at defense.  (and use
Sword and Shield)  If you become good at shield work, you will
become more confident, allowing you to concentrate more on your
offense.  i.e. your shield should be "automatic".

Two ways to train defense:
1)  When practicing, spend some time "defending", i.e. take 20-30
seconds during a fight to "defend", not throwing any shots.
2)  Get someone to play "watch my sword" with you.  They just throw
shots at you, and you just block.  This help them learn to throw
good shots, teaches you to block good shots.

Staying alive in Wars:  Pay attention to where you are.  (and use
any weapon combination you feel comfortable with)  Basically, don't
get stuck in situations that aren't to your advantage.  i.e. if you
have a Round Shield, don't get stuck in the middle of a shield wall.
if you have a Pike, don't run around in the open.

Fighting as an individual in a War is basically a game of manuever,
staying out of fights that don't do your side any good.  Look for
places where you can fight to your advantage, or where the extra
body will help your side.

Example:  Attack the end of a line of the enemy while they are
engaged with a line of your troops, hopefully you can kill the end
person and help "turn the line".

Example:  When the enemy charge the gate of a castle, and are
pushing in, charge into the back of your line and help push the
enemy back out.  But when you are done, pull yourself back, out of
the line.

Think of yourself as a "reserve of one", and try and use yourself to
the best advantage.  This is much different if you are trying to
fight with a group as someone is probably issuing orders, but don't
be afraid to say "I'm not very good at 'whatever'" if the leader
wants you to do something you think isn't what you are good at.
i.e. don't contradict the "order" just that you probably aren't a
good person for that task, and someone else who is good will usually
volunteer.

Using Pikes/Spears/Glaives:  Basically, there are two very different
weapons, those with only points, and those with edges (and points).
I will talk about "Pikes" i.e. weapons with only a point (and no
edge).

If you have face thrusting:  Keep the point aimed right at your
opponents eyes.

Also, any time your opponent engages you, try and disengage, you
have length. i.e. start the fight over.

Enough for now,

Etienne d'Argent
Abeyance of the Westermark
Kingdom of the West

