Date: Wed, 26 Apr 89 10:13:43 EDT
From: "S. Gwen Johnson" <sgj%ctj.uucp@BRL.MIL>
Subject: SCA Weddings
Message-ID:  <8904261807.aa07335@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

I've had a few weddings myself, but none of them were SCA.  I've attended
several weddings af SCA folk.  There are two ways to go about it.  Have one
wedding mixing mundanes and SCA folk, or two have two weddings one in garb for
SCA folk, one in mundanes for family.  I've seen mixed weddings that failed and
mixed weddings that succeeded.  By doing this at Pennsic you've apparently
decided to keep mundane and SCA separate. That's the easiest way to handle it.

Well, to describe a successful mixed wedding.  Bride and groom wore matching
green and white garb that was from, hm, 14th century? And the bridesmaids and
groomsmen were also color coordinated, but not style coordinated.  It was too
expensive to get them all togther.  The bride made her and her groom's costume.
She also did two fabulous card woven sashes to wear with the costumes.  The
wedding took place in a small Tudor style chapel and was limited to a small
number of people-all of whom were educated to know what to expect and the
minister modified the service to more closely resemble a medieval service.

The reception was open to a LOT of people, and and mixed.  Many of the mundane
guests came in costume.  The couples parents were in costume.  Music was
provided by tape recorder and was mostly of the medeival "easy listening"
style.  But later, after many of the mundanes had left, there was dancing.
This was announced diplomatically.  But basically they said": The receptions
over, anyone staying behind will be subjected to medeival foolery."  The key to
a successful wedding seems to be communication, and attention to coddling the
sensibilities of the uninitiated.  Alas, that noble lady has succumbed to her
handicap, and is no longer with us.

A mixed success was caused when a couple was planning two separate weddings,
and their families said, "What's the matter, don't you want us to meet your
friends?"  At this wedding, each member of the bridal party was dressed in
their own personal garb.  The groom was Scottish, his best man Mongol, with a
several undistinguishable European types to fill out the honor guard. At this
point I'm going to delete examples of mundanes and SCA folk failing to get
along with each other.  Suffice it to say many people found it difficult to
cope with people who were so radically different from themselves.  Business
suits and t-tunics don't match unless both sides are educated first. 

Having gone on too long about protocol, I will discuss dress.  Medeival
weddings were a time to show off.  This meant regular clothes, but in the most
extreme, fashionable style the family could afford. Colors such as red, which
the family could not normally afford to wear were popular.  White as the sign
of purity didn't become de rigeur until after our period.  

I don't know about medeival, ah, premarital relations, but in colonial America,
analysis of wedding and birth records show that about half the brides
were "eager brides".  Meaning they had babies less than nine months after
their weddings.  I'll bet a similar rate is true for medeival weddings.
(With no central heat I bet a lot of people used alternative sources of
warmth:-)  

One piece of advice that worked very well for me:  Get married by a magistrate
several days, weeks, or months before the official wedding, and don't tell
anybody.  It means you will no longer have "stage fright" and can concentrate
on autocratting your wedding instead of worrying about things like whether
you're groom's going to chicken out at the last minute, and whether every
single item is perfect.  It is a myth that this is your day.  It is not.  This
is the day your parents get to show off how well-to-do they are, what gorgeous,
successful kids they have, and to enjoy being proud parents.  For the people
who attend, the wedding is entertainment. Lots of couples forget this and fight
terribly about the wedding. Forget it. You're hosting a theme party for a bunch of
people, nothing more.  And if you're already married, you can concentrate on
beings good hosts. 

One more piece of advice. Consult  Miss Manners' Guide to Excruciatingly
 Correct Behaviour.  Her section on weddings will tell you how to
do weddings the proper way according to modern etiquette, and is full of useful
reccommendations about how to handle all the planning and stay sane.  Even if
you don't do half of what she says, you will at least know what is generally
expected, and can choose what is and is not appropriate for you.  I have found
all her etiquette to be soundly based on good sense and to be very pragmatic
about how to handle mundane details like what to do if the flowers aren't what
you ordered.

And remember this, you will  survive.  My wedding gown was hemmed the night
before by the mother of the groom and her best friend.  She was thrilled to get
to help.  And the bridesmaids dresses weren't done and lady Muriel discovered
she'd left the sleeves in Milwaukee.  We couldn't find a fabric that matched
well enough to make sleeves out of.  She scrounged the scraps left over from
the dresses and added lots of lace.  Voila, a beautiful sleeve.  And nobody
stared at the maids armpits to discover that they'd been pieced.  Things like
this will make you go insane if you let them. 

Yours in Service to Staying Sane at Your Own Wedding,
Awilda Halfdane
Bright Hills, Atlantia
<sgj%ctj.uucp@smoke.brl.mil>


