Date: Thu 27 Apr 89 00:18:23
From: "]ke Eldberg" <CONS.ELF@aida.csd.uu.se>
Subject: Medieval weddings
Message-ID: <890427001823.8.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>

Milord Ulfin of Wyrmgeard asked how to perform a medieval wedding.

I am currently researching this subject for a possible future TI article.
When I sat down to find out about medieval weddings, I foolishly believed
that there would exist some sort of "Missale Romanum", an official Roman
Catholic manual where I could find the whole ceremony. Not so! The catholic
church didn't get a uniform ritual until 1614. There is an older "Missale
Romanum" from 1474, but that was never ratified. Instead I found myself
buried under a ton of books about medieval law, liturgy and folklore.

The rites vary much from country to country, and also from time to time
within the middle ages. There is no such thing as The Medieval Wedding 
Ceremony. What I have tried to find out is how it was done in nothern 
Europe from 1100 to 1500. I have found some sources from England and
some from Scandinavia.

Generally, the Church was very willing to incorporate pre-christian traditions
in the wedding ceremonials. Before Christianity, in the Germanic tribal 
societies, marriage was exclusively the business of the two involved clans.
It was first and foremost an economic transaction, not a religious ceremony.
When Europe was christianized, the church had a difficult time getting a
foot into these things. Most people thought that the old juridical ceremonies
were enough, and had only a small understanding for the need to have a priest
bless the union. 

The Germanic wedding traditions involved three ceremonial actions that were
necessary to make the marriage legally binding:

1. Engagement, which meant that the man and the woman were promised to each
other. This was part of the deal, and economic compensation was due if an
engagement was broken.

2. Wedding, where the bride was formally given to the bridegroom by her 
guardian, usually her father. This was done at a feast in the bridegroom's
home. "I give thee my daughter" was the formula spoken.

3. Bedding, where the couple went to bed together in the presence of
witnesses. This was not a pornographic "live show"! The significance was
that witnesses should see that the couple had gone to bed together.

Several medieval wedding rituals have been preserved, but even those from
one and the same country are different in details, e.g. the various parts may
come in a different order. Traces of how weddings were performed may also be
found in laws.

What I say here applies mostly to Scandinavian practise, and in some degree
to English customs. Things may have been different in otheregions of
Europe. The first part of the ceremony took place outside the church door.
At cathedrals with more than one entrance, there was usually a designated 
"bridal door" for this. The actions done there corresponded roughly to the
old Germanic ceremony. Even though this was now led by a priest, it was 
essentially a secular act by which the union of the families was confirmed.

When people had arrived at the church door, the men were placed on the right
side and the women to the left. If the bride was a virgin, her hands were bare.
If she was a widow, she wore gloves. In some countries the most important 
part of the ceremony were conducted in the vernacular, in others everything
was in Latin. In the latter case, the priest would dictate the words that
the bride and groom were supposed to say.

The exchange of rings took place at the church door, as well as the questions
and the "yes" (consesnus facit nuptiam). After all these things were concluded,
everybody went into the church and a special mass was sung for the couple.

I can't give you many more details now because I have only just begun to
dig my way through all these books. But I have performed a medieval wedding
myself, and we decided that the real medieval ceremony was too complicated
to go through with. We followed the standard Swedish ritual, but with a few
changes:
1. Medieval music was played when we entered the church.
2. No hymns were sung. Instead, a lady sung a gregorian chant blessing
   the couple.
3. Pater Noster was sung in Latin (by me, the priest).
4. Everybody stood up throughout the ceremony, except that the bride
   and groom kneeled during prayers.

Another difference was that the bride & groom wore medieval finery. The bride's
gown was black, since that was a more luxurious color than white in the middle
ages (white bridal gowns are 19th century I think).

If you have any more specific questions, do write. I will try to look it up
in the books I have here.

William de Corbie
