Date: Wed, 26 Apr 89 16:49:40 EDT
From: obsolete!pro-angmar!rmonroe@BLOOM-BEACON.MIT.EDU (Richard Monroe)
Subject: weddings

Unto the people of the Rialto and Ulfin of Wyrmgeard particularly, Li Kung Lo
sends greetings! You asked for information on weddings, so I would share with
you what little I know. I apologize that often we are too busy to respond to
reasonable requests for information as we are involved in vituperative
correspondence (flaming those audacious enough to disagree with us). I only
know a little bit about period weddings, and nothing about the SCA versions,
but here goes:
        As Diablu pointed out, we cover a huge area and a vast amount of time,
and you can find that which aesthetically appeals to you somewhere in period,
and mix and match, if you want to. Among the pagan community, the Saxon custom
of handfasting became popular enough to eclipse the older Celtic customs in
the British Isles, and little seems to be known about them now. In
handfasting, the bride and groom's hands are joined together by a cord,
ribbon, or thong, thus symbolically joining them. This was done without
benefit of clergy, but publically, for all to see. Often the fathers of both
parties would tie on cords, followed by the older family patriarchs, and then
in turn by every person at the ceremony.(When we got through with this, boy
were my lady wife and I tied together!) This seems to be the origin of the
term "tying the knot". 
        The Saxons seem to have been neolocal, with the new married couple
occupying a new structure which had been built for them by all these relatives
prior to the wedding, or donated, if one of the families had an extra
structure. It was then necessary to "bed" the couple, attendant with the
public exhibition of the bloodied sheets to show that the marriage had been
consummated. To fail to do this was a disgrace to both parties, as the
implication was that she was not a virgin, and he was impotent. In earlier
times (dates uncertain), it seems to have been popular to hold a public
drinking party to observe and verify the performance of the marital act, but
later it became common practice merely to hold the party around the house,
singing bawdy songs and yelling out advice, words of encouragement, and
cheering on the newlyweds. This made the whole thing easier to fake, and many
an old woman gave her young relative a fresh vial of pig or sheep's blood for
those public sheets. This practice, in modified forms, seems to have survived
at least up to the 19th century, both in England and the U.S., where it was
known as a shivaree.
        Of course, the relatives and guests continued feasting and partying
with formal toasting and the consuming of huge amounts of mead, for a full
month after the wedding ceremony. This was known as the "honeymoon". As late
as the fifteenth century, references can be found to English men and women
going to Scotland to be married, and to hold the honeymoon, as English law
mandated that a marriage must be presided over by a (Christian) priest, and
Scotland had no such law. This may well represent the origins of going away
for a honeymoon. This is one of the many pagan customs that died hard, in
spite of the fact that all of these people were most likely nominal Catholics.
        Unto Ulfin and your bride to be, the blessings of Hearn and the Earth
Mother. I hope that my ravings are of some use to you. If they are, by all
means invite me to the revel, and save bottle of long mead.

                                        In Service to Nuptial Bliss,
                                        Li Kung Lo

