In article <8904211643.AA20537@tut.cis.ohio-state.edu> PROSSER@ECS.UMASS.EDU writes:
* 	I have a question that has bothered me for quite some time now, 
* ...
* Our shire has occasionally debated the performance of bawdy songs at 
* events, with the more prudish members of our group having the last word
* most often.  At one event,  one of my household members sang an original
* composition that was somewhat bawdy, much to the delight of everyone.
* All was fine and good until the next shire meeting, when another gentle,
* generally well-loved by all, took the floor and began to complain about 
* the same song at grat length.  As a result of this, my dear sister has
* refused to perform *anything* since, and the shire has unfortunately 
well, for my two pents worth...
This seems, in all, a most unfortunate situation, that one way or another
(several) someone ended up feeling offended and/or embittered and/or
unappreciated and/or generally feeling bad as a result of an event
intended to be simply enjoyable by all.  And seemingly someone lacked
discretion in _either_ performance _or_ response thereto.
So...
Well, what do we mean by "bawdy"?  OUCH!
It seems fair to say that "period" mores of public topic of conversation
and performance were what almost any of us would call a bit "looser" than
what prevails mundanely, even if our own preference is for the looser end
of the range.  Yes, there were intervals of priggish or downright prudish
superficial standards, but even then the (cruder?) aspect was only very
thinly varnished.
So it is probably fairly "period", and maybe even to be expected, that
"bawdy" be a part of entertainments.  And, assuming that the lady
performer was in personna something of a minstrel, or that the request
that she perform was anywhere close to in-role and in-course of the event,
then "bawdy" was probably not at all out-of-line or inappropriate.
That is, the minstrel in the prevalent case had license to do or say
somewhat more freely than other folk anyway.  And someone in-role or
in-course who is called upon to do minstrelsy had likewise the same license.
The extreme case of the former being the "court fool" who had license
to jape even upon the host or the most honored guest.  The case of
the latter being any interval of foolery invited or permitted by the host
and thus thoroughly implicitly granting license to all.
--
Now, what is "bawdy" and what is "lewd"?  Or what is "amusing" and
what is "offensive"?...
Well, describing one character's overly amorous pursuit of another,
or contretemps resulting therefrom, or doing a verbal "fade-to-black" like
in a movie seeing them fall into bed but not being shown the humps and moans,
or referring to a character's prowess or predeliction (or lack or ineptness)
without getting into anatomical description or precise measurement,--is
probably "just bawdy" and "amusing" and (PERSONAL OPINION) likely
offensive only to those who take determination to be offended by something
and, simply, pick a target of opportunity regardless of fact or consensus.
But, getting down to counting strokes, or measuring members, or having NO
element of humor, or recounting of sex (or other basic function) just for
the sake of recounting such topic, is probably "lewd" and "not amusing"
and (PERSONAL OPINION) not only offensive but likely to end up
being taken as demeaning by at least some persons of sensitivity
and shoud not be invited and should be chastised (sub voce, at least)
(post facto in prive, if possible) and should be generally and clearly
