Greetings my lady,

I have always found travelling to events and crashing to be one of the
more rewarding aspects of the SCA.  You meet more people, and really
get to know them, than you can at the event itself.  If you're lucky,
there's a post-revel.  Maybe someone pulls out a guitar and starts
singing SCA filk, or bawdy songs, or telling stories.  There's no
better way to learn SCA history, good songs, good stories, and good
gossip.  For new people, especially, it's a great way to really get
into the culture of the Society.  By the same token, it can be great
fun to open your home for crashers at your own shire's event.  Things
are done a little bit differently in every SCA group, and the best
things come from shared ideas, whether its a great song which no one
in your own group[ has heard, or a new dance which is all the rage in
Atlantia. 

It's a good idea to come prepared to put your host to as little
trouble as possible.  Bring a bedroll, so you can sleep on the floor
if you have to, and a towel or two.  You'll probably find that it's
not necessary, but it's best to be sure.  I always try to bring some
kind of crash gift: a bottle of wine, something for breakfast before
the event, whatever.  It shows that you appreciate their hospitality.

Consider it your duty to offer hospitality and to return it in kind,
and you will find the SCA a very pleasant place to live.

	Arval.
