From: lindy!news@labrea.stanford.edu  (Steven E Goodman)
Subject: Units
Message-Id: <2883@lindy.Stanford.EDU>

Re:  Frequency of fighting units.

There seems to be two major problems incountered when trying to form
fighting units.

1)  Finding a "leader"/recruits.  i.e. if Duke James Greyhelm formed
a unit, he would probably have all the recruits he wants.  However,
Knights "normally" prefer to train their squires/men at arms for
tourney fighting not for units.

A "normal" fighter trying to form a unit has trouble gathering like
minded recruits, i.e. doesn't have reputation to help out.  (I know,
I tried a couple of years ago.)

2)  Getting everyone together on a regular basis.  i.e. it is hard
to get the same 10 people to show up for fighter practice at the
same time, regularly.

Basically, there seem to be two kinds of fighting units in the SCA.
Those based around "households" (i.e. organized by a Knight), and
those based around an organization (i.e. shire or barony, etc.).

I'm talking about true fighting units, those that train together as
a unit, not just being in a group at a war.  i.e. the Westermark
doesn't have a real unit, although we may fight as a group at wars.

Household units seem to be more stable, as they have a central
leading person, who is obviously in charge.  And they seem to have
less "turnover", even if some of the members get Knighted.

The most successful (my opinion) unit I've seen (and fought with) is
Griffin's Guard.  It was started about 7?  years ago by Sir Brandon,
and a bunch of his Squires/Men at Arms/Friends.  Not all of the
members were part of his household, but they all knew each other,
and camped/partied, etc, together.  As members have become Knights
they have still remained part of Griffin's Guard, and their
Squires/Men at Arms have become members also (instead of the new
Knights dropping out of the unit).

The new Squires/Men at Arms help maintain the total number of
members (as some of the "oldtimers" are much less active now), and
the Knights maintain a solid core of experienced fighters.  I
believe there are currently 6 Knights in Griffin's Guard.  However,
the Knighted members are all willing to take orders from Sir Brandon
as it is his unit.

If John the Boftist is out there, he can give a better opinion as to
Griffin's Guard's success (as he is a member), I just fight with
them sometimes.  (They have a lot of friends, who aren't members,
but sometimes fight with them, as flankers or scouts, etc.)

Units based on a territorial area seem to have a high turnover as
members become Knights, and start households, or members become
Squires to Knights in other areas.

More later,

