ALTERNATE PERSONAE:  As has already been noted, most people are not
necessarily very serious about alternate personae (or, for that matter,
primary personae...).  For example, down here in Trimaris, there are by
necessity lots of "warm weather personae."  In these instances, the usual
approach is of the sort Duke Cariadoc described.  However, there are those
gentles who *really are* equally interested in more than one culture, and
manage to present more than one persona with equal facility.  One gentle here
upon the Rialto is one such:  Baron Seamus McRyu McHoo is as Scots (bagpipes
and all!) as Jutte-sama is Japanese, and Benjo-san is unmentionable :-).  I
never forget (well, *almost* never) to call these personae by their proper
names, respectively, because each is fully _there_, as it were.  As Awilda
Halfdane noted, comportment, movement, etc., are all intrinsic to successfully
conveying the varying personae.

On the other hand, his lady wife became Elspeth-Jean of Lochmaree in no small
measure because she just about *never* answered to her original name,
Kriemhilde (sp?) von Habichtslager (Hush, Jean!  You did *not* answer to that
name, even if you *still* insist you *did!*  :-)

I am sorry that Awilda hopes her friend Julious never finds the SCA, in the
sense that: a) his presence would probably do us all a world of good; b) we
could learn much from such a gentle; c) good role models provide something
positive to live up to; d) really good role models are hard to come by; e)
good role models challenge us to better ourselves.

CAROLINGIA/AUTHENTICITY POLICE:  It should be remembered that stereotypes are
easily formed, and cling tenaciously.  We would all do well to remember not to
be too judgemental, or to form opinions too quickly.  Likewise, we should
remember that most stereotypes have at their heart a kernel of truth, and that
there is but one chance to make a first impression.

Both "authenticity mavens" and "party mavens" bug the hell outta me, because
each represents to me an undesirable extreme.  "Authenticity mavens" who take
things to the point of becoming "authenticity police" are stodgy and stuffy,
and often fail to see the multiplicty of reasons people join the SCA.  They
also tend to lose sight of the limitations (read:  lack of $$$$$$$) on many of
our members, especially the younger/newer ones.  I often find myself thinking
that there are actually more appropriate places for people with these
attitudes; groups for whom accuracy of historical re-enactment is the primary
goal.  And, frankly, I wish some of them would go there and leave the rest of
us alone!  I'm sorry, but the guy who (years ago) once told me, *in all
seriousness*, that since his persona was Spanish he wouldn't talk to anyone
with French or English personae turned me off-- that kinda dreck *ain't* while
we're here!  All things considered, an over-emphasis on authenticity seems to
me to tend to stifle creativity and discourse between individuals.

I don't think I need explain why "party mavens" bug me.  :-)

As for Carolingia itself:  I don't know if this will be any consolation to the
Carolingians on the Rialto or not, but my only contact with Carolingia has
been _via_ this medium.  All of you have been very nice, and have generally
had something worthwhile to say.  I've been favorably impressed.  So, for what
it's worth, this whole discussion really surprised me when it arose!  I never
woulda thunk it by what's gone on hereabouts!  So, take heart!

RUSSIAN PERSONAE/COSTUMING:  For the several gentles who have expressed
interest recently in this subject, some hopefully-useful hints.  Firstly, try
to find info on such pre-Russian states as the Principalities of Kiev and
Moscow, and Prussia.  Also try to find info on the Rus, the original tribe
from which Russia took its name.  Remember that Russia, as a sovereign nation,
came along fairly late.  For costuming, check out Byzantine dress.  The
Russians adapted heavily from the Byzantines, especially with respect to
headdresses.  See the classic silent film "Alexander Nevsky"-- no joke!--
which presents the story of one of Russia's earliest military heroes, with
great attention to accuracy and detail in costuming (great musical score by
Prokoffiev (sp?), which was meant to be played live with the film).  Also, see
if someone has the recent TV miniseries "Peter the Great".  The period
portrayed is much later, but clothes hadn't changed that much in Russia.

CENSORSHIP:  Is a *bad* thing, period!  I loathe censorship in all its many
forms, both overt and subtle.  Performers should *always* be free to perform
(even as we should be free not to listen).  *BUT!* as has already been noted,
one should not confuse censorship with propriety and/or appropriateness.  I
have no problem with bawdy songs and dirty ditties.  However, the middle of
feast (especially if children are present) is *not* the right time and place
for, say, "The Bloody Balls of Scotland."  Some subtle double-entendre, maybe,
but nothing overt.  Filking and bawdy should be reserved for bardic circles
and the like, where people can come and go more freely.

With any freedom comes responsibility, and that includes freedom of
expression.  While no one should attempt to censor a performer in any way,
likewise a performer should show some modicum of common sense by choosing
material appropriate to the situation.  No one can make all of the people
happy all of the time.  But, if you make a lot of the people *un*happy, you
goofed.

And, if someone *does* have a problem with a particular piece (for any
reason), the proper way to handle the situation is *NOT* a public
dressing-down of the performer!  Your seneschal should never have allowed that
to take place; and if the seneschal did goof and allow it, the group should
have no just sat there, in my opinion.  Certainly, it is wrong to allow one
person to impose his/her own tastes on everyone else.

And, just for the record:  I do *not* regard the person in charge of
entertainment (be that Crown or autocrat) telling a performer "I don't think
that piece is suitable for performance during feast" as being _ipso facto_
censorship.  Sometimes, we all need reminding.

Finally:  Taliesin, do keep urging your sister to return to performing!  Not
only should she not let one individual's dissenting view get her down, it is
something that as a performer she will need to learn to deal with.  Besides
which, there are too many people who will appreciate her.  Not to mention that
one could take the view of triumph being the best means of revenge... (who
said that!?!  Not *me!* :-) )

REGALIA:  When Trimaris went to Kingdom status, lotsa people made lotsa
Regalia.   Nice Regalia.  Expensive Regalia.  Hard to transport Regalia.  End
result:  much Regalia that's *never* seen.  My advice:  make any Regalia
durable, adjustable and/or collapsable (as appropriate), reasonably light-
weight, and not unreasonably expensive.  And keep it to a minimum, because
it's going to be passed from Crown to Crown.

