Milord Cariadoc,

I beg to differ about the relative value of pearls and diamonds.  I have not
specifically researched this topic, but after many years of reading history,
original sources, and talking to people, I have seen a definite pattern
develop. which I have referred to both jewelers and financiers, and had them
support my position.

Up until about the 18th century, pearls were pre=eminent.  Catherine the Great,
Elizabeth the First, Marie Anoinette all wore diamonds, but there is nothing
to indicate that they valued their diamonds more than any other gem.  Fiction
from the late 18th century uses jewelry as part of the personifications of
characters.  Well-bred, conservative older women wear pearls, younger, rich,
more flamboyant women wear diamonds.  And the older women dissapprove of the
modern taste, which to their eyes, is bad taste.  Obviously, the 18th century
in England saw a rising popularity of diamonds as compared to pearls.

This trend continued in the 19th century so that by the turn of the new
century in the United States, pearls, diamonds, and gold are the only jewelry
that is considered to be in impeccable taste.  In Europe, colored stones retained
popularity, but diamonds did eclipse all others.  Both Lady Di and Fergie had
colored engagement rings.  When I had a colored engagement ring, everybody who
saw it remarked on it as unusual.

This is the result of a heavy advertising campaign by the diamond cartel. In
order to encourage diamond sales, they advertised.  And sales soared.  Pleased
that they'd succeeded in creating a  much bigger market, they relaxed.  And
sales dropped.  so they learned that they had to keep advertising.  After a
while, they had a surplus of smaller stones, so they advertised composite
jewelry.  Small stones sold well-soltaires drooped.  So they manage their
advertising very carefully to keep the demand tailored to the supply.  A neat
racket.  As for how they avoid chiselling, they don't.  When cheap stones
appear on the market they buy them up rapidly-a fact the Soviet Union has used
to raise a few quick bucks in the past.  Obviously they can't keep this up
forever, something has to give.  What's given is the Soviet economy.  They are
now in sufficiently desperate straights that a few quick dollars is utterly
inadequate for their needs.

At this point I will ackowledge that I have exhausted my knowledge of the
financial industry. Money in the abstract doesn't interest me, all I want to
know is if I've got enough of the green stuff in my pocket to satisfy my whims.
(Alas, I rarely do.)

Yours in service,
