Subject: Forks and Kimonos

Forks: The just-produced first issue of The Oak, the Atlantean A&S adjunct to
the kingdom newsletter has a fine little article on this subject (written by
Robyyan Torr d'Elandris, as I recall; perhaps he could pass a quick summary
on to the Rialto?).

Kimonos: I really must disagree with William de Corbie that having a persona
different from one's own genotype is all that big an obstacle. Two cases in
point:

Richie Munroe is not Oriental, although Li Kung Lo is *quite* Chinese. His
persona is well-enough developed, and noticeable enough, that the Crown gave
him an AoA scroll written entirely in Chinese (very, very pretty, even if no
one in the Barony can read it).

Likewise, Mussttafa doesn't *look* Arabic, but you cease to notice that after
listening to his storytelling for a few minutes. Again, his mannerisms and
persona are developed to enough of a degree that he *feels* Arabic.

In general, if one is willing to put some work into it, one can become pretty
much any persona believably. Indeed, many of the best-worked-out personae
have had just this sort of cross-cultural basis; it forces the person to
really sit down and think through the persona, instead of just drifting
along the way most of us do.

*However*, (and getting back to the point of this note stream), doing a 
persona well is a *lot* of work. Not very many people manage a single persona
to the point that an observer can simply talk to them for a minute and
know their persona, and I don't know anyone who can do it for two. 
Therefore, I agree with Cariadoc's advice: *let* yourself be Ariel in a
kimono. Unless you can really get *yourself* to believe in an alternate
persona, no one else is going to...

					-- Justin du Coeur

