Subject: Performing at events.

The subject of performance of any sort at SCA events is a difficult one.
As someone who has in the past run the Jongleur's Guild here in Carolingia,
it is a something that i have had to deal with many times.  Here are my
observations:

1. Not everyone comes to SCA events to take part in the event.  Many
   (quite reasonably) treat it as a social occasion.  Therefore, unless
   the event is specifically and explicitly a performance (e.g., several
   years ago we had an event which was a production of Midsummer Night's
   Dream) there *must* be some place to which people can "escape" if
   they want to.  This means having two halls, or a "bardic circle" room
   or suchlike.  People who can hear the performance *want* to hear the
   performance, and those who don't can avoid it without slinking around
   in the parking lot.  (Makes for better relations with the local
   gendarmes as well :-) As a performer, i don't want to be performing
   if no one wants to listen, and *far* perfer a small appreciative
   audience to a large indifferent one.

2. As a corollary to #1, performances at the feast are *very* tricky to
   pull off successfully.  Everyone is distracted (food, friends, perhaps
   alcohol, darkness) and the hall is almost by definition the largest
   one at the site.  Furthermore, the audience is captive, that is, the
   audience is at the focus of the event at that moment.  Autocrats who
   would blanch in fear at the suggestion that there be an hour of music
   performance scheduled during court think nothing of scheduling twice
   that much during the feast, even though in many important respects the
   audience is in the same situation.  Not everyone likes singing, not
   everyone likes harping, not everyone likes belly dancing, and the
   annoyance of being shushed for an hour or more can be pretty wearing.

   The ideal performance for this situation is a loud group that performs
   well for about five minutes, followed by a "reasonable" break.  Most
   people can sit still for that.  I have also heard truly extraordinary
   performers (a couple of harpers come to mind) who kept an entire hall
   spellbound through sheer talent, but this is, sadly, rare.

3. Now (at last) we get to the subject of "controversial" material.
   While i heartily approve of having fun (in spite of being a Carolingian
   :-) and have through my, uh, studies acquired an, uh, well, appreciation
   of medieval bawdy songs, i also understand that many people are
   uncomfortable with the subject material.  The same goes for filk/folk,
   though in a different way.  What i have said above about "ordinary"
   performances goes double for anything that might be expected to raise
   eyebrows.   I personally would not schedule either for the feast hall
   or court (unless it was a Seven Deadly Sins event or suchlike where
   people should not be surprised).  It seems only courteous to avoid
   these forseeable problems.  On the other hand, there should then be
   no objection to the mere *existance* of the stuff.

   As an aside, the medieval madrigallists wrote in an elaborate language
   of sexual metaphor.  Ever wonder about all those "spent shafts"?  What
   *were* all those lovers doing "dying" all the time?  Wink, wink,
   nudge, nudge.  :-)

In summary, it is possible to strike a balance between providing
entertainment and forcing it on an unwilling populace, but it requires
some care due to limitations of human endurance and variations in taste.

In service to performance in the Society, i am,

		--Kobayashi Yutaka, sometime performer

