Date:         Mon, 24 Apr 89 11:56:51 EDT
From:         Mike Hojnowski <MQH@CORNELLC.cit.cornell.edu>
Subject:      Niccola's Helpful Hints #2

I am again posting for this on behalf of Niccola...  Orlando
----
This, and other helpful hints, provided as a service to anyone who
would like to try to beat me at the Ice Dragon Arts Pentathlon next
year.  Print it out.  Pass it around.


DON'T POLISH ANYTHING UNTIL YOU'RE FINISHED HITTING IT

Don't cut the woodblock until the design is right.
Don't hem the dress until it hangs right and the seams are overcast.
Don't oil the wood until the carving is clean.
Don't color the illumination until the underdrawing is correct.

The SCA is at the moment a haven for the self-proclaimed craftsman who
presents to the public view items which were ill-conceived, ill-planned
(or unplanned), and which he abandoned as perfect when they were about
half-finished.

Your time and your materials are valuable.  If you do half-assed,
shoddy work you're wasting both.  You deserve to have your efforts
repaid with a well made, attractive artifact.  You're cheating yourself
if you rush into a project without planning it, hurry through a job you
could do better, or decide that it's "good enough" when it's really not
done.

I don't mean that you should obsessively refuse to complete a project
because it's not perfect.  Nothing is ever perfect.  Your first- or
your fiftieth- attempt is not going to look like the work of a
professional craftsman taught by other professionals.  On the other
hand, the dedicated and careful amateur can produce works of very high
technical quality.

There are points in every project at which you may reasonably ask
yourself whether you should go on to the next task or if you should
stick with the process at hand a little longer.  These include the time
when you think you know how you're going to make your artifact, each
occasion when you change techniques (you finish drawing and start to
embroider; you finish forging and start to grind; etc.), and that
moment when you first imagine you are finished.  Don't be sad if you
can't go on yet.  Your project is going to be splendid.

Niccola Sebastiani

Reade, Practise, and Censure

