Subject: Alternate Personas - It Ain't the Clothes

Howdy folks, To be able to talk about personas, I have to be Donna Hrynkiw.
Please 'scuse the mundanity.

In Digest #312, Cariadoc says:
> ...one of the problems with alternate personae--people who
> try to have them typically end up with at most one persona. They
> react as the same person in different clothes, and others react
           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^  NOTA BENE
> to them as the same person in different clothes--making it
> harder for either side to believe in even one persona (what is a
> celt doing in a kimono anyway)?

*That's* the biggest problem with alternate personas. Unless you *act
differently* you are still the same old persona. Just changing clothes
don't do it.

And a little later says:
> The solution I recommend is to have one persona. If you really
> want to wear a kimono, or elizabethan garb, or whatever, simply
> assume that your persona saw that kind of clothing on someone
> else in the society and decided it was an interesting foreign
> fashion and worth copying.

Also for convenience: Elizabeth Braidwood wears Celtic/Viking garb
during the summer. It's easier to pack, cooler to wear and faster
to make. But everyone knows that even if she isn't wearing a houppelande,
it's still E.B.

And William de Corbie says (Digest 313):
> It is very difficult to believe in oriental personas when the bearer
> is obviously a white caucasian.
PHOOEY. William, it's *attitude*.

Awilda Halfdane says in Digest 314:
> But just because
> they're white is not what's wrong. [interesting but irrelevant stuff
> deleted] But to tell you about this samurai.  He was new to the SCA, but
> he wasn't new to Japanese culture, and had absorbed much of the Japanese
> body language.  He was very convincing.

Here we go: Ask anyone in the barony - Her Ladyship Elizabeth Braidwood
and Lizzy the Kitchen Wench are *not* the same person. It ain't the clothes
(although they *do* help) - it's the attitude / behaviour / body language /
whatever you want to call it.

I stumbled upon Lizzy when I was asked to serve at a tavern night. I
borrowed a late-period bodice and skirt, stuck some gum in my mouth and
this...  this... *person* appeared. She's not at all like Elizabeth and I
only had to do a little campaigning to clarify things. ("Who's this Braidwood
chick I keep hearing about? The name's Lizzy and all I do is sling beer and
grub!")

An alternate persona story: Lizzy served at a rather large tavern that was
attended by quite a few people from not-around-here. She had a good time,
met lots of people and made some new friends. About 5 months later, many
miles away from home, Elizabeth Braidwood was attending an event in her
capacity as Royal Retinue. All during the day and well into the banquet,
she kept catching a local lord watching her with a puzzled look on his
face. They had spoken once or twice during the day, but only exchanging
pleasantries. As the banquet was folding up, E.B. was helping to clear
up and (falling a little out of persona) was bopping to the cowboy music
coming from the hall next door.
"Aha!" exclaimed the Local Lord "I *have* met you before!"
"Yes?" inquired E.B.
"You were serving at the tavern - you're Lizzy!"
I was still in my E.B. clothes, but for a moment I had fallen in to being
Lizzy - and someone recognized the change.

Other persona comments:
The strangest things happen in alternate personas - one of E.B.'s best
friends does *not* get along with Lizzy at all.

Donna Hrynkiw
(aka Elizabeth Braidwood and Lizzy the Kitchen Wench)
