As at least two others have responded in much more fluent words than I
to the posting "why join the SCA if you're not interested in romance", 
I shall simply applaud their sentiments.  Thank you for supporting the
view that there is much more of interest in the SCA than mating games, 
and much more to chivalry than cottonwool wrapping the "fair sex".

When I first tested the waters of the SCA, I was hesitant to assume a 
female role.  I have studied medieval history with the rest, and was
not enamored of the female position in life.  Uncertain of the authenticity
of SCA attitudes, I feared a chauvinistic, insulting encounter.

I hedged by starting out in male garb.  Let me assure you, this raised
no eyebrows.  I was addressed with masculine terms, and treated as I
by my attire requested.  The situation was perhaps more common in the
group with which I associated.  We had one dearly loved and respected 
member whose name I am desperately trying to recall - with little success - 
who maintained a male persona.  I do wish there be someone familiar with
her who might recall her to me.  She was an accomplished leather worker;
short, dark hair, quite attractive.  She was part of the household headed
by Lord Emeris of Ellenar, based in Tear Sea's Shore (Charleston, SC).  
She lived nearby.  I believe her mundane nickname was Elf (but I could be
mistaken).

As an aside - I have found that I retain little of the details of new
experiences - names, faces, locations, etc.  Is this common?  I mostly
remember emotions, typically recalled by images, almost snapshots, of
events.  I say this both to explain my inability to recall the name or
other pertinent details about someone I remember so clearly and to ask
whether others have similar recollection storages.

Returning to my point, I don't see that persona gender and mundane gender
or sexual preferences have anything to do with one another.  As I have 
become more familiar with SCA attitudes, I have reverted to female garb,
mostly for the sake of convenience.  As I develop a persona (which is a
VERY long and lingering process !!! ), I may switch back to being male.
My half-formed, jellied as it were, persona lives in a place and time in
which women were afforded somewhat more independence (exigencies of life
and all that).  

Ok, ok, I'm a Celt.  It's something of a cop out, as I'm a Celt in real 
life (ancestrally, that is).  My forefathers were tossed out of Wales for 
stealing sheep - not that they were alone among Welshmen.  My foremothers 
(?) were forced out of Scotland by the murthering English.  The joys of 
mongreldom ... I have also English blood running through these veins.
Enough digression! 

I in male garb have been known to flirt with the ladies.  I in female garb
have been known :-) to flirt with the lords.  I in male or female garb expect
and receive the courtesy of choosing whether or not to flirt, in which I
hope I am not alone. 

In male or female garb, I would not object to being flirted with by ladies.
(I am resistant to being flirted with by lords in male garb - the illusion 
becomes somewhat precarious).  Apart from William de Corbie, am I alone in
not taking offense?  Appreciation is too rare to be rejected out of hand.

