Subject: Censorship

  Unfortunatly, censorship is one of the things from the middle ages that we
haven't even managed to stomp out in the 'modern' world.  There are things that
90% of the people consider fun, while 10% take it as offensive.

    Since my persona is that of a minstrel, this is something that I've given a
good deal of thought to, with less than satisfactory results.  My advice to the
good gentle that sang the song is to remember this equation.

    Offending 1 person (not royalty)  =   Tough luck buddy.
    Offending 2              "        =   Change a word or two, perhaps?
    Offending 3              "        =   Would changing the song a little ruin
                                          it beyond all repair?
    Offending 4 or more      "        =   Change it, or perform it only for
                                          those people who you know would
                                          enjoy it.

    Even the performers today have different sets of songs that they will
sing based on the audiences responses to their previous songs,  as I'm sure
they did in the middle ages.  No documentation on this of course, but people
have had preferences and were motivated by the same base things since time
started.  The performers are going to have songs that they love to perform,
and damn the torpedos if someone doesn't like them, and the audiences have
had their favorites that made the performers wince each time they were
requested.
    Moderation should still be practiced, of course.  There are songs that
can cause one to be chased about with non regulation weapons (although duct
tape is still optional 8-).

    Please please PLEASE beg her to keep performing... The discomfort of one
person complaining is by FAR out weighed by the happiness that a group of
people can experience through the enjoyment of a good song.  A good song helps
to bring about a sense of fellowship and friendliness (you've all experienced
it, looking around and seeing everyone else smiling at the same joke or play
on words) and communication.  They spur communications, breaking down the walls
by helping to start conversations and discussions, and (most certainly
important) spread information and ideas that would otherwise be tedious to
sit through a workshop or class to learn.

    But enough, there are others would will most certainly feel strong enough
to post their own views on this subject....

