Subject: Alternate Carolingian Fork
Message-ID: <890422170328.21.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>

Carolingia:

Sounds like a wonderful place. Rampant authenticity! Must go there sometime!
I agree with those gentles who have said that there is no right way to do
the SCA, but there are different ways. Every group can choose its own style.
Authenticity is good. If you can't, or don't want to be 100% authentic, that's
OK too. (Being 100% mundane, in clothing or behavior, is NOT OK though.)

Alternate personas:

I believe that another reason why Ariel's alternate Japanese persona is
perceived as "Ariel in a kimono" may be that Ariel is not Japanese. It is
very difficult to believe in oriental personas when the bearer is obviously
a white caucasian. What about a blond Scandinavian type of person who wants
to be Lord Mbwane of Zwaziland? Or what about a black Viking? Or a Chinese
Anglo-Saxon? Certainly, all of these are permitted. But if your persona
is totally out of line with your physical appearance, people will unfortunately
get the wrong idea. Not much anyone can do about that. It's easier to be
someone looking like you do.

Forks:

The fork is indeed an ancient invention. Even the Romans had them. But how
were the forks used? Modern manners say you should cut the food in small
pieces with your knife, on your plate. Then you use the fork to bring a
piece of food to your mouth. I think that it's not likely that people used
their forks like that in the middle ages. More probably, the fork was used
to protect the hands from getting burned by hot food. They would use it to
take a piece of hot meat from the servant's tray. They would use the fork
to hold up the food in front of them while they gnawed at it. 

Another thing that probably was different was the use of the knife. They
did not have china plates, but wooden or metal plates. These aren't hard
enough to stand the kind of food-cutting that we do today. I don't believe
they cut against the plate. Rather, the technique would be to use their
teeth as much as possible and only cut with the knife to get a chunk from
the steak.

I cannot document this, but it makes more sense that way, right?

William de Corbie
