Date: 21 Apr 89 06:48:42 GMT
From: unmvax!ncar!tank!fac_ddf@gsbacd.uchicago.edu
Subject: Ariel in a kimono (alternative personae, problems with)
Message-Id: <2834@tank.uchicago.edu>

or
Ariel in a kimono

Ariel of Caer Myrddin  comments that her alternate (japanese)
persona is generally interpreted as just "Ariel in a Kimono."
That is one of the problems with alternate personae--people who
try to have them typically end up with at most one persona. They
react as the same person in different clothes, and others react
to them as the same person in different clothes--making it
harder for either side to believe in even one persona (what is a
celt doing in a kimono anyway)? I can think of only two or three
exceptions, in my own experience in the SCA.

The second problem is that no one, or at least no one I know,
myself included, does a really adequate job of one persona, so
trying two or three makes the outcome even worse.

The solution I recommend is to have one persona. If you really
want to wear a kimono, or elizabethan garb, or whatever, simply
assume that your persona saw that kind of clothing on someone
else in the society and decided it was an interesting foreign
fashion and worth copying. You may know that it is from two
thousand miles away or five hundred years in the future, but
your persona does not know that. It is simply attractive foreign
dress. The same works for armor, dancing, etc. It blurs your
persona a little--sticking to things your persona could actually
have worn, done, etc. would produce a more believable
persona--but it is far better than multiple personae. 

David Friedman (Cariadoc)
College of Grey Gargoyles, Middle Kingdom

