Date: 21 Apr 89 07:42:19 GMT
From: unmvax!ncar!tank!fac_ddf@gsbacd.uchicago.edu
Subject: Tolerance, pro and con
Message-Id: <2836@tank.uchicago.edu>


There is *no* right or wrong way of dealing with the Current
Middle Ages, but there are different ways. People who think that
Carolingia must be stuffy because of its emphasis on
authenticity (which isn't really all that much stronger than in
most places I've seen) and arts are being just as silly as the
occasional Carolingian I've encountered who thinks that a group
that doesn't do those arts is somehow incomplete. Both styles
are valid, and both are fun.

I agree with part of the point he is making in this posting, and
disagree with part. Criticizing other people in order to have
the pleasure of feeling self-righteous and proving they are
worse than you are is both discourteous and counter-productive.
But it does not follow that one should not have opinions of how
SCA ought to be done, and try to persuade others of them, which
is what the quoted passage seems to imply. There are many ways a
game can be played, but they are not all equally good, whether
"good" means "fun," "educational," or whatever. There are
reasons why almost nobody plays medieval chess any more--modern
chess turned out to be a more interesting game. Similarly, I am
willing to argue that a group that does nothing actually
medieval beyond putting on costumes is playing a less
interesting game than Carolingia is. Their way of dealing with
the Current Middle ages *is* "wrong," pace Justin du Coeur, not
because it is evil, or against the bylaws, but because it is
less interesting and less fun than other ways. My arguments and
my conclusions may well turn out to be wrong, but not because
all ways of dealing with the Current Middle Ages (or anything
else) are equally good. 

Tolerance as a spur to courtesy is a fine thing, but tolerance
as a technique for assuming away interesting issues is not.

Yours for courtesy and controversy

David Friedman (Cariadoc)
College of Grey Gargoylse, MK

