> 
In response to Li Kunk Lo

You ask:

1) Are we (Carolingia) really a bunch of stuffy
authenticity cops?
2) Is there such variation between groups that I would
encounter such problems
throughout the laurel kingdoms?
3) Does anybody else have a similar problem?
4) What do you do when the local role models say, "You
really shouldn't do that, it's not period," and the crown
gives you scrolls for the same behavior?

The society is a large, decentralized, voluntary
organization, and there is a wide range of opinions as to
the nature of the game we are playing. My own view is that
one should not do things at events that are obviously out
of period (songs about knights in mail going through metal
detectors), that things that only someone with specialized
knowledge would recognize as out of period (most Childe
Ballads, stories that really happened in the seventeenth
century, etc.) are acceptable, but things that are really
period (from period sources, or composed in such a way that
they could be from period sources) are better. One ought
not to make the best the enemy of the good--if sticking to
strictly period material means never singing another song,
it is better to keep singing. Never introduce an
out-of-period piece with an apology about being out of
period, since the apology is much more blatantly out of
period than the piece.

Remember also that in authenticity, as in other things,
there are trade-offs to be made. A song sung in old French
is more authentic in language than a translation, but less
authentic in the effect on the audience, since the original
audience was listening to a song in a language they understood.
1)Carolingia is more authentic than the average group. There is
nothing particularly stuffy about trying to be authentic--it can
be fun, and (in my opinion) a more interesting kind of fun than
getting an easy laugh by making twentieth century remarks while
wearing twelfth century clothes.
2)There is considerable variation in groups. Most groups regard
as acceptable blatantly out of period and out of persona
behavior--to the throne and from the throne in court, as well as
elsewhere. I prefer Carolingia.
3) Anyone who has a clear idea of what the Society should be
like has such a problem, because ideas on that subject vary
enough so that, whatever your view, there will be some good
people who honestly disagree with it.
4) You decide for yourself what the Society should be like, how
we ought to behave, and try to act accordingly, while doing your
best not to be discourteous to those who disagree.

Hoping this has been of some help, I remain

Your servant in service to the Society

David Friedman (Cariadoc, O.T.)
 

