Date: Thu, 20 Apr 89 22:30:57 EDT
From: "S. Gwen Johnson" <sgj%ctj.uucp@BRL.MIL>
Subject: More Russian Chainmail
Message-ID:  <8904202228.aa02157@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

In response to questions, I will attempt to be both brief and helpful on the
subject of Russian chainmail.

Book:  The State Armoury in the Moscow Kremlin, pub 1969 (if I have deciphered
the Russian correctly), edited by Zinaida Prokhorovna Chelyubeeva, (with the
help of 4 other editors and translators).  This copy is a discard of the Univ.
Of Baltimore Lib.

The shirt of flat chainmail is called "baidana".  The other shirt is a shirt
and vest combination called a 'bakhterets".  To me it looks like two pieces,
but the text implies that it is all one garment.  A number of pieces of chainmail
are shown with a vest of armour over them.  The bakhterets looks like Japanese
armour a little, and the text claims it was proof against firearms. A   14th
century helmet is also pictured, it has the spire typical of  Tartar arms and is
a very handsome piece.  It has a full aventail of conventionally made
chainmail.  The face plate has no eyeholes nor mouth hole.  It is a plain oval
of metal punched with many holes.  A friend of mine characterized it as  a
"oilcan with hockey mask attached".  It  my eye it is quite a handsome piece.

As for general tips about Russian garb: load it with pearls.  The tsars had
vast collections of precious gems to sew on their clothes, saddles, holsters,
carriages, you name it, and the passion for pearls was shared by anyone who
could afford it.  By the way, up until the late nineteenth century, pearls were
considered the most vauable gems.  When the diamond cartel was formed it
established a monopoly that inflated prices to approximately twice what market
forces would bear.  They maintain the monopoly by manipulating the buying and
selling of gems.  If you want a period jewelry from anywhere, pearls are your
choice.  

And just in case you were wondering, I have found the source for the
doorknocker in the movie " Labyrinth".  It's an excellent copy of a 17th
century Russian artillery officer's breastplate.  Only instead of a doorknocker
the lion is holding a spy glass in his mouth. The things you find when you
weren't looking!

Yours in service,
