Date: 21 Apr 89 18:10:10 GMT
From: unmvax!ncar!tank!fac_ddf@gsbacd.uchicago.edu
Subject: Pearls, Diamonds, De Beers, Forks, My Address
Message-Id: <2842@tank.uchicago.edu>

are intended as sacrificial victims.

Awilda Halfdane writes:

" By the way, up until the late nineteenth century, pearls were
considered the most valuable gems.  When the diamond cartel was formed it
established a monopoly that inflated prices to approximately twice what market
forces would bear.  They maintain the monopoly by manipulating the buying and
selling of gems.  If you want a period jewelry from anywhere, pearls are your
choice."

I doubt that this is correct; judging by the number of pearls used in period
pieces, they were popular but less expensive than the most expensive
gemstones. CelliniUs comment on the subject (Treatises on Goldsmithing and
Sculpture, 16th century):

"But I have a thing or two to say in order not to scandalize a certain class
of men who call themselves jewellers, but may be better likened to hucksters
or linen-drapers, pawnbrokers, and grocers;... . So what I say is out of
respect to these dunderheads lest they should be shocked at my affirming that
the real stones are of four sorts only, and thus wag their arrogant tongues at
me & cry, 'How about the chrysoprase or ... and why the Devil wonUt you add
pearls, too, among the jewels, ainUt they fish bones?'"

A ruby, for instance, of five grains of wheat, & of as fine a fire as you
could wish, would be worth about 800 golden scudi, and an emerald of the same
.. 400, ...diamond ... 100, sapphire ... 10."

I have left out a good deal of CelliniUs badmouthing of the competition, but
it certainly sounds as though the ruby is the most expensive stone, next
emerald, then diamond, then sapphire, with pearls in, or perhaps below, the
class of semi-precious stones.

Checking further sources would be more work than I feel like going to at the
moment, but I am pretty sure that the increase in the popularity and price of
diamonds occurred long before the late 19th century. Casanova, for instance,
who is 18th century, frequently mentions them in a way that suggests they are
the most presigious gemstone. Modern sorts of diamond cutting, up to and
including the brilliant cut, develop, as I remember, starting in the late
sixteenth century, so I think the seventeenth century is when the diamond
becomes important.

So far as the diamond cartel is concerned, I am not sure how anyone could know
what the market price would be in its absence. The general question of just
what the De Beers cartel is and how it works is more complicated than
references to it usually suggest; from what I remember of an article on the
subject by (I think) Benjamin Klein at UCLA, De Beers does not control all
that large a fraction of production (perhaps a majority, but way under 100%).
What it does have a near monopoly on is marketing. This presents some obvious
problems, since if the price is being held way above market, producers should
want to produce more than De Beers is willing to sell, in which case you would
expect chiselling by the non-De Beers producers.  KleinUs explanation gets
into some interesting economics of information, and interprets De Beers not as
a cartel but as a natural monopoly on marketing.

I suppose that will be of interest to only a few of you, but I am an economist
by profession, and Awilda pushed one of my buttons.

Back to the subject of pearls. It is possible, although difficult, to get
"commercial grade" pearls, which are lower quality than what is normally sold.
They are relatively inexpensive (about twenty  dollars for a string of about 7
mm pearls, as I remember), real (although cultured), and probably closer to
what would be used in period than more expensive modern pearls. I got Patri
some a couple of years ago for a coronet he is going to finish real soon now.
I got them from a dealer at the Tucson gem and mineral show, which is
certainly the largest such in this country, possibly in the world. You might
be able to locate a source in New York, but I am not sure. They do permit you,
at a tolerable price, to use real pearls in your jewellery, and Awilda is
correct in saying that they were widely used in period.

On another subject, Donal Artur of the Silver Band asks about forks. Contrary
to popular SCA folklore, forks are used in period, including early period.
There is an early Byzantine fork in the Cleveland Museum of Art, and two
Anglo-Saxon fork and spoon sets in the British Museum. There is a pamphlet
from the Victoria and Albert that discusses the whole question of forks. I
think the earliest picture of people eating with them is something like
twelfth or thirteenth century. I believe early forks are not consistently two
tined, again contrary to SCA folklore.

What seems to be happening is that through most of period forks exist but are
not a standard eating implement. Think of them as equivalent to our fondue
forks--something occasionally used for special purposes. I believe they become
part of the standard table setting in England around the seventeenth century,
although I might be a little off. If it is important, I could check--all this
is from memory.

David Friedman  (Cariadoc)
