Subject: What about longships?
Message-ID: <890421225407.12.CONS.ELF@AIDA.CSD.UU.SE>

Greetings!

It would be interesting to know if there are any Viking longships in
the SCA or in the USA at large. I have a photo of a longship belonging
to the Kingdom of An Tir, but I hear that they have two ships both
built of fiberglass and powered by outboard motors - which is not quite
what I'm looking for.

There are a number of modern copies of historic ships that have been
built in Scandinavia. The Danish boy scouts have been particularly
active in this, and have several:
IMME AROS, copy of a 12th century merchant ship. This is a "knarr".
SEBBE ALS, copy of a small warship found at Skuldelev, Denmark. This is
  a long, narrow ship of a type that occurs on the Bayeux tapestry.
LENDHEIM SUNDS, another copy of the small warship but better built
  than Sebbe Als.
IMME SLEJPNER RODDING, a viking ship in style but not an exact copy
  of any existing period ship.
The Norwegians built a 2/3 scale copy of the Gokstad ship and sailed
it to the Isle of Man in around 1979. It seems the ship remains there,
and as far as I know there are no sailing copies in Norway now.

Swedish archaeologists built a copy of a Gotlandish viking-time merchant
  ship about five years ago, and sailed it through the USSR down to
  Constantinople. Just to prove how long it took and that it could be done.
There is also a full-size copy of a Viking ship in northern Sweden, all
  built with period tools (no electricity!). It has eight oars per side
  and is said to sail well, but I can't remember its name.
In Taby just north of Stockholm, there is also a viking ship copy. This
  one was built for a rich 19th century tycoon who used it for partying.
  It has five oars per side but is usually powered by an inboard motor.
  Looks very real though it's not quite authentic.

Does anyone on the net know of more longships, Viking or Norman?

Yours, William de Corbie
