Date: Fri, 21 Apr 89 22:58:02 EDT
From: "S. Gwen Johnson" <sgj%ctj.uucp@BRL.MIL>
Subject: authenticity police
Message-ID:  <8904212254.aa12182@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

The authenticity police tend to be more in old groups than in the newer.  I
think the reason for this is because in old groups people (old people) have had
years to research, sew, practice, and generally upgrade their SCA equipment.
Not to mention, the older they get, the bigger their income.  This was  a real
problem for me when I joined.

I was a high school student, I had a long way to go to catch up to even an
impoverished college student.  With no income, no transportation, and few
research facilities ( I lived in the boondocks and commuted to SCA meetings) it
was hard.  It was also very frustrating to get sniffed at "THIS is the Way It
Should Be Done".  It was very depressing.  Basically, if you were a woman, you
had to be doing Tudors to get any appreciation.  If you were a man, you had to
be almost knighted.  Well, yes, Tudors are quite spectacular, but for me who
didn't even know how to sew, Viking was a practical solution.

I've seen people like the fellow who spent five hundred dollars on a
superb set of reproduction Japanese gauntlets.   And the Lady who blackworked
two very full sleeves solidly, and the fellow who built a gypsy wagon from scratch
and hauled it in on a flatbed trailer.  Wonderful!  But I don't have five
hundred dollars for gauntlets, I don't have time for yards of blackwork, and I
haven't got  a flatbed trailer!  Limitations of these sorts seem to escape the
authenticity police.

Right now I'm at work on a Russian costume.  Russian isn't my persona, but I've
been getting interested in it.  I like to try new things.  Since I'm out in the
boondocks agains, I'm winging it.  It's going to be very pretty, but I don't
know what shape headdresses women of this early period wore.  Did they even
wear headresses in the early 11th century?  All the resources I have availible
are later period.  So I'm guessing that they did, and I'm guessing that the
shape would be a simple, basic one.  First time I strut my stuff I'm sure I'm
going to meet somebody who tells me, "But they didn't use pearls that early!"
Well, phooey!  Pearls existed then, so they could have used them, and maybe 
it wasn't the social norm, and maybe I'm considered wierd by my contemporaries
for wearing a funny hat, but I LIKE IT, AND I DID THE BEST I COULD.

I do this part time as a hobby.  I have plenty of other things, more important
things like job and family that take precedence over the SCA.  I will do as
much as I can and still enjoy the SCA.  Some people who are more gung ho
than me will get to be  a lot more famous, but I don't care.  The stars
wouldn't shine unless there were lots of us ordinary folks around to compare
them to.  Unfortunately, the Authenticity Police come across as "If you can't
do it perfectly, you shouldn't bother doing it."

Some things, like no soda cans at feasts are simple.  Most of it takes work.
And we get there.  And we get there with helpful questions like, "I'd didn't
know they used pearls that early.  What are your sources?"  This is a much
friendlier way to go about educating the ignorant.  It conveys information
without denigrating effort.  Please encourage people who are daring  to try new
things!  Beginnings are delicate things, and people are easily discouraged into
abandoning projects.  We'd have a lot more Laurels if we passed out compliments
instead of criticism.

Yours in Service,
Awilda Halfdane
