A while back, David le Casse' asked:
    Date: 10 Apr 89 15:58:26 GMT
    From: david@davids.UUCP  (David Herron)
    Subject: Plays
    I'm curious if anybody else on the Rialto is involved in putting on plays
    -- especially plays from period....

and I waited from someone else from Carolingia to answer, but no one did.
Well, here in Carolingia, we have The Baron's Own Troupe of Mummers, an
elaborate renaming of the former simply Mummers' Guild perpetrated several
years ago on the grounds (I believe) that any stationary band of players
would have been taken into the service/protection of the local noble if
possible to enhance the prestige of his court.  Or something like that.
    Anyway, I am not a member of the Troupe, so I comment as an outsider.
This is a loose guild, which increases in activity when a play is being
worked on, but seems fairly quiescent between productions.  The members are
anyone who acts in or otherwise helps with the plays, though some of them
seem to be a steady core while others vary in their attention to this
activity.  The Barony usually end up with a few plays a year, at various
events and of various lengths as autocrats request and directors wish.  We
have also had 3 or 4 events where (watching) the play was the main activity
-- usually with Shakespeare plays or something of similar length and
complexity.  I'm not sure what the sources are; I think the present
Guildmistress, Lady Caryl de Trecesson, has done a moderate amount of
research into period sources.  She isn't online, so I give her snailmail
address:
	Carol Hanson
	138 Lebanon St.
	Malden, MA 02148

Good luck with this attempt to provide entertainment; I don't recall ever
-not- liking a play I've seen at an SCA event.

Eowyn Eilonwy of Alewife Brook

