Date: Thu, 20 Apr 89 09:49:15 EST
From: justin@inmet.inmet.com (Mark Waks)
Message-Id: <8904201449.AA27513@inmet.inmet.com>
Subject: Rolls, Rialto, and Reputations

Time to toss out a few comments:

First off, the Rolls Ethereal are (finally) done and in Danulf's hands. As soon
as he figures out how to get a 50+K file out to the list without killing
things, it will go out. My apologies for how late this is; I dramatically
underestimated the amount of time that it would take to do the data entry.
The new Rolls are almost twice the size of the last edition, so be ready for
it...

Second, it appears that the discussions here are having some real effects.
At both EK Coronation and the Carolingian Quest to Save Appledor this past
weekend, when scrolls were presented, they were greeted with a little hum
of approval, but a very conspicuous *lack* of "ooo, ahhh, ohhh" (instead,
there was a two-second pause, in which one could hear the entire Peanut
Gallery thinking, "oh, right, that's rude"). At least out East, people do
seem to be taking the thoughts of the Rialto to heart...

Lastly, I don't think that Carolingia's reputation is really all *that*
bad -- we seem to just suffer from a problem fairly common in the Society,
as it is in any group as large and unstructured as ours. There is a 
tendency for people to think that the way that they do things is the "right"
way to do them. The Society is a diverse enough organization to support a
*lot* of variety, and people just don't always realize that.

For example, one friend of mine moved here from the West some years ago,
determined to "show the Easterners how it's done". After living in
Carolingia for three years, he moved back West, and did *exactly* the
same thing in the other direction, deciding that the West had to educated
in the Carolingian Way of Doing Things, missing the point entirely.

There is *no* right or wrong way of dealing with the Current Middle Ages,
but there are different ways. People who think that Carolingia must be
stuffy because of its emphasis on authenticity (which isn't really all
that much stronger than in most places I've seen) and arts are being just
as silly as the occasional Carolingian I've encountered who thinks that
a group that doesn't do those arts is somehow incomplete. Both styles
are valid, and both are fun. Let's face it: an SCA group that isn't fun
isn't going to survive very long, since it won't get new members. 

Yes, there are people who don't understand this; there are probably some
people who will never understand this. Denigrating and/or converting the
heathen is some peoples' favorite pastime, and there are some people who
will never understand that "different" doesn't mean "worse". But there
aren't a heck of a lot of them; I've run into less than half-a-dozen people
who actually believed in Carolingia's reputation in my six years with the
Society. Frankly, that's fewer than the number of Carolingians I've hit who
deserved that reputation. In short, don't sweat it; there will always be
twits around, but, so long as the reputation they spread isn't really
justified, most people aren't going to listen to them.

					-- Justin du Coeur
					   Editor, Rolls Ethereal
					   Dancemaster Carolingia

