Subject: Comment on Period Music at Events

In SCA Digest #310, Eliane Esperance Sans Asile says: (paraphrased)
that hearing modern folk music at events saddens her and compares it to
someone attending an event in tie-die garb.

I would respectfully suggest that true period music is an acquired taste,
similar to that of say, true period food. You can taste/tolerate samples of
both on a periodic basis, but for full enjoyment, you'd prefer something
with which you are more familiar.

Folk/Filk songs are easier to enjoy because we understand the language and
can hum along. It comes to us from our childhood and from our radios. It is
what we know. Period music requires interest and dedication to be enjoyed.

As it happens, I was developing an interest in classical music just before
I joined the SCA. But it's only recently (5+ years later) that I've started
to actively seek out recordings of SCA-period medieval music. It's taken me
that long to develop my classical taste to the point where I enjoy period
music done on period instruments. (That's "enjoy" as in putting it on while
I cook dinner - seeking it out - as opposed to "enjoying" a presentation
at court - being vaguely interested.)

I'm sorry you find Folk/Filk music disrupts your enjoyment at events. It
seems to me that you are in the same situation as a Master Armourer who
sees hockey gloves, carpet armour and pickle-barrel plate on the field.

Perhaps it would help to remember that while the folk songs we sing are
perhaps not period, folk songs as a genre are. And while I also cringe
at the sound of a filk to, say "White Christmas", the concept of filking
is *very* period.

> Even when the live musicians were not up to snuff, someone once brought
> tape of medieval "dinner music" to play during the feast.  The
> atmosphere improved remarkably for all attending, especially for me.
Yes, please! (Actually, this isn't a bad idea for "educating the masses".
Play true period music while only their subconsious is listening...)

