M'lord, Kobayashi, I heartily sympathize.

I spent my first 4 years or so in the Society in the Barony of the
Cleftlands in the Midrealm, another old, large group with a strong core
of people, which has developed a strange reputation over the years.

After I moved away, I started hearing all of these stories about how
Cleftlanders were snobs and so on.  In a way this is at least partially
true, since members of the Barony are rightfully proud of what they've
built.  However, one of the other characteristics of the members of
the Barony that I have noticed is the willingness to talk with anyone
for as long as they're willing to hang around, and an intolerance for
people who aren't willing to consider alternate points of view or
the lessons of history (of which there are actually a few in the SCA).

Then, though, I started hearing tales about The Evil Baron and Baroness,
who were plotting the Destruction of The Society As We Know It (mainly
because they tend to be skeptical of Great New Ways To Solve All Our
Problems...), would like to see all heralds roasted slowly over a fire,
and so on.

The descriptions I heard bear no real resemblance to the people I know,
which puzzled me to no end.  Then I started hearing similar tales about
Carolingia (which I must admit made me think that it must be a fairly
nice place to be :-)), Northwoods, Bhakail, and other older groups, and
I started to sense a pattern.  It was when I started hearing similar
sorts of things about the Midrealm as a whole from people in younger
kingdoms (complaints about an invitational Crown Lists, for example),
that it occurred to me that the Society is new to an awful lot of
people, and that they tend to think of it as a lot more mutable than
it really is.  Soon we will be celebrating the Argent Anniversary.
Cleftlands will soon be celebrating its Twentieth (if I've got my dates
right :-)).  This is a lot of time, folks, and if some of us sometimes
come across as snobbish by getting irritated by Coke cans or SF filk
songs at events, it's not because we don't like them (often quite
the opposite, in fact), but because we have learned from experience
how much of a difference can be made by paying attention to these kinds
of little details.  Pouring Coke into a goblet is simple, and helps
preserve the atmosphere (note: avoid using marble goblets for this--I
tried it once and discovered that Coke has enough phosphoric acid in it
to etch soft stone...).  These "little" things are part of preserving
the atmosphere at an event, as much as wearing garb instead of a T-shirt
and jeans, even if the garb is just a T-tunic and belt.

Paying attention to this sort of thing also opens you up to any number
of little bits of medieval life that can themselves make even more of
a difference--things like salt cellars, oil lamps, and so on.

Everyone was new at one time, and everyone runs into people with more
of an authenticity fetish than they do themselves, but one thing to
remember is that, like most things, reputations have more than one side,
and the accuracy of the stories that tend to circulate about people and
groups often depends a lot on your point of view.


Amanda

