Date:  Wed, 19 Apr 89 14:52:43 EDT
From: akobayas@spica2.prime.com (Andrew Kobayashi)
Message-Id:  <8904191852.AA16607@spica2.prime.com>
Subject: Into the Breach! (Apologia pro Carolingia)

Sigh.  Here we go.  This is *very* long, but Lord Li Kung Lo has
touched a subject near and dear to my heart, and i cannot, nay
*must* not be silent.  The opportunity for stirring things up is
impossible for me to resist.

I am going to try to pre-empt some of the potential mail on this
subject, and will no doubt generate more (but different) mail as
a result.  Isn't progress wonderful?  I have cataloged the Carolingian
Myths that *i* know about, as a sort of framework for the Carolingia-
bashing that is no doubt about to happen.

MYTH #1: Carolingians are snobs.

Carolingians have this problem.  We are members of one of the oldest
active groups in the Known World.  We have had reputations of various
sorts longer than many groups have even *existed*.  And we are now
in what i believe to be a no-win situation.

The reputation of Carolingians (for the two or three of you out there
who haven't heard) is that of Authenticity Police.  That is, we
Disapprove of things that Aren't Period, and do so intrusively.
We disapprove of zippers.  We disapprove of Coke cans on
feast tables.  We disapprove of forks.  We disapprove of badly-
reconstructed dances, or folk songs at revels, or any of a large
number of things.  Above all, and the main source of complaint, is
that we don't approve of having fun.

Doesn't this sound unpleasant?  What sort of tight-lipped, piggy-
eyed curmudgeons we must all be.  How could such a group exist?
Why would anyone *join* such a group?  How could these people
continue, year after year, to attract new, talented individuals?
Why hasn't the group faded into obscurity?

Unfortunately, a reputation like this is almost impossible to get
rid of.  If even *one* person who identifies him/herself as
Carolingian offends *one* person from out-Barony, our sorry
reputation is secure for another year at least.  It doesn't matter
if ten or twenty Carolingians are nice to people, because no one
ever gossips about *nice* things that people do.

So what happens?  I go to an event, and see a Coke can on the table.
It annoys me.  I have two choices: 1) ignore it and be annoyed in
silence, or 2) say something about it.  Either way, i lose.  If i
don't say anything, the stupid Coke can sits there for the whole
feast, intruding on my very personal enjoyment of the feast.  If i
say something, another Carolingian Snob has reared up to quash
Someone Else's Fun.  No one *else* will say anything about the can,
lest they be branded a Carolingian Sympathizer, which fate is worse
than death.  And yet all i am doing is requesting that things be
made more medieval in a very do-able manner.

For those of you who think i am overstating our importance, i only
wish that it were so.  I have met people from many Kingdoms, and
the reaction is always, "Gee, but you don't *act* like a Carolingian."
I've given up worrying about it, because as far as i can tell, there
is nothing i can do.

Now having said all that, i must now backtrack and admit that, to
a large extent, the reputation has been deserved at various times
in the past.  Being a large and largely self-sufficient group, we
have grown insular and clique-ish (though a clique of 100 is something
of a contradiction in terms).  Many newcomers (and this includes
both new-to-SCA and new-to-Barony) have been put off by us in the
past.  This is regrettable both for the loss of a potential friend
and the additional damage it did to our reputation.

MYTH #2: Carolingians don't travel.

There is a basis for this myth as well.  Being a large group, we can
put on successful (read: non-money-losing) events that draw only on
the local population.  Furthermore, our potential supply of turk--
uh, autocrats is large enough that we could put on an event a month,
and have done so in the past, to the great annoyance of our neighbors.

Now, if you only wanted to go to one SCA event a month, and had a
choice between taking the bus or driving for four hours, which would
you choose?  Suppose you are a full-time university student (read
"poor")?

Now we add the reputation from Myth #1, and even if people do travel
they are reluctant to admit they are Carolingian!  Furthermore, if
someone is a transplant from, say, Myrkfaellin, or one of the other
"fun" groups, that person is thought of as a Myrky, not as a
Carolingian, even after man years.  And even when a dyed-in-the-wool
Carolingian such as myself travels, people just decide that i am not
"typical", since i am presentable in public places.  Sheesh!

MYTH #3: Carolingia serves bad feasts.

This is the only one that disturbs me, because i know it just isn't
true.  The only thing i can conclude is that someone happen to hit
one or two bad feasts (everyone makes mistakes), spread the word,
and everyone believed it because we were wierd anyway.  I would really
like to squash this one, because it reflects badly on a very talented
set of cooks here, and may, for all i know, be standing in the way
of awards for them.

So, CAROLINGIA COOKS YUMMY FEASTS!

This is already too long, and i'd like to hear what people have to
say.  Let me say again that i acknowlege past transgressions, and do
not mean to excuse them.  My main interest is in what, if anything,
i can do to have our reputation more accurately reflect our actuality.

Yours for the impossible task of changing one's own reputation, i am,

Kobayashi Yutaka, wearing my Seneschal of Carolingia hat.

