Date:     Wed, 19 Apr 89 20:37 EST
From: slarkin%UMASS.BITNET@mitvma.mit.edu
Subject:  Period Music at Events


Unto the folk of the Rialto, I send greeting.  In response to Lord
Li Kung Lo's missive, I'm afraid I have rather a lot to say.  I am a
mundane musician who spends a lot of time doing research on period
music, history, practice, paleography, etc ad nauseum.  I like the
stuff.  So does my persona, it's all she knows.  When I hear modern
folk music demanded and played, then rewarded at events it saddens me.
I know too many musicians who try VERY HARD to learn and perform
period stuff, and even write period songs, who go unrecognized.  As
a musician, part of the Dream for me is music.  Hearing filk played
at an event is as jarring as seeing someone attend an event in tie-die,
haveing obviously made no attempt to even look vaguely period.  What is
worse, at least for me, is that the people at the event where my lord
Li Kung Lo played seemed to prefer the modern stuff.  At the same event,
I offered to play recorder for the dancing, but the dancers prefered
the tape player, even though it only played one refrain.  (Yes, I can
play up to a dancers tempo)
I do not find Carolingia the least bit stuffy in regards to music.
What I found when I lived there was a group of people who shared my
love for period music, and who tried to learn and perform this at events.
Even when the live musicians were not up to snuff, someone once brought
tape of medieval "dinner music" to play during the feast.  The
atmosphere improved remarkably for all attending, especially for me.
It's not really a matter of being stuffy, it's a matter of just how
hard we are trying to recreate the Middle Ages.  We eat with knives
at events, we refuse to sew zippers into our clothes, we cook period
food, we use period manners (at least at court), why should music be
any different from any of these other arts?
I love Lord Li Kung Lo's songs, but i prefer to hear them in a more
modern context, say at post revels.  It is not hard to refrain from
modern tastes for a little while, trust me.

				Yours in service to the Dream,
				and to the memory of Josquin Des Prez,

				Eliane Esperance Sans Asile

