Subject: Russian chainmail
Message-ID:  <8904181008.aa08341@SMOKE.BRL.MIL>

A friend of mine recently bought a book called "The State Armoury in the
Moscow Kremlin".  It has photographs and text of many historical artefacts in
the Armoury, a building that formerly housed the steel workshops of the Tsars.
It now contains the treasures of all the workshops, gold and silver, textiles,
carriages, horse rfurniture, you name it, whatever was necessary for the
magnificence of the Tsar and his family.  Most of the objects date from the
16-17th centuries, but pieces cover the range from 5-18th centuries.
Unfortunately for armourers, the book concentrates on religious objects,
textiles, and carriages.  It does have a few pictures of armour, including the
chainmail stylke with which we are all familiar, but including also photos of
two different pieces, the like of which I have never seen before.  Well, I am
not an armourer, so maybe what I have to describe is not news to those more
involved than myself, but I  thought the Rialto would like to know.

The two pieces date from the middle of the sixteenth century.  They are made
with flat rings that have a word  stamped on one side.  The ring look a little
like washers, and it is apparent to me that they were cast in molds.  This
seems like a very fast way to get rings to me.  

The second thing differnt about them is that they were knit in the round.  A
metal wire going around the throat is the starting point.  The armour is built
up in concentric circles gradually getting bigger until the circle thus made
reaches the armpit.  It is then divided into three tubes: one large for the
body, two amall for the arms.  Additional stitches are put in at the armpits to
get the necessary fullness, and these additions make a clearly raglan sleeves.
Interestingly enough, the first rounds were done with what in testile knitting
we call an "invisible" increase.  Therefore there is a seam running from the
underarm part way up, and then stopping.   The coat of mail is also slit in the
from, like a tunic.  Whatever closures were used to fasten it shut are now
lost, but the pieces are in superb condition otherwise.

I have not finished reading the text, so I have no more information than what I
could observe from the pictures, but if I learn anything additional, I shall be
happy to post it.

Yours in service to faster chainmail,
