Milord William,

I disagree with you (don't I always? :-) about the oath of fealty.  The oath is
not to the man, but to the Crown.  The man is only a man, doing the best he
can, even if that best isn't very good.  All of us are flawed, no one agrees
with us perfectly, there is consensus about very few matters. We all agree that
chilvalry is one of our ideals, yet witness the debate we had on the Rialto
about what constitutes chivalry on the battlefield.  The  Crown is the symbol
of a set of medeival virtues we ascribe to, but cannot agree on the defintion
of.  To wit, courage, integrity, loyalty, courtesy, chivalry, generosity,
skill, knowledge, and  hospitality.  

We specifically DO NOT include highly personal matters such as religion and sex
among the virtues of the Crown.  Sex is completely irrelevant to the Crown.  It
doesn't matter whether the king is gay or straight, virgin or promiscuous,
virile or impotent, we do not perpetuate dynasties, and family connections have
nothing to do with our choice of Sovereign.  I grant that this is very
unperiod, but I think all of us agree that we do not want any part of the
tyrany of kings.

Since sex is not among the duties of the Crown, sex is in no way relevant to
choosing the Sovereign, nor does the sovereign's sexual behaviour have any
relevancy to the SCA.  The mere fact that someone who is gay happens to be
serving as king does not means that by swearing fealty to him you are condoning
a sexual practice you disaprove of. You are swearing fealty to the Crown, and
the Crown has no sex.  In this way it is also possible to swear fealty to a
king who is a rhinohide, a drunk, a wife beater, drug user, a theif, or
anything else you disapprove of.  The Crown is none of these things. It is
impossible for a mere human being to besmirch the Crown, it is the shining
ideal of which we are all poor reflections.

The only reason I can see refusing fealty to the Crown is when the Sovereign
wearing has committed treason.  That is to say, when the Sovereign has acted to
deliberately damage the SCA.  I can think of only one king who has done that,
and that was Michael, know variously as the Abominable, or Black Michael.  His
goings on were sufficient to require recourse to a mundane court of law.

And now to close witha  quote from "The Burden of the Crown" by Baldwin of
Erebor,

"This cap of burnished metal is the symbol of a the land,
 Supporting all we cherish, the dreams for which we stand.
The weight you'll find is nothing when you hold it in your palm,
The burden of the Crown begins the day you put it on."

