Unto the fair folk of the Rialto Li Kung Lo sends greetings! My present
confusion comes not so much in the form of a problem as a conflict in local
practice. For a very long time I was a mundane singer/guitarist, and though I
do not try to make a living of it any more, I do still love to perform. I know
frighteningly little about period music, having written one song which has a
clear medieval theme, and collaborated on another. I also am learning some
modern Scottish/Irish ballads for fun.
        Certain individuals who are taken with my songs (which has included at
least four sets of royalty) have caused me to sing at feasts, and rewarded me
for my performances. This culminated at recent coronation where I was inducted
by the crown of the East into the Order of the Troubador, the EK award for
bardic arts. This is gratifying in its own odd way, of course. All of my other
awards are for service, and although I have labored long and hard on a variety
of tasks, particularly sewing/costuming, which did not come easily to me, the
OT is the only award I have ever received for doing something artsy.
        After my arm was twisted by a pelican who shall remain unamed into
playing my songs before the crown, I suggested that in Carolingia I would be
strongly criticized for performing them at a feast, because they really aren't
period. The crowned head in attendance, who shall also remain unamed replied,
"That's all right, I'm not stuffy."
        The obvious solution is to write some wonderful ballads with period
voice leading, melody, and ornamentation, but that may take some time. In the
mean time, I feel a proper sense of guilt when somebody begs me to play at an
event where I know someone's version of the dream will be intruded on by a
not-quite-period ballad. I usually try to invite them to hear me play at a
post-revel, where this presents no problem. 
        The more global questions for the folk of the Rialto concern variation
between groups:
1) Are we (Carolingia) really a bunch of stuffy authenticity cops?
2) Is there such variation between groups that I would encounter such problems
throughout the laurel kingdoms?
3) Does anybody else have a similar problem?
4) What do you do when the local role models say, "You really shouldn't do
that, it's not period," and the crown gives you scrolls for the same behavior?
  
My only answers to these questions at present seem to be- take the scroll and
run. Quick, change your name, and adopt a mute alternate persona.

                                        Yours in Trepidation,
