From: eecae!tank!fac_ddf%gsbacd.uchicago.edu@netnews.upenn.edu
Subject: Heraldry and alternate personas
Message-Id: <2757@tank.uchicago.edu>

personas. I am not a herald but my lady wife is, so I asked her.
The heralds will only register one device per mundane person. 
Secondary personas may have their own badges, however, just as one
persona may have more than one badge. She does not know about names.
The next question is why one would want multiple personas. My own 
view is that nobody I know, myself certainly included, does even one
persona adequately. In almost all of the cases I have observed,
people who say they have two personas in fact have none-just one
20th century person with two kinds of costumes. I offer as 
evidence that in almost all cases, friends of one persona 
assume they are (and are assumed to be) friends of the other,
conversations are started with one and finished with the other,
and both personas have similar personal styles, opinions, etc.

One argument for multiple personae is that it makes it possible to
have clothes, or armor, or do dances from two different times or
places. I have two responses. The first is that the constraint of
having to find out how the thing you want to do would have been
done by your persona is one of the things that can push you into
interesting research. The second is that if you really want to do
things your persona could not have done (period dancing, for 
example, if your persona is pre-fifteenth century), there is, I
think, a better and less artificial excuse. Within the Society, 
you know people from many different times and places (although 
I prefer to let my persona assume that they are simply from 
different places, time travel not being a medieval concept-at least
not backwards time travel). There is no reason you cannot try to
copy a style of dress, or dance, or cooking, or armor, from one of
your foreign friends. The body armor I wear (Char Aina) is a type
probably too late and almost certainly too far east for my persona.
I started wearing it when I was living in the Shire of Black 
Diamond, along with Sir Ishmael ibn Murad-a mongol-persian from 
somewhat later than Cariadoc (a westerner, a Berber from North
Africa). Ishmael had what looked like a very practical piece of 
body armor, so I copied it. Later, when I was living in Grey 
Gargoyles, several people copied my Char Aina. Explaining it as a
piece of foreign armor they decided to imitate seems much less 
forced than adopting late eastern Muslim alternate personae.

Sincerely

