> received his scroll as "Owain of Skraeling Althing", because those
> recommending him had not asked the herald about Owen's registered
> name.

Personally, I don't really see that this is a great problem, as long
as the name is close.  In your example: Owen & Owain are two common
spellings of the same Welsh name.  They are the same name.  If the
gentle lived in Skrealing Althing, then he IS Owen of Skrealing
Althing.  He is also Owen atte Thorn (good name, by the way!), and he
may also be described in many other ways.

Similarly, I am Arval Benicoeur, or Arval of Rusted Woodlands, or
Arvaldus Heraldus, or Arval Kingsherald, etc.  Such variation of
bynames is perfectly correct period usage.  The fact that the College
of Arms registers only a single form of your name has fostered the
fallacy that there is ONLY one correct form of your name.  That's
silly.  There may be only one FORMAL spelling of your name, but in
appropriate circumstances,other forms will be used.  If Lord Owen got
his award specifically for service to his shire, it seems quite
reasonable to use that byname to describe him, does it not?

