> In Message-Id: <12398@reed.UUCP>, Todd Ellner (todd@reed.uucp) writes:
> > ... Richard the Lionhearted and Philip [Augustus] of France _did_ have 
> > an active relationship.  ...it happened in the Period and is fairly 
> > well documented. 
> Well documented?!  I'd like to see ONE piece of reputable documentation
> for this statement.  It has been repeated so often it has taken on the
> force of fact, but I can't find a single of primary source for this
> story.

I first investigated "Christianity, Social Tolerance, and
Homosexuality: Gay People in Western Europe from the Beginning of the
Christian Era to the Fourteenth Century", by John Boswell, The
University of Chicago Press, (c) 1980, ISBN 0-226-06711-4 (paperback)
or ...10-6 (cloth).  He discusses Richard I on pages 231--232.  I find
certain of his arguments unconvincing because he seems to overstate
his case.  However, he knows a number of ancient languages; he is a
scholar of good repute (although biased in this case); he has good
references to other sources, primary and secondary; he gives the
original texts for many of his translations.

Boswell gives a quote from Roger of Hovedon in Latin and in English
(#1 below).  He points out that Richard twice repented of "that sin"
and resolved to lead a better life (#2).  He points out that Richard's
Queen, Berengaria, was extremely obscure, and that no mistresses of
Richard are known (#3).

=====

[1] Boswell quotes (below) from "Gesta regis Henrici Secundi Benedicti
abbatis", ed. William Stubbs (London, 1867), 2:7.  An almost identical
passage occurs in "The Annals of Roger of Hovedon", trans. Henry Riley
(London 1853), 2:63-64.

"Ricardus dux Aquitaniae, filius regis Angliae, moram fecit cum
Philipo rege Franciae, quem ipse in tantum honoravit per longum tempus
quod singulis diebus in una mensa as unum catinum manducabant, et in
noctibus non seperabat eos lectus.  Et dilexit eum rex Franciae quasi
animam suam; et in tantum se mutuo diligebant, quod proper vehementem
dilectionem quae inter illos erat, dominus rex Angliae nimio stupore
arreptus admirabatur quid hoc esset."

This is translated by Boswell as

"Richard, [then] duke of Aquitane, son of the king of England,
remained with Philip, the king of France, who so honored him for so
long that they are every day at the same table and from the same dish,
and at night their beds did not separate them.  And the king of France
loved him as his own soul; and they loved each other so much that the
king of England was absolutely astonished at the passionate love
between them and marveled at it."

I consulted a professor of Classical Latin here at the U of I about
this.  He said that, unless the meaning of "dilectionem / dilexit"
changed during the Middle Ages, it has the connotation of "esteem" or
"agape" (in Greek) rather than more carnal implications ("amare").
Further, Boswell translated "vehementem" as "passionate".  So I
suppose that Boswell used the most favorable translation for his
purposes.  The translation by Riley uses more sedate language, like
"esteem".  Further, Roger of Hovedon makes clear in a few lines that
Henry II became worried about Philip aiding Richard in rebellion (a
persistent problem with Henry's sons).

On the other hand, the king of France was hardly short of beds in his
own palace.  I doubt that even the closest of friends shared the same
bed, if more were available.  This action is even more
incomprehensible if they were merely allies in a military cause.

[2] Boswell would have done better to look more closely at Richard's
public penances.  On two occasions, Richard did public penance for
offenses which included sexual immorality.  However, he listed other
sins (wine, extravagance, etc.); Boswell notes "there is no indication
that he regarded it as any more serious than the types of high living
... for which all religious monarchs (and most writers) of the Middle
Ages occasionally did penance".

The second penance was in Eastertime of 1195, I think.  Hovedon (in
2:356--57) records that an unnamed hermit reproached Richard in
Sicily, saying "Be thou mindful of the destruction of Sodom, and
abstain from what is unlawful, ...."  Richard ignored him (although
the hermit found it prudent to withdraw elsewhere) until an illness
afflicted him.  Richard made a confession, "took back his wife, whom
for a long time he had not known, and putting away all illicit
intercourse, ..."  Hovedon doesn't actually say that Richard confessed
to "sodomy", but that's the clear implication.

[3] Boswell writes, "He was married but died without legitimate
offspring, and so few people knew about his wife [Berengaria] that she
had to sue the pope after his death to be recognized as his heir.  All
his biographers agreed that 'it was no marriage'."  I thought
Berengaria had to sue because of King John's greed in wanting to keep
her dowry.  Also, I've met previously-married men with children who
were nevertheless gay; it is a common fallacy that "gay" -> "can never
perform sexually with any woman".

However, note how atypical the situation was.  They were married N
years (8?).  She was the only Queen of England who never set foot in
England (granted, he wasn't in England much himself, but she could
have followed him there).  She was separated from him for most of
their marriage, even when it would have been convenient for them to
meet.  They had no children when one of the primary duties of a king
and queen was to beget children.  In Roger of Hovedon's long chronicle
(several hundred pages), she is mentioned at most 5 times; the
references total to less than half a page.  Has ANY Queen, of any
nation, of such duration, EVER come so near to complete obscurity?

Further, Richard had one rather obscure bastard (I didn't write down
the name -- I saw only one biography mention him).  He gave this
bastard a castle or two; said bastard was never of any public note
thereafter.  The name of this bastard's mother is totally unknown.
Consider how often royal mistresses occurred, and how often they were
well-known: Alice and Fair Rosamund for Henry II, "Salisbury" for
Edward III ...  In fact, the only reason we know that Richard ever had
a mistress is because of this by-blow.

=====

Boswell lists some of Richard's biographies: Kate Norgate, "Richard
the Lion Heart" (London, 1924); Philip Henderson, "Richard Coeur de
Lion" (London, 1958); and James Brundage, "Richard Lion Heart" (New
York, 1974).  "Norgate's biography remains the best, despite her
reticence on this subject."  Brundage considers Richard to be
homosexual; Henderson refers to "dark hints" about his sexual
proclivities.  (Or was it Norgate?  Drat!  I should have checked them
out from the library.)

My summary?  Nothing can be absolutely proven beyond *any* doubt at
this remove, unless someone finds a document reading
        "Sodomitus sum.  Philipo amo.
                [s] Ricardus, rex Angliae"
:-)

Consider that chroniclers had a tendency to suppress or invent things.
Unpopular kings had every vice in the book ascribed to them; for
popular kings, doings that might cause scandal were often hushed up.

I consider the strongest evidence to be Richard's second confession as
given in Hovedon, which comes THAT close to calling him a "sodomite".
Second in strength is the evidence (or, rather, lack of same) in re
Berengaria or mistresses.  I think that the preponderance of evidence
shows that Richard was homosexual.

As for Richard and Philip Augustus being lovers: there IS
documentation, of a sort.  To me, it seems that one source is too
slender to prove a case with, even if one doesn't question Richard's
homosexuality.  I think the appropriate verdict is the Scots' verdict,
"not proven" -- "not guilty, and don't do it again".

--

