Unto the Good Gentlefolk of the Rialto, greetings.  Pardon me for this
message, but I was slow in entering this discussion now old; I have
been composing this message for too long.

Suppose that a Knight has a man who he loves and who is willing to be
his Consort, willing to perform the Consort's public duties and to be
a help meet for the King's work.  But suppose this Knight fights for a
stranger to be his Queen, not even attempting to elevate his "beloved"
to royal dignity.  Whether you agree or not, I would call this man a
hypocrite, and no Knight.  I would deem that this man has denied his
Beloved; by giving the greatest possible honor to another, he has
failed him.


I would answer a missive of William de Corbie:

>All I was trying to say was that consorts of the same sex would make the
>throne a platform for gay liberation (if the King and consort were openly
>homosexual lovers).

Pardon me?  Does mere sitting as a couple "make the throne a platform
for gay liberation" (as opposed to speeches, etc.)?  Does the mere
showing that gay couples exist constitute such an act?  Most current
Kings are open bedmates of the Queen.  Do they not then use the throne
as a platform to promote heterosexuality?  Does this not "make the
throne a platform"?

>Swearing fealty in such a reign would signify an open acceptance of
>homosexual activities and relationships.

Excuse me?  I disapprove of drunkenness and smoking, for I think them
most damaging and foolish.  There are many drinkers and smokers who
are Barons and Kings.  Does my swearing fealty to a drunkard King mean
that I approve of alcoholism?  I think not!

Homage-and-fealty implies many things for a vassal (in period and in
the Knowne World): I have a right and a duty to give counsel; I am
obligated to obey lawful orders; I have the duty to assist the King to
protect his rights and carry out his duties; I have various rights due
me from the King.  By no means does fealty mean that "I completely
approve of the King and of everything he does"!  Not even "I approve
of the King in general".  Sometimes, fealty (in period and in the
Modern Middle Ages) must perforce be said through gritted teeth.  "I
mislike this man, but he is King in this time, and I have a duty to
help him, to protect the kingdom from the King if naught else."

>I think that all such personal matters should be kept off the thrones.

What?  But that is not at all the current practice.  In the Midrealm,
most Queens have been the wife or lover of the King.  My source is a
very long-time member, who could only think of 2 counterexamples
immediately.  (Michael the Abominable and Zarina I, and Talymar I and
"Valmi"?  More examples are most welcome.)  Indeed, many think that a
King not choosing his beloved may imply disrespect or dishonor upon
this beloved, unless there is an evident disability (pregnancy, say).
For it may be that the King thinks his beloved incompetent to uphold
the royal honor and duties.

Why is commendable for opposite-sex couples to proclaim and confirm
their quite *personal* relationships in this very *public* manner,
while same-sex couples dare not?  If the King wishes to bestow the
greatest title of honor on his beloved, why is it commendable if his
beloved is female, but not commendable if male?

>I expect gay people to respect my beliefs on this matter, as a matter
>of courtesy if nothing else.

My lord of Corbie, most certainly I respect your right to have such
beliefs as you choose, but I need not agree with you, or act in a
manner consistent with your beliefs.

But I cannot even understand the reasons for your positions.  I shall
reread them, and try harder.

