I am fairly certain, Mistress Cher, that the question originally posed
referred to the heraldic registration of alternate persona names, not
the membership registration.  The Registry has absolutely nothing to
do with the heralds' office.  The Registry will put ANYTHING on a
membership card, as long as you pays your money.  Heraldic
registration is a different beast altogether, and the two are not
connected in any way.

> There's also the Heralds and Scribes:  one of the purposes of having
> a primary name is to permit people preparing awards and their
> scrolls to have a uniform name to put them in!  

I think you are mis-stating a bit here: The purpose of registering a
name with the College of Arms is to prevent anyone else in the Society
using a similar name.  From the point of view of the College, this is
the only purpose.  In practice, the list of names in the Armorial does
serve as a sort of official list of standard spellings of names, but
that is not a design feature.  Furthermore, there is no particular
reason that the Crown shouldn't put an alternate persona name on a
scroll.  For example, Master El of the Two Knives has an alternate
persona Kay the Minstrel.  In this persona, he is a minstrel and a
herald.  SHould he receive awards for those activities, it would be
most courteous to give them to the alternate persona.  On the other
hand, I rather agree with you that using multiple names leads to lots
of confusion!


> By the way:  it was *years* before the College of Arms unbent enough to allow
> the registration of alternate personae _via_ badges, and there is a limit to
> how many of these you can register (I thinks it's eight, but I'm not sure).
> And, *that* was a begrudging compromise.

Each individual may register one alternate persona name and as many as
three badges.  These limits were set 4 or 5 years ago.

