   For a brief while we (BMDL, K of E) were trying out "Trollball" games.
This was based on the Trollball game described in one of the FRP games,
I believe Runequest.  Five people on the field per team (one was goalie),
two alternates.  Blunt weapons only, polearms considered blunt.  We had a
stuffed 'trollkin', which acted as the ball.  The trollkin was designed to fall
apart easily, with quick repair.  The object of the game was to get the 'live
part' of the trollkin across the goal line.  This meant that the trollkin was
considered 'dead' if you tore off more than one limb, or if the head came
off or the body fell in two.  Once anyone died (abdomen shots were
considered 'hideous wounds') they had to be 'carried' (escorted) to the
sideline where they were replaced and then revived.

   The one play where opposing players passed each other and each ended
up with half of the trollkin (top and bottom) caused several gentles to fall
down laughing, as did the pass where the body went in one direction and
the head in another.
   When the trollkin died, players could refresh the teams by clearing the
dead; this became an important factor.  The person carrying the trollkin
was not allowed to strike it - but it was permissable to parry with him...

   We tried a couple of games here, and one at Pennsic XV(?), but it sadly
didn't catch on.
   We did find that the lighter armored fighters (especially the ones wearing
running shoes) had to be evenly distributed between teams...

